WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.679 --> 00:00:22.519
Around the year 1200 AD, the medieval
Arab traveler and scholar Abd Al-Latif

00:00:22.519 --> 00:00:28.960
Al-Baghdadi departed from his hometown
of Baghdad and set out on a journey of

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:34.160
exploration.
As a young man, Al-Baghdadi had studied

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:39.360
law, medicine, and philosophy, and was
inspired by the works of classical

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:44.879
philosophers; in particular,
Aristotle. At the turn of the 13th

00:00:44.879 --> 00:00:50.199
century, Al-Baghdadi embarked on a series
of journeys that would take him to many

00:00:50.199 --> 00:00:56.440
of the great cities in the region. He
traveled to Mosul, to Jerusalem, Damascus,

00:00:56.440 --> 00:01:02.440
and Aleppo, and eventually, around the
year 124, his journey took him across

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:10.159
the Sinai Desert to the banks of the
Nile. On his travels, Al-Baghdadi wrote a

00:01:10.159 --> 00:01:15.479
book that was part travel account and
part philosophy, entitled The Book of

00:01:15.479 --> 00:01:21.520
Edification and Admonition. In it, he
recalls the remarkable impression that

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:24.439
Egypt made on him.

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:37.600
Egypt is a land of wondrous monuments
and strange stories. It consists of a

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:43.399
valley enclosed by two ranges of hills;
one to the east, and one to the west. The

00:01:43.399 --> 00:01:47.719
Nile runs between them until it reaches
Lower Egypt, where it divides into

00:01:47.719 --> 00:01:54.040
branches, all of which flow out into the
sea. The Nile is unusual for its length.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:58.840
We know of no other river in the
inhabited world that covers a greater

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:01.840
distance.

00:02:08.959 --> 00:02:14.560
As Al-Baghdadi traveled around Egypt, he
was struck by the incredible variety of

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:21.239
ancient remains he saw; great temples of
stone and tomb complexes crumbling

00:02:21.239 --> 00:02:26.959
beside the waters of the Nile. But none
of these compared to the most fabled of

00:02:26.959 --> 00:02:33.200
all Egypt's monuments, which rose over
the horizon not far from the city of

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:41.490
Memphis, at a place called

00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:50.239
Giza. The ancient monuments in Egypt are
such as I have never seen nor heard tell

00:02:50.239 --> 00:02:56.159
of in other lands. First among them are
the pyramids. They are very numerous. All

00:02:56.159 --> 00:03:00.200
are situated on the Giza side of the
Nile and extend in the direction of

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:06.120
Memphis, spread out along a distance of
about two days  journey. Some are big, others

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:12.319
small; some are of clay and mud brick, but
most are of stone. Some are stepped, but

00:03:12.319 --> 00:03:15.239
most of them taper

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:23.599
smoothly. Of all these pyramids, three
stood out for their seemingly impossible

00:03:26.519 --> 00:03:31.040
immensity. Turning to the pyramids that
everyone talks about, points at, and

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:35.879
characterizes in terms of their sheer
size, there are three laid out in a

00:03:35.879 --> 00:03:41.000
straight line at Giza. Two of them are
particularly enormous, and it is with

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.360
these two that the poets have been
infatuated. The spectacle is so awe-

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:52.080
inspiring that your sight will falter as
you try to take it all in.

00:03:54.159 --> 00:04:00.560
Al-Baghdadi wrote accounts of the
local people who lived close to these vast

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:06.239
remains. He describes some who climbed to
the tops of these structures, and others

00:04:06.239 --> 00:04:12.040
who quarried them for their fine-cut
stone. Others still became obsessed with

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:19.040
exploring the hidden tunnels and
chambers that branched out beneath the

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:23.880
pyramids. In one of the great pyramids,
there is an opening that allows people

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:29.840
to gain entry. It leads them into narrow
corridors, labyrinthine passageways, well

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:34.680
shafts, pitfalls, and other such features, as
appear in the accounts of those who

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:40.160
venture inside and explore the innermost
parts. Many people, obsessed by the

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:45.240
pyramid and filled with fanciful ideas
about it, are inspired to penetrate its

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:50.680
depths, but they always end up at some
place beyond which they cannot go. They

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:55.120
spoke of how the pyramid was full of
bats, and how these bats grow to the size

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:58.440
of
pigeons. There are inscriptions on the

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:03.800
stones, written in the ancient characters
that no one understands. In the entire

00:05:03.800 --> 00:05:09.160
land of Egypt, I have never found a
single person who so much has claimed to

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:13.039
have heard of anyone who knew how to
read them.

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:20.400
He even seems to have visited the
Sphinx nearby, which was then buried up

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:25.000
to its neck in the sands.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.759
Also, by the three pyramids, at a
distance from them of rather more than a

00:05:29.759 --> 00:05:36.160
bow-shot, the likeness of a most enormous
head and neck protrudes from the ground.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:41.759
The people call it  old father dread , and
assert that its body is buried in the

00:05:41.759 --> 00:05:47.120
ground. The face is handsomely, indeed
admirably portrayed, with a touch of

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:53.759
elegance and beauty about the features,
as if a smile were playing across

00:05:53.880 --> 00:06:00.080
them. Above all, Al-Baghdadi was impressed
by the mastery of engineering it must

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:05.000
have required to build such
constructions and to have them survive

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.690
for such a stretch of time.

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:16.199
The construction of the pyramids
was carried out according to a

00:06:16.199 --> 00:06:21.240
methodology remarkable in respect both
to design and to precision of

00:06:21.240 --> 00:06:26.680
execution. This is what has enabled the
pyramids to endure time's passing eras;

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:33.360
or rather, it is meant that time itself
has had to endure the era of the

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:39.319
pyramids. Noble intellects gave the
pyramids their all; pure minds exhausted

00:06:39.319 --> 00:06:44.319
their every effort for their sake;
enlightened souls outpoured their

00:06:44.319 --> 00:06:50.000
loftiest capabilities on their design, to
stand as exemplars that are the pinnacle

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:55.720
of the possible. Because of this, they all
but speak aloud of their builders,

00:06:55.720 --> 00:07:00.720
telling us what sort of folk they were,
giving voice to their intellects,

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:05.240
relating the stories of their lives and

00:07:08.759 --> 00:07:15.639
times. When Al-Baghdadi visited Giza
around the year 1200, the Great Pyramid

00:07:15.639 --> 00:07:21.120
was the tallest man-made structure in
the world, and had been for more than

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:26.599
3,700 years.
All that time, it had testified to

00:07:26.599 --> 00:07:31.639
the greatness of a civilization that
had grown up on the banks of the Nile,

00:07:31.639 --> 00:07:36.400
a civilization that had passed through
countless periods of flourishing and

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:43.199
decay, and then finally disappeared
beneath the sands of the

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:01.440
desert.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:20.960
My name's Paul Cooper, and you're
listening to the Fall of Civilizations

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:25.680
Podcast. Each episode, I look at a
civilization of the past that rose to

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:30.840
glory and then collapsed into the ashes
of history. I want to ask, what did they

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:35.719
have in common? What led to their fall,
and what did it feel like to be a person

00:08:35.719 --> 00:08:41.959
alive at the time who witnessed the end
of their world? In this episode, I want to

00:08:41.959 --> 00:08:47.800
tell the story of one of the most iconic
cultures ever produced by humankind; the

00:08:47.800 --> 00:08:53.959
civilizations of Egypt's Nile Valley. I
want to show how this series of related

00:08:53.959 --> 00:08:59.040
societies grew up in the floodplains of
their great river, and built some of the

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:03.920
most enduring and recognizable
structures in the world. I want to tell

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:09.320
the story of how they rose, how they
endured, and how they finally faded from

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:12.560
history altogether.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:27.519
The story of Egypt is one of
the greatest and longest epics in all of

00:09:27.519 --> 00:09:32.240
history. Many empires would consider
themselves lucky to last through the

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:38.920
reigns of thirty-one kings, but Ancient Egypt
would see the reign of thirty-one dynasties of

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:47.480
kings, lasting for more than three thousand
years. In the time since, historians have

00:09:47.480 --> 00:09:52.680
long struggled with this panoply of
rulers and eras, and have tried to

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:58.360
wrestle the history of Egypt into neat
categories. They typically split its

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:02.760
history into three sets of
dynasties, commonly known as the Old

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:09.040
Kingdom, the Middle Kingdom, and the New
Kingdom. Between these are a number of

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:15.320
intermediate periods when the central
power of its kings failed and the land

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:21.440
divided. Throughout this history, Egypt's
empire would ebb and flow, just like the

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:27.040
great river that gave it life. That river
was the greatest watercourse of the

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:32.680
entire Afro-Eurasian landmass,
the river Nile.

00:10:34.279 --> 00:10:41.040
The Nile finds its source in Lake
Victoria, the largest lake in

00:10:41.040 --> 00:10:48.079
Africa. It's a body of water about the
size of Georgia, or nearly the size of

00:10:48.079 --> 00:10:53.680
Ireland. The gigantic Lake Victoria
drains into the river known as the White

00:10:53.680 --> 00:11:00.399
Nile, which is joined by the so-called
Blue Nile further downstream at Khartoum, the

00:11:00.399 --> 00:11:04.920
capital of
Sudan. From there, it flows for a further

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:11.279
2,000 km across the Nubian and Egyptian
deserts to Cairo, where it branches out

00:11:11.279 --> 00:11:17.399
into a wide delta and empties into the
Mediterranean Sea.

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:23.959
Next to the Amazon River, the Nile is
either the longest or second-longest

00:11:23.959 --> 00:11:29.920
river on
Earth. It runs for 6,800 km,

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:35.200
or around a sixth of the way around the
Earth, and its drainage basin covers a

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:41.600
tenth of the entire landmass of
Africa. Egypt itself has an extremely

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:47.040
arid climate, and its inland territories
experience virtually no

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:52.360
rainfall. If geography had been only a
little different and Lake Victoria had

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:57.360
not begun to drain westwards, we can only
imagine how differently history might

00:11:57.360 --> 00:12:03.519
have gone. For at least the last
five thousand years, every blade of grass and

00:12:03.519 --> 00:12:09.079
every tree in the Nile Valley, every
animal and every person to ever live,

00:12:09.079 --> 00:12:15.959
every priest and every king, owes their
existence solely to this

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:30.199
river. Human presence in Egypt is among
the oldest in the world. After evolving

00:12:30.199 --> 00:12:35.440
in the region of East Africa, modern
humans migrated primarily along this

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:39.120
corridor, and from there spread to the
rest of the world.

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:46.800
The Nile is, in a sense, the highway
down which all of humanity has once

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:53.279
passed. As one of our first stops along
our great journey, Egypt is home to human

00:12:53.279 --> 00:12:59.639
remains of astonishing
antiquity. Stone tools worked by archaic

00:12:59.639 --> 00:13:05.560
humans have been discovered in Nile
deposits dating to as early as 600,000

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:12.199
years ago, and modern Homo sapiens
followed in the last 100,000 years or

00:13:12.199 --> 00:13:18.120
so. These migrations likely happened
during one of the many African humid

00:13:18.120 --> 00:13:22.399
periods that have occurred over the last
millions of years.

00:13:22.399 --> 00:13:28.120
These are times when shifts in the
planet's climate caused rains to fall on

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:32.760
the Sahara Desert.
During these periods, the desert bloomed

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:39.720
into a verdant grassland, home to animals
and people, and when the period ended, the

00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:44.519
grasses would die, the animals would
leave, and the sands would

00:13:44.519 --> 00:13:50.399
return. It's thought that this cycle has
occurred more than two hundred times since

00:13:50.399 --> 00:13:55.160
the desert first formed eight million years

00:13:58.040 --> 00:14:04.279
ago. The earliest peoples in this region
lived by hunting and fishing, and left

00:14:04.279 --> 00:14:08.040
behind stone tools and a multitude of
rock paintings.

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:14.360
From about the year 13,000 BC,
in one of the Sahara's driest periods in

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:20.000
history, the Sebilian culture began
gathering wild wheat and barley, and from

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:27.199
there developed their own domesticated
strains. From 9,000 BC, people began to

00:14:27.199 --> 00:14:32.399
weave thread from wool, and another humid
period began.

00:14:32.399 --> 00:14:40.199
One enigmatic stone circle at the
desert site of Nabta Playa dates to around

00:14:40.199 --> 00:14:46.560
7,500 BC, when the Sahara was a range of
rolling grasslands once

00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:51.959
more. This stone monument may have been
used to mark the movements of stars at

00:14:51.959 --> 00:14:56.399
different times of the year, so that
people could keep track of cycles like

00:14:56.399 --> 00:15:02.720
the harvest and the migration of animals
for hunting. Nabta Playa has been called

00:15:02.720 --> 00:15:08.720
Egypt's Stonehenge, but this doesn't
quite do it justice, since it was built

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:14.639
at least five thousand years before the first
stones of Stonehenge were ever

00:15:14.639 --> 00:15:21.480
laid. When the last Ice Age ended and the
Sahara once more dried up, any peoples

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:25.720
who had been living and herding in its
grasslands would have been driven out of

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:31.199
their ancestral home. They would have
wandered across the newly-formed desert

00:15:31.199 --> 00:15:36.959
until they reached the only stretch of
green in the midst of all that sand. That

00:15:36.959 --> 00:15:41.959
was the banks of the Nile, and here they
would make their home.

00:15:41.959 --> 00:15:46.920
These peoples would build a
collection of scattered settlements

00:15:46.920 --> 00:15:52.079
reaching up and down the river, but
slowly, as more and more people were

00:15:52.079 --> 00:15:57.360
driven to the riverbank to survive,
these began to coalesce into larger

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:02.600
towns, cities,
and finally, kingdoms.

00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:19.040
The Ancient Egyptians referred
to the whole region by the name  the two

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:25.399
lands , referring to the long Nile Valley
in the south and the delta that spread

00:16:25.399 --> 00:16:32.519
out in the north, close to the sea. These
were the two lands that today we call

00:16:32.519 --> 00:16:38.319
Upper and Lower Egypt.
Surprisingly, for a modern person

00:16:38.319 --> 00:16:43.360
who orients their maps facing north, the
Egyptians thought of their world in the

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:47.079
opposite direction.
As a consequence, their word

00:16:47.079 --> 00:16:54.000
for  east  was the same as their word for
left , and  west  the same as  right . In the

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:59.319
Egyptian mind, they were always facing
upstream, waiting for the annual floods

00:16:59.319 --> 00:17:02.920
to arrive.
If you find this confusing, as we

00:17:02.920 --> 00:17:08.520
continue, just remember that southern
Upper Egypt is the region upstream, and

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:14.919
northern Lower Egypt is
downstream. For many people at this time,

00:17:14.919 --> 00:17:19.720
the lands along the riverbank would
have constituted their entire

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:25.559
world. The Egyptians referred to the
river's floodplain as Kemet, or  the

00:17:25.559 --> 00:17:31.799
black land , due to the rich, dark soil
left behind by its life-giving

00:17:31.799 --> 00:17:37.440
floods. This land was the realm of the
noble god Horus, who had the head of a

00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:44.160
falcon, the god of life, protection, and
healing. If you walked just an hour in

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:50.120
either direction, you would soon reach
what they called Deshret, or  the red

00:17:50.120 --> 00:17:57.320
land . This was the inhospitable desert
stretching out on all sides; roasting hot,

00:17:57.320 --> 00:18:02.960
largely devoid of water and shade, and
inhospitable to most life.

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:10.679
These deserts were presided over by
the god Set, the god of chaos and

00:18:10.679 --> 00:18:18.640
violence. The Nile itself they knew
simply by the name Iteru, or  the river ,

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:23.320
since in their world there was no

00:18:27.760 --> 00:18:34.840
other. The Egyptian world began in Upper
Egypt far up the reaches of the Nile at

00:18:34.840 --> 00:18:41.320
a place now known as
Aswan. Here, a belt of hard granite

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:46.120
crosses the landscape and forces the
river waters into shallow whitewater

00:18:46.120 --> 00:18:51.760
rapids, running over boulders and through
rocky channels called

00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:57.720
cataracts. This word comes from the Greek
word  kataraktes , or  rushing

00:18:57.720 --> 00:19:04.120
down . Today, the waters of these cataracts
have been tamed by the construction of

00:19:04.120 --> 00:19:10.799
the Aswan Dam, but in ancient times, they
could be a rushing torrent. Each year,

00:19:10.799 --> 00:19:15.120
when the floodwaters passed through this
rocky stretch of the river, they made

00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:20.280
such a thundering sound that the Earth
itself could shake, and this led the

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:24.320
Ancient Egyptians to believe that the
waters were coming up from beneath the

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:30.440
Earth, bursting out of vast, subterranean
seas.

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:35.080
At Aswan, they built a temple on an
island in the middle of those rushing

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:43.440
waters, and here worshiped that primeval
force. The fast-flowing waters at Aswan

00:19:43.440 --> 00:19:49.280
made it a natural barrier to ships, and
prevented any further exploration upriver.

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:54.840
For this reason, for much of its
early history, this was where Ancient

00:19:54.840 --> 00:20:00.600
Egyptian influence ended, the final
extent of their power and border of

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:05.280
their empire.
Beyond Aswan was the southern

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:11.440
lands of Nubia, and for this reason,
Egyptians would also refer to it as  the

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:17.200
narrow gateway to the
south . The temple island in the Aswan

00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:23.480
cataracts was known to the Egyptians as
Abu, the Egyptian word for  elephant , since

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:28.679
it was a hub for the ivory trade with
these southern lands. The Greeks would

00:20:28.679 --> 00:20:35.320
follow this example, and named the place
Elephantine. From here, trade caravans

00:20:35.320 --> 00:20:42.280
would pass over land south to the Darfur
region of Sudan, bringing gold, ivory, and

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:48.480
other goods. But north of Aswan,
everything was considered to be Egypt, as

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:54.280
Herodotus records.
All the land watered by the Nile

00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:59.120
in its course was Egypt, and all who
lived lower down than the city

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:05.200
Elephantine and drank the river's water
were Egyptians. Such was the oracle given

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:10.360
to them.
Luckily for the Egyptians, the Nile

00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:15.440
flows from the south to the north, while
the prevailing winds blow in the other

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:20.039
direction, meaning that you could use the
winds to sail against the current as far

00:21:20.039 --> 00:21:26.039
as Aswan without too much effort. But the
return journey would be even easier,

00:21:26.039 --> 00:21:31.039
allowing the river waters to simply
carry you along. A ship heading

00:21:31.039 --> 00:21:37.400
downstream to the north from Aswan would
see for some time only rocky desert and

00:21:37.400 --> 00:21:41.120
the river bordered by cliffs of hard
Nubian sandstone.

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:46.400
This is not a land well-suited
to agriculture, but in ancient times,

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:53.000
these valleys were sources of natural
resources like gemstones, copper, and gold.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:57.919
Further north, the red cliffs fall away,
and the floodplain around the river

00:21:57.919 --> 00:22:01.880
gets wider.
Here, the landscape would have blushed

00:22:01.880 --> 00:22:07.559
green, and a larger population could be
supported. It was in this region that the

00:22:07.559 --> 00:22:12.840
desert city of Thebes would grow up,
which the Egyptians called

00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:18.840
Waset. This would one day become the most
powerful city in Upper Egypt, the capital

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:21.520
of the desert regions.

00:22:21.840 --> 00:22:27.520
The living part of an Egyptian
city, its houses and markets and

00:22:27.520 --> 00:22:32.600
workshops, tended to be built on the
eastern bank of the river, where the sun

00:22:32.600 --> 00:22:39.200
rises, while the western bank, where the
sun set, was used only for burials and

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:45.640
tombs. Sailing further north, you would
reach the area we call Middle Egypt, and

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:50.679
the floodplain gets wider
still. This region would have been full

00:22:50.679 --> 00:22:55.200
of wildlife and
vegetation. Some way to the west of the

00:22:55.200 --> 00:23:02.159
river, the waters divert and fill a large
oasis known as Faiyum, which sprouts like a

00:23:02.159 --> 00:23:08.799
broad leaf from the stem of the
Nile. In ancient times, this lake was home

00:23:08.799 --> 00:23:14.159
to large populations of Nile crocodile,
so that the settlement on the shore

00:23:14.159 --> 00:23:19.960
would be known by the Greeks as
Krokodeil polis, or  Crocodile

00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:25.919
City . Here, Egyptians apparently even
tamed crocodiles in their temples, as

00:23:25.919 --> 00:23:28.960
Herodotus recounts.

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:34.039
Now, for some of the Egyptians, the
crocodiles are sacred animals. Those who

00:23:34.039 --> 00:23:40.559
dwelt about Thebes and about the lake
of Moiris hold them to be most sacred, and

00:23:40.559 --> 00:23:45.120
each of these two peoples keep one
crocodile selected, which has been

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:51.320
trained to tameness, and they put hanging
ornaments of stone and of gold into the

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:57.000
ears of these, and anklets round the
front feet, and they give them food

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:03.480
appointed and victim of sacrifices, and
treat them as well as possible.

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:10.120
In other places, crocodiles were
hunted for food using ingenious but

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:12.720
risky methods.

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:19.720
A man puts the back of a pig
upon a hook as bait, and lets it go

00:24:19.720 --> 00:24:24.960
into the middle of the river, while he
himself upon the bank of the river has a

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:30.720
young live pig, which he beats; and the
crocodile, hearing its cries, makes for the

00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:36.480
direction of the sound, and when he is
drawn out to land, first of all, the

00:24:36.480 --> 00:24:42.640
hunter plasters up his eyes with muck; and
having done, so he very easily gets the

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:49.559
mastery of him. But if he does not do so,
he has much trouble.

00:24:54.480 --> 00:24:59.480
Also living in the river were
the animals that the Greeks would call

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:05.080
river horses , or hippopotamus,
our hippopotamus.

00:25:05.080 --> 00:25:10.880
The river horse is sacred
in districts of Papremis, but for the other

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:17.360
Egyptians it is not sacred, and this is
the appearance which he presents; he is

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:23.840
four-footed, cloven-hoofed like an ox, flat-
nosed, with a mane like a horse, and

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:29.039
showing teeth like tusks, with a tail and
voice like a horse,

00:25:29.039 --> 00:25:36.520
in size as large as the largest ox; and
his hide is so exceedingly thick that

00:25:36.520 --> 00:25:41.480
when it has been dried, shafts of
javelins are made of it.

00:25:41.480 --> 00:25:47.520
The most strategically important
location was what the Egyptians called

00:25:47.520 --> 00:25:52.399
the balance of the two
lands . This was the place where the river

00:25:52.399 --> 00:25:57.240
split into its delta.
As the crossroads between Upper

00:25:57.240 --> 00:26:01.679
and Lower Egypt, this was always the
natural place for the capital when the

00:26:01.679 --> 00:26:05.600
empire was united.
This location would give rise to

00:26:05.600 --> 00:26:11.240
the city of Memphis, and in turn, to
modern Cairo, and it is here that the

00:26:11.240 --> 00:26:16.520
Egyptians would build their most famous
and lasting monuments.

00:26:17.080 --> 00:26:23.240
Each year, the monsoon rains
falling in the highlands of Ethiopia and

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:29.159
Central Africa would swell the river, and
the annual flood would arrive.

00:26:29.159 --> 00:26:33.480
This happened with such regularity,
around the middle of August, that the

00:26:33.480 --> 00:26:38.919
Egyptians timed it using the rising of
the star Sirius.

00:26:38.919 --> 00:26:47.120
In the fifth century BC, Herodotus wrote
the following description of these floods.

00:26:47.120 --> 00:26:53.559
When the Nile is in flood, it
overflows in places as far as two days

00:26:53.559 --> 00:26:59.679
journey from either bank. The Nile comes
with a rising flood for a hundred days from

00:26:59.679 --> 00:27:05.880
the summer solstice, and when this tale of
days is complete, it sinks again with a

00:27:05.880 --> 00:27:12.120
diminishing stream, so that the river is
low for the whole winter, till the summer

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:17.679
solstice again.
The Egyptian year was divided into

00:27:17.679 --> 00:27:23.720
three seasons; the flood season of Akhet,
the growing season of Peret, and the

00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:28.480
harvest season of Shemu.
Once the flood waters receded in

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:34.919
early autumn, the land was refreshed and
fertilized with rich Nile mud, and new

00:27:34.919 --> 00:27:42.240
crops could be grown. In this black mud,
farmers grew emmer wheat, barley, beans, and

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:47.519
lentils throughout the cooler winter
season, and when summer came again, the

00:27:47.519 --> 00:27:52.799
grain was ready to be
harvested. Egyptian life was held in this

00:27:52.799 --> 00:27:57.320
delicate balance.
Each year, if the river flooded

00:27:57.320 --> 00:28:03.720
too little or too much, the results could
be devastating, as one Ancient Egyptian

00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:07.559
hymn to the Nile makes clear.

00:28:16.960 --> 00:28:24.679
If he is greedy, the whole land
suffers; great and small fall moaning;

00:28:24.679 --> 00:28:31.000
people are changed at his
coming. When he rises, then the land is in

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:37.919
joy, then every belly is glad, every jaw
has held laughter.

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:52.519
Since their lives depended so
greatly on these floods, the Egyptians

00:28:52.519 --> 00:28:58.840
developed ingenious systems for
measuring them. At the cataracts of Aswan,

00:28:58.840 --> 00:29:05.519
they built a series of devices known as
Nilometers. These often take the form of

00:29:05.519 --> 00:29:11.200
towers with deep wells inside that allow
the river to flow in, with measurements

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:17.880
inscribed on their walls in Egyptian
cubits. Each year, ancient people would

00:29:17.880 --> 00:29:24.399
anxiously check these Nilometers to see how
high the water was rising that year, and

00:29:24.399 --> 00:29:29.200
whether it would be a time of famine, a
time of plenty, or a time when they

00:29:29.200 --> 00:29:33.519
would need to hastily build some flood

00:29:35.159 --> 00:29:40.960
defenses. During the period known as the
pre-dynastic era, the two halves of Egypt

00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:46.960
were divided, and this division was
cultural as well as political. The desert

00:29:46.960 --> 00:29:52.600
people of southern Upper Egypt worshiped
their own god Nekhbet, who was commonly

00:29:52.600 --> 00:29:57.039
depicted as a griffon vulture, a powerful
and majestic

00:29:57.039 --> 00:30:02.679
bird. These people were likely darker-
skinned, and had more of a cultural and

00:30:02.679 --> 00:30:08.159
linguistic connection with the southern
lands of Nubia and Sub-Saharan Africa,

00:30:08.159 --> 00:30:11.679
their rulers sometimes even
intermarrying with the royalty of

00:30:11.679 --> 00:30:18.159
southern kingdoms. Meanwhile, the people
of northern Lower Egypt paid deference

00:30:18.159 --> 00:30:22.679
to the god Wadjet, usually shown as an
Egyptian cobra.

00:30:22.679 --> 00:30:28.240
They had more genetic influence
from North Africa and the Mediterranean,

00:30:28.240 --> 00:30:34.039
and may have been somewhat lighter-
skinned. The kings of southern Upper

00:30:34.039 --> 00:30:38.960
Egypt ruled while wearing a white,
bulbous crown, while the kings of the

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:44.799
north wore a red crown with a spiraling
representation of a cobra emanating from

00:30:44.799 --> 00:30:49.919
it. The kingdoms that ruled over these
regions were always fluid, but the

00:30:49.919 --> 00:30:55.840
geographical distinction between Upper
and Lower Egypt always held sway. But

00:30:55.840 --> 00:31:03.399
around the year 3000 BC, or more than
five thousand years ago, all that began to

00:31:03.399 --> 00:31:12.240
change. That was because of a king of a
kingdom called Thinis. His name was

00:31:20.559 --> 00:31:27.000
Narmer. The figure of Narmer is wreathed in
mystery, and what little we know about

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:33.159
him has been pieced together from fragments
of inscriptions and a few significant

00:31:33.159 --> 00:31:40.039
artifacts. Narmer was born under the
personal name Menes, but chose Narmer as his

00:31:40.039 --> 00:31:46.200
Horus name or king name when he came to
the throne of Thinis, and this name

00:31:46.200 --> 00:31:51.480
perhaps gives us some sense of his
personality. That's because  Narmer  means

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:57.000
something like  fighting
catfish . The Nile catfish that the king

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:02.120
clearly admired
is a remarkable species. It's a predatory

00:32:02.120 --> 00:32:08.519
fish, a nocturnal hunter that can grow up
to 1.2 meters long, or about the size of a

00:32:08.519 --> 00:32:15.240
dolphin, and uses a form of naturally-
generated electricity as a weapon. Using

00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:21.080
a unique organ in its body, it can
generate an electric shock of up to 350

00:32:21.080 --> 00:32:27.240
volts that stuns its prey. In the largest
catfish, this shock can be enough to stun

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:33.039
an adult human, and the Egyptians were
fascinated by this unique property. They

00:32:33.039 --> 00:32:38.120
depicted these shock-and-awe predators
on painted wall murals, and even

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:42.639
experimented with using the weak
electric charges of young specimens as a

00:32:42.639 --> 00:32:46.880
treatment for
arthritis. We might imagine that this

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:52.760
King Narmer wanted to emulate some of the
characteristics of these surprise hunters,

00:32:52.760 --> 00:32:57.279
but whether it was their patience lying
in wait for their enemies, the tenacity

00:32:57.279 --> 00:33:02.600
of their surprise attacks, or the shock and
awe with which they stunned their prey,

00:33:02.600 --> 00:33:07.399
we may never know. Virtually the only
source we have for this period is a

00:33:07.399 --> 00:33:14.799
carving known as the Narmer Palette, which
contains only a handful of cryptic

00:33:15.039 --> 00:33:21.200
clues. One side of this carved artifact
shows King Narmer standing over a defeated

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:27.039
enemy, gripping him by the hair in one
hand and raising a mace in the other.

00:33:27.039 --> 00:33:32.480
It's a clear sign of
domination. Here, Narmer is shown wearing

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:37.039
the white, bulbous crown of his native
Upper Egypt, suggesting that he

00:33:37.039 --> 00:33:42.639
bludgeoned his rivals there into
submission. On the other side, the carving

00:33:42.639 --> 00:33:47.880
shows the king leading an army, while
ranks of his defeated enemies lie before

00:33:47.880 --> 00:33:53.279
him. Below this, an image of a bull is
shown tearing down the walls of a

00:33:53.279 --> 00:33:59.360
fortress with its horns. On this side of
the carving, Narmer is wearing the Red Crown

00:33:59.360 --> 00:34:04.480
of Lower Egypt. From this, we might assume
that he set out on a campaign of

00:34:04.480 --> 00:34:11.119
conquest and successfully brought the
two lands of Egypt together. Two mythical

00:34:11.119 --> 00:34:16.560
animals carved on one side of the Narmer
Palette stand with their long necks

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:21.200
intertwined, perhaps representing the
coming together of the two sides of

00:34:21.200 --> 00:34:29.720
Egypt, their lives and their fates now
inextricably bound.

00:34:43.480 --> 00:34:48.359
This was a union that would see the
newly-united Egypt grow to become one of

00:34:48.359 --> 00:34:52.520
the most influential societies in early
human history.

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:57.839
At first, Egyptian culture was
heavily influenced by the slightly

00:34:57.839 --> 00:35:01.920
older civilizations of Mesopotamia, like
the Sumerians.

00:35:01.920 --> 00:35:07.480
Egyptian palaces were often
built to a Sumerian design, and they used

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:14.280
Sumerian motifs in their art, too. But by
at least the year 3000 BC, Egypt had

00:35:14.280 --> 00:35:20.320
matured its own indigenous artistic
culture and its own system of

00:35:20.320 --> 00:35:26.200
writing. The Greeks would later refer to
these by a word which means  sacred

00:35:26.200 --> 00:35:29.640
carving , or hieroglyph.

00:35:32.680 --> 00:35:38.040
The Egyptian hieroglyphs are
a mixed writing system that uses a

00:35:38.040 --> 00:35:43.320
variety of phonetic symbols, as well as a
collection of symbols that represent

00:35:43.320 --> 00:35:49.160
whole words. For example, an image of a
man holding up his hand to his mouth

00:35:49.160 --> 00:35:54.160
could be used to represent the common
word  eat , but other symbols that

00:35:54.160 --> 00:35:58.520
represented groups of consonants could
be used to spell out other less

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:04.640
common words, names, or
places. Hieroglyphs emerged a little

00:36:04.640 --> 00:36:09.359
after the invention of cuneiform in
Mesopotamia, and it's possible they were

00:36:09.359 --> 00:36:15.560
inspired by this older writing system. In
Mesopotamia, we can see the gradual

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:21.000
evolution of the cuneiform writing
system from its earliest symbolic roots,

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.760
but in Egypt, the earliest discovered
example of hieroglyphs show the symbols

00:36:25.760 --> 00:36:31.520
springing into existence already fully-
formed in a complex system. This suggests

00:36:31.520 --> 00:36:36.720
that they may have been developed all at
once as a conscious effort, and were

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:43.560
perhaps even devised by a single
person. The Egyptian hieroglyph for  ruler

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:47.800
was the shepherd's crook, since the king
was considered to be a kind of shepherd

00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:53.240
for his people. Egyptian kings would even
symbolize their royalty by holding a

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:58.359
gilded, curved crook modeled after those
used by shepherds,

00:36:58.359 --> 00:37:04.679
and these kings have come to be known as

00:37:04.720 --> 00:37:11.240
pharaohs. The word  pharaoh  derives from
the Egyptian word  per aa , meaning  great

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:16.400
house , and it has stuck in the popular
imagination as the name used for any

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:21.960
Egyptian ruler, partly due to its use in
the Bible. But there is actually no

00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:27.240
evidence that it was used to refer to
Egypt's rulers until nearly two thousand

00:37:27.240 --> 00:37:32.040
years after Narmer s
lifetime. Up until that time, throughout

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:37.000
the first eighteen dynasties of Egypt's
history, its rulers were simply referred

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:44.720
to as kings or  Neswet , and by epithets
such as  His Majesty . Still, the term

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:49.520
pharaoh  has gained such currency and
popular usage that it's still used to

00:37:49.520 --> 00:37:53.119
refer to all the rulers of Egypt across
the ages.

00:37:53.119 --> 00:37:58.480
The pharaoh in Ancient Egypt was
considered the living embodiment of the

00:37:58.480 --> 00:38:02.920
falcon god Horus and the son of the sun
god Ra.

00:38:02.920 --> 00:38:08.079
One later hymn praises the figure of
the king.

00:38:08.079 --> 00:38:14.040
Pharaoh is the lord of wisdom whose
mother knows not his name. Pharaoh's

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:20.800
glory is in the sky; his might is in the
horizon. Pharaoh is the bull of the sky

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:26.440
who shatters all at will, who lives on
the being of every god.

00:38:26.440 --> 00:38:31.520
Perhaps most famously of all, the
Egyptians were compelled by their

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:36.839
religious beliefs to embalm the bodies of
the dead, ritually cleansing them in

00:38:36.839 --> 00:38:41.720
preparation for the afterlife.
The Greek Herodotus, who

00:38:41.720 --> 00:38:46.960
traveled widely in Egypt, wrote about the
specialist embalmers who would prepare

00:38:46.960 --> 00:38:54.560
bodies in this way in exchange for a
fee. They, whenever a corpse is conveyed

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:59.760
to them, show to those who brought it
wooden models of corpses made like

00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:06.440
reality by painting, and demonstrate on
these the best of the ways of embalming;

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:12.440
the second which they show is less good
and also less expensive, and the third is

00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:18.160
the least expensive of all. Having told
them about this, they inquire in which

00:39:18.160 --> 00:39:22.720
way they desire the corpse of their
friend to be prepared.

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:27.920
With the price negotiated, the
embalmer could begin their work,

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:32.720
the grizzly process of which Herodotus
also describes.

00:39:32.720 --> 00:39:39.520
First, with the crooked iron
tool, they draw out the brain through the

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:45.839
nostrils, extracting it partly thus and
partly by pouring in drugs; and after

00:39:45.839 --> 00:39:51.440
this, with a sharp stone of Ethiopia, they
make a cut along the side and take out

00:39:51.440 --> 00:39:57.560
the whole contents of the belly, and when
they have cleared out the cavity and

00:39:57.560 --> 00:40:03.920
cleansed it with palm wine, they cleanse
it again with spices pounded up. Then

00:40:03.920 --> 00:40:11.000
they fill the belly with pure myrrh and
with cassia and other spices, and sew it

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:17.960
together again. Having done so, they keep
covered up in natron for seventy days, and

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:23.680
then they wash the corpse and roll its
whole body up in fine linen cut into

00:40:23.680 --> 00:40:29.920
bands, smearing those beneath with gum,
which the Egyptians use generally

00:40:29.920 --> 00:40:36.720
instead of glue.
Mummification was expensive, and only

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:43.000
those with wealth could afford it; rich
merchants, royal officials, and of course,

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:46.680
the pharaoh himself.

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:52.560
One inscription on the walls of
a tomb for the pharaoh Unus gives a

00:40:52.560 --> 00:40:57.000
sense of the kinds of prayers and
blessings that might have been spoken

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:05.800
while these rituals took place; this one to the
sun god Amun-Ra and the moon god Thoth.

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:22.480
Sun and Thoth, take Unus with you, that
he may eat of what you eat of, that he

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:28.440
may drink of what you drink of, that he
may sit where you sit,

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:35.240
that he may sail in what you sail in.
The booth of Unus is plaited of

00:41:35.240 --> 00:41:43.160
reeds; the flood of Unus is in the Marsh
of Offerings; his feast is among you, gods;

00:41:43.160 --> 00:41:49.960
the water of Unus is wine, like the sun.
Unus will circumnavigate the sky like

00:41:49.960 --> 00:41:55.119
the sun; Unus shall course the sky.

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:12.440
Upon coming to the throne of the
newly-united Egypt, King Narmer built a new

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:18.880
capital, perfectly placed at the balance
of the two lands, where the river met the

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:25.400
delta. This city would become known as
Inebu-hedj, or  the city of white walls ,

00:42:25.400 --> 00:42:32.040
but today we know it as Memphis.
The kings who followed Narmer

00:42:32.040 --> 00:42:36.520
would rule from this new capital, but
they spent much of their time traveling

00:42:36.520 --> 00:42:42.040
between palaces, and when they died, their
bodies were still taken back to Narmer s home

00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:47.359
region of Thinis in Upper Egypt to be
mummified and buried in the city's

00:42:47.359 --> 00:42:53.079
ancestral burial ground at
Abydos. That was until the reign of a

00:42:53.079 --> 00:42:58.400
king named Hotep-sekh-emwy.
He ruled from about

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:05.079
2,900 BC, and started what has been
called the second dynasty of Egypt, and

00:43:05.079 --> 00:43:09.760
he took the decision to start a new
burial ground near Memphis so that

00:43:09.760 --> 00:43:13.559
Egypt's pharaohs could be buried close
to their new capital.

00:43:13.559 --> 00:43:18.760
For the site of this new burial
ground, he chose a place on the western

00:43:18.760 --> 00:43:29.119
bank of the river, the side where the sun
sets, at a vast, open place called Saqqara.

00:43:34.559 --> 00:43:40.640
Saqqara is situated on a raised plateau
that the floodwaters of the Nile do not

00:43:40.640 --> 00:43:45.319
reach. Visually, it would have been
striking to ancient people, as the place

00:43:45.319 --> 00:43:50.880
where the green river lands end and the
dead sand of the desert abruptly

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:56.040
begins. For this reason, it may have been
considered a crossing place between

00:43:56.040 --> 00:44:00.680
death and life,
the perfect place for a necropolis, or a

00:44:00.680 --> 00:44:05.079
city of the dead.
For kings who wanted their tombs to

00:44:05.079 --> 00:44:10.160
be remembered, it also had the benefit of
being highly visible from the new

00:44:10.160 --> 00:44:15.559
capital of Memphis.
Over the coming centuries, this

00:44:15.559 --> 00:44:20.599
site would become full of tombs of kings
and queens, and countless royal

00:44:20.599 --> 00:44:24.640
attendants and nobles who followed them
into the afterlife.

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:30.720
At first, these tombs were
built in a form known as a mastaba, large,

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:36.079
rectangular constructions built of mud
brick and promising their inhabitants a

00:44:36.079 --> 00:44:41.559
rebirth into the next life.
These could be very large, but they

00:44:41.559 --> 00:44:46.440
were still relatively
unassuming. But soon, Egyptian pharaohs

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:49.920
would get even more ambitious with their
burial arrangements.

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:55.839
This ambition truly began
with the rule of a pharaoh named

00:44:55.839 --> 00:45:01.860
Netjerikhet Djoser.

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:15.160
The reign of Djoser begins the period
known as the Old Kingdom, which would

00:45:15.160 --> 00:45:22.280
last for the next five hundred years. Djoser was the
son of a king named Khasekhemwy, who had

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:29.160
reunited Egypt after a period of turmoil,
during which the northern delta rose in

00:45:29.160 --> 00:45:36.119
rebellion. With order now restored, Djoser
clearly wanted to keep it that way.

00:45:36.119 --> 00:45:40.359
Rather than continuing to travel around
the country as pharaohs before him had

00:45:40.359 --> 00:45:46.040
done, he moved to a permanent capital at
Memphis, where he could keep a better eye

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:51.240
on the restive northern
riverlands. Over his nearly three decades

00:45:51.240 --> 00:45:55.920
of rule, he set about an ambitious
program of construction, rebuilding

00:45:55.920 --> 00:46:00.680
temples, and throwing up fortresses all
along the river, but it was in the manner

00:46:00.680 --> 00:46:04.200
of his burial that he would truly leave
his mark.

00:46:04.200 --> 00:46:09.920
When Djoser began the construction of
his final resting place, it looked a lot

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:15.240
like the mastaba tombs of the kings that
had come before, but his royal architect

00:46:15.240 --> 00:46:21.200
soon began dreaming of a more ambitious
structure. He was a visionary chancellor

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:27.400
and engineer who held numerous official
titles in the kingdom, including  head of

00:46:27.400 --> 00:46:33.640
the royal shipyard ,  royal seal bearer , and
overseer of all stone works .

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:38.079
His name was Imhotep.

00:46:42.040 --> 00:46:48.400
Imhotep s name means  the one who
comes in peace , and he was born in the

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:54.040
27th century BC, but beyond that, much of
what we know about him has been

00:46:54.040 --> 00:47:00.200
distorted by myth and legend. He was
something of a polymath; a priest, a

00:47:00.200 --> 00:47:06.359
statesman, a scribe, physician, and
architect, and even gained fame as a

00:47:06.359 --> 00:47:12.000
magician. He also has the distinction of
being perhaps the first non-royal person

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:18.000
to be recorded in any detail by
history. As the king's most trusted

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:23.960
architect, Imhotep was put in charge of
the construction of Djoser's tomb, but it

00:47:23.960 --> 00:47:28.040
would not be a regular mud brick mastaba
like his predecessors.

00:47:28.040 --> 00:47:33.599
In fact, Imhotep was
determined to build this tomb out of

00:47:33.599 --> 00:47:38.880
stone. This stone would need to be
quarried from the bedrock nearby, roughly

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:43.960
cut into blocks.
But as this stone mastaba rose

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:47.800
out of the desert, Imhotep seems to have
had an idea.

00:47:47.800 --> 00:47:52.400
With this stronger building
material, the structure could support

00:47:52.400 --> 00:47:57.839
more weight, and so, there was no real
reason to stop building.

00:47:57.839 --> 00:48:02.920
Once the first mastaba was
built, he experimented with placing

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:08.960
another smaller one on top of it, and
then another on top of that, creating a

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:15.160
stepped design like a wedding
cake. Originally, Imhotep planned to build

00:48:15.160 --> 00:48:20.520
this construction four tiers high, but
soon he became even more

00:48:20.520 --> 00:48:27.440
daring. By the time it was finished,
Djoser's tomb stood six layers high. It was

00:48:27.440 --> 00:48:33.119
perhaps the world's first large-scale
construction made from cut stone, and

00:48:33.119 --> 00:48:39.960
rising to a height of sixty-two meters, it was likely
also the tallest building on Earth.

00:48:39.960 --> 00:48:46.640
Finally, the stepped pyramid of
Djoser was complete, and when the king died,

00:48:46.640 --> 00:48:52.559
he was laid to rest in a granite chamber
beneath the great edifice, surrounded by

00:48:52.559 --> 00:48:57.040
a maze of tunnels.
Djoser s pyramid was a

00:48:57.040 --> 00:49:01.559
revolutionary step in Egyptian
architecture, and it would stand as a

00:49:01.559 --> 00:49:06.440
challenge to all the kings who would
follow him, a challenge that they would

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:09.160
find irresistible.

00:49:15.160 --> 00:49:20.240
The difficulties that
engineers like Imhotep faced in building

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:25.960
these pyramids were enormous, but their
achievement becomes even more impressive

00:49:25.960 --> 00:49:30.040
when you consider that these monuments
also had to be built fast.

00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:36.000
Today, Egypt is littered with the
remains of half-built

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:40.760
pyramids. These were abandoned halfway
through their construction, usually

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:44.119
because the pharaoh who commissioned
them had died early.

00:49:44.119 --> 00:49:49.559
Once a pharaoh was dead, it seemed
no one saw any point in continuing to

00:49:49.559 --> 00:49:55.559
build his tomb. After all, there was a new
pharaoh now, and construction on his

00:49:55.559 --> 00:50:01.160
pyramid would have to begin right
away. For this reason, pyramids usually

00:50:01.160 --> 00:50:05.000
had to be completed, at the very least,
within thirty years.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:10.480
Only the kings with the longest
and most stable reigns would ever live

00:50:10.480 --> 00:50:14.280
to see the final capstone placed.

00:50:15.160 --> 00:50:21.240
The next pharaoh after Djoser was
a man named Sekhemkhet, who may have

00:50:21.240 --> 00:50:25.240
been Djoser's brother, and he would join the
ranks of the unfinished.

00:50:25.240 --> 00:50:30.040
As soon soon as he came to
the throne, he began the construction of

00:50:30.040 --> 00:50:35.599
another stepped pyramid of immense
ambition, sure to dwarf his brother's

00:50:35.599 --> 00:50:41.760
achievement. But only the first layer of
the pyramid was built when Sekhemkhet died,

00:50:41.760 --> 00:50:46.760
just six or seven years into his reign, and
the pyramid was abandoned.

00:50:46.760 --> 00:50:53.280
Another king, Khaba, also died
after six years, before his stepped pyramid

00:50:53.280 --> 00:50:57.160
could be completed.
To build each pyramid, the

00:50:57.160 --> 00:51:02.599
Egyptians would require enormous amounts
of laborers, as many as 100,000 per

00:51:02.599 --> 00:51:08.640
pyramid, with about 10,000 laboring at
any one time. There's a widespread

00:51:08.640 --> 00:51:13.720
misconception that these monuments were
built by armies of slaves, but most

00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:19.040
historians now believe this not to be
true. Slavery was an aspect of Egyptian

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:24.040
society, as it was across the ancient
world, and slaves were mostly taken from

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:29.280
prisoners of war, and also from those who
fell into debt or committed serious

00:51:29.280 --> 00:51:34.359
crimes. But slaves were mostly used as
domestic servants, or if they were

00:51:34.359 --> 00:51:39.079
unlucky, toiled in extraction industries
like mining and

00:51:39.079 --> 00:51:42.880
quarrying. These were considered an
underclass, and would not have been

00:51:42.880 --> 00:51:47.319
trusted with the construction of such
important and sacred

00:51:47.319 --> 00:51:52.319
buildings. In fact, evidence shows that
the pyramid builders were a mixture of

00:51:52.319 --> 00:51:57.119
professional artisans and laboring
peasants who worked seasonally

00:51:57.119 --> 00:52:01.880
in exchange for rations.
The life of an Egyptian farmer

00:52:01.880 --> 00:52:06.280
was dictated by the coming and going of
the annual floods, and there were only a

00:52:06.280 --> 00:52:11.119
few times of year when they could be
meaningfully employed in the fields. For

00:52:11.119 --> 00:52:14.400
the rest of the time, they would have
leased out their services to

00:52:14.400 --> 00:52:19.480
construction projects, the digging of
canals and other public works,

00:52:19.480 --> 00:52:22.400
and construction of

00:52:25.520 --> 00:52:30.920
pyramids. While they labored for the king,
these workers drank beer three times a

00:52:30.920 --> 00:52:36.440
day, and ate meat
regularly. They toiled in three-month shifts,

00:52:36.440 --> 00:52:42.119
and were divided into teams of twenty men.
The discovery of their graffiti, hidden on

00:52:42.119 --> 00:52:47.160
the inward-facing sides of some stone
blocks in the pyramids, shows that they

00:52:47.160 --> 00:52:54.079
gave themselves playful and boisterous
team names, some of which have been

00:52:54.079 --> 00:53:00.559
recorded.  The Friends of Khufu .
The Vigorous Gang .  The Followers of the

00:53:00.559 --> 00:53:08.440
Powerful White Crown of Khufu .  Those Who
Know the Pharaoh .  The Drunkards of

00:53:08.440 --> 00:53:14.000
Menkaure . It seems their supervisors fostered
a sense of team pride and healthy

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:19.240
competition, perhaps giving honors and
extra beer rations for those who shifted

00:53:19.240 --> 00:53:23.000
the most blocks.
Doubtless the work was

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:27.280
backbreaking, but over the following
millennium, millions of Egyptians would

00:53:27.280 --> 00:53:31.760
take this deal.
Perhaps they also felt a sense of

00:53:31.760 --> 00:53:36.599
pride at the great constructions they
were taking part in, which if all went

00:53:36.599 --> 00:53:41.559
well, they would live to see
completed. These laborers were

00:53:41.559 --> 00:53:46.160
sufficiently respected that any who died
during the construction were buried in

00:53:46.160 --> 00:53:51.559
tombs within the royal complex, their
bodies forever a part of the monolith

00:53:51.559 --> 00:53:56.480
they had given their lives to build, an
honor that would never have been given

00:53:56.480 --> 00:54:00.079
to a slave.

00:54:00.079 --> 00:54:05.040
The vast administrative effort of
building these tombs over the next

00:54:05.040 --> 00:54:10.720
centuries required a fundamental
restructuring of Egyptian government. In

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:14.520
the past, most of the high positions of
state had been doled out to the

00:54:14.520 --> 00:54:20.480
pharaoh's family, but with such ambitious
projects to be completed, skilled people

00:54:20.480 --> 00:54:24.400
would be needed.
In the decades that followed,

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:29.520
individual functions of government such
as the Master of Scribes and Controller

00:54:29.520 --> 00:54:35.160
of Workshops were separated out, and
these roles were delegated to capable

00:54:35.160 --> 00:54:41.920
individuals who were promoted on
merit. The Egyptologist Toby Wilkinson

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:46.400
summarizes the transformation in the
following terms.

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:54.280
As Egypt embarked on pyramid-
building, the pyramids were building Egypt.

00:54:54.280 --> 00:55:01.119
This new caste of civil servants
took pride in their work. One Egyptian

00:55:01.119 --> 00:55:07.319
text of the fifth dynasty records the advice
that a vizier named Ptah-Hotep gave to his

00:55:07.319 --> 00:55:14.599
son about how to be a successful administrator.
Let not your heart be

00:55:14.599 --> 00:55:21.599
puffed up because of your knowledge. Be
not confident because you are a wise man.

00:55:21.599 --> 00:55:27.559
Take counsel with the ignorant as well
as the wise. Good speech is more

00:55:27.559 --> 00:55:33.839
hidden than the emerald, but it may be
found even among maidservants at the

00:55:33.839 --> 00:55:39.440
grindstone.
Still, the failures of the kings

00:55:39.440 --> 00:55:44.920
that followed Djoser must have left a
mark on the empire's morale. Their

00:55:44.920 --> 00:55:50.680
crumbling, half-finished pyramids stood
in the desert as an image of kingship

00:55:50.680 --> 00:55:57.240
that could also be fragile and
fleeting. With his stepped pyramid, Djoser

00:55:57.240 --> 00:56:02.440
had laid down a provocation that would
have to be answered. But it wasn't until

00:56:02.440 --> 00:56:09.400
the reign of a king named Sneferu that
someone would rise to the challenge.

00:56:20.400 --> 00:56:26.760
Sneferu's full name was
Hor-neb-Ma at-Snefru-waj;

00:56:26.760 --> 00:56:33.480
Horus, Lord of Ma at, has perfected me .
Ma at, in Egyptian religious belief, was

00:56:33.480 --> 00:56:39.480
the embodiment of justice and truth,
sometimes portrayed as a goddess wearing

00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:44.720
an ostrich feather on her head, who kept
the stars and the seasons in their

00:56:44.720 --> 00:56:51.880
regular patterns and maintained
peace. Opposed to her in their theology

00:56:51.880 --> 00:56:57.440
was the concept of
Isfet; chaos, darkness, and

00:56:57.440 --> 00:57:03.480
disorder. This was sometimes depicted as
a great coiling serpent.

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:09.680
For the most part, Sneferu s name
seems to have been appropriate. Under the

00:57:09.680 --> 00:57:15.839
protection of Ma at, he reigned for as
long as forty-eight years, a time of prosperity

00:57:15.839 --> 00:57:20.799
and stability. His accession to the
throne is remembered in the later

00:57:20.799 --> 00:57:27.000
Egyptian source, the Prisse Papyrus.
The majesty of the king of

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:33.520
Upper and Lower Egypt, Huni, came to the
landing place of death, and the majesty

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:39.400
of the king of Upper and Lower Egypt,
Sneferu, was raised up as a beneficent

00:57:39.400 --> 00:57:45.240
king in this entire land.
During his half-century on the

00:57:45.240 --> 00:57:50.799
throne, Sneferu would secure his place as
Egypt's most ardent and determined

00:57:50.799 --> 00:57:54.200
pyramid-builder.
With the failure of the last

00:57:54.200 --> 00:58:00.400
kings to build a stepped pyramid to
match Djoser s, Sneferu began to wonder if he

00:58:00.400 --> 00:58:05.400
could build something even better, a
pyramid that conformed to a perfect

00:58:05.400 --> 00:58:11.720
geometrical shape. He had a vision of a
pyramid with polished, smooth sides,

00:58:11.720 --> 00:58:16.920
unlike anything the world had seen
before. His first attempt to accomplish

00:58:16.920 --> 00:58:21.480
this would be at the pyramid of Meidum.

00:58:30.160 --> 00:58:35.920
There is some debate about whether the
Meidum pyramid was built by Sneferu or by his

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:41.480
predecessor Huni, but we can assume they
wouldn't compete for the honor, as it

00:58:41.480 --> 00:58:47.160
stands as one of the most impressive
failed pyramids in history.

00:58:47.160 --> 00:58:51.880
The Meidum pyramid was built in
several stages.

00:58:51.880 --> 00:58:56.640
First, it was a stepped pyramid of
similar design to Djoser s,

00:58:56.640 --> 00:59:01.520
and then this interior structure was
encased in a steep shell of white

00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:07.039
limestone, creating a high and narrow
point. The effect would have been

00:59:07.039 --> 00:59:12.720
beautiful. That is until one day, as the
pyramid neared completion, when the

00:59:12.720 --> 00:59:18.400
entire weight of the stone facing began
to collapse in all directions.

00:59:18.400 --> 00:59:22.599
We can only imagine the noise
and calamity that must have accompanied

00:59:22.599 --> 00:59:28.280
this; the workers leaping clear of the
wreckage, the overseers watching aghast as

00:59:28.280 --> 00:59:34.200
an avalanche of painstakingly cut stone
poured off the side of the pyramid. The

00:59:34.200 --> 00:59:40.480
moment this happened, Sneferu ordered the
construction to be halted. Workmen inside

00:59:40.480 --> 00:59:44.960
the interior chambers simply put down
their tools and left.

00:59:44.960 --> 00:59:51.319
Today, the burial chamber inside the
pyramid is still unfinished, with raw,

00:59:51.319 --> 00:59:57.520
uncarved walls and wooden supports still
in place, which were usually removed

00:59:57.520 --> 01:00:01.799
after construction.
Sneferu must have been

01:00:01.799 --> 01:00:08.000
devastated, but he wasn't
discouraged. Soon, he tried again with a

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:12.839
pyramid at the site of
Dahshur, just to the south of the royal

01:00:12.839 --> 01:00:15.880
necropolis of Saqqara.

01:00:18.480 --> 01:00:24.079
This pyramid was intended to be
tall, and its sides were even steeper

01:00:24.079 --> 01:00:30.359
than the first. His workmen began to
construct it with a sharp 53-degree slope to

01:00:30.359 --> 01:00:35.400
its sides, and this time, Sneferu must have
hoped that he would get the pyramid he

01:00:35.400 --> 01:00:42.039
dreamed of. But this would not turn out
to be the case. This second pyramid was

01:00:42.039 --> 01:00:45.480
built on ground that was only soft sand
and shale.

01:00:45.480 --> 01:00:51.440
As the pyramid took shape and its
weight climbed into the millions of tonnes,

01:00:51.440 --> 01:00:56.039
they found that the stone was sinking
into the earth and causing cracks to

01:00:56.039 --> 01:00:59.880
appear in the structure.
We can only imagine how it

01:00:59.880 --> 01:01:04.799
felt to be the architect who had to
bring this bad news to the king, the son

01:01:04.799 --> 01:01:12.119
of Ra, the living embodiment of the god
Horus. The workmen tried everything they

01:01:12.119 --> 01:01:17.680
could, from adding new supporting blocks
to the base to propping up subsiding

01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:24.280
sections with huge beams of cedar wood,
but it was hopeless. It became clear that

01:01:24.280 --> 01:01:29.000
if they continued the pyramid as planned,
it would likely collapse just as the

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:34.000
first one had.
The pharaoh Sneferu seems to have

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:39.640
listened to reason. He consented to allow
his workmen to hurriedly finish the

01:01:39.640 --> 01:01:47.319
pyramid with a reduced angle of only
43 degrees and a final height reduced by twenty-

01:01:47.319 --> 01:01:53.359
five meters. This means that today, the pyramid has
a peculiar snub-nosed appearance that has

01:01:53.359 --> 01:02:00.839
given it the name  the bent pyramid .
It s clear that Sneferu still wasn't

01:02:00.839 --> 01:02:06.319
satisfied. He now ordered the
construction of a final pyramid one kilometer

01:02:06.319 --> 01:02:11.520
to the north, combining everything his
craftsmen had learned from the first two.

01:02:11.520 --> 01:02:16.880
This one was now built with a 43-degree
incline from the beginning, more evenly

01:02:16.880 --> 01:02:23.920
distributing the weight on the earth, and
finally, Sneferu got the pyramid he

01:02:23.920 --> 01:02:29.119
desired. This was the first structure
that truly took the iconic shape of an

01:02:29.119 --> 01:02:34.480
Egyptian pyramid, and would be used as a
model for those that would be built in

01:02:34.480 --> 01:02:40.599
years to come.
It was 105 meters high, nearly twice the

01:02:40.599 --> 01:02:45.359
height of Djoser's pyramid and the
world's new tallest building,

01:02:45.359 --> 01:02:51.319
and its geometrical perfection
was undeniable.

01:02:51.400 --> 01:02:56.359
When Sneferu died, he was
buried in this pyramid according to

01:02:56.359 --> 01:03:02.920
his wishes, and his son took the throne.
He would be the greatest pyramid-builder

01:03:02.920 --> 01:03:07.559
of all. His name was Khufu.

01:03:14.760 --> 01:03:20.359
As a boy, Khufu must have seen his
father Sneferu obsessed with the

01:03:20.359 --> 01:03:25.119
construction of his three
pyramids. We can imagine the young prince

01:03:25.119 --> 01:03:29.319
listening in on his father's
conversations with his architects, the

01:03:29.319 --> 01:03:34.240
tension and anger as the first two
pyramids failed, and then the final

01:03:34.240 --> 01:03:40.279
triumph of the red pyramid. Perhaps
as a boy, he dreamed of one day building

01:03:40.279 --> 01:03:43.559
such a monument for himself.

01:03:49.160 --> 01:03:55.400
We know very little about Khufu
or what his reign was like, but it's

01:03:55.400 --> 01:04:02.720
clear that he was inspired by one thing;
size, and above all, the desire to build

01:04:02.720 --> 01:04:08.119
the largest pyramid that would ever
stand. Learning from his father's

01:04:08.119 --> 01:04:14.240
mistakes on the bent pyramid and likely
inheriting some of his architects, Khufu

01:04:14.240 --> 01:04:21.400
elected to build his tomb some fifteen
kilometers to the northwest of Saqqara, on a

01:04:21.400 --> 01:04:29.319
shelf of strong limestone just outside
Memphis, at a place called Giza.

01:04:29.799 --> 01:04:35.160
When construction began on the
Great Pyramid, there must have been some

01:04:35.160 --> 01:04:40.160
uncertainty about whether it would even
be possible. It was built using an

01:04:40.160 --> 01:04:47.599
estimated 2.3 million large, stone blocks,
weighing a total of six million tonnes, and

01:04:47.599 --> 01:04:53.200
when its first layer was completed, it
was the size of more than ten football

01:04:53.200 --> 01:04:59.240
pitches. Its builders used predominantly
local limestone quarried from nearby on

01:04:59.240 --> 01:05:04.680
the Giza Plateau to build the pyramid's
interior structure, and these were bound

01:05:04.680 --> 01:05:08.400
together with lime mortar packed with
straw and charcoal.

01:05:08.400 --> 01:05:13.559
Luckily, these organic remains
in the pyramid mortar can be carbon

01:05:13.559 --> 01:05:18.880
dated, allowing archaeologists to date
the pyramids with scientific certainty

01:05:18.880 --> 01:05:22.880
to this period.
But while rough stone would do

01:05:22.880 --> 01:05:27.720
for the main body, the king's burial
chamber at its heart was made of blocks

01:05:27.720 --> 01:05:33.119
of hard granite brought from Aswan, since
it needed to resist the crushing weight

01:05:33.119 --> 01:05:38.520
of millions of tonnes of stone above it.
The fine limestone blocks of its outer

01:05:38.520 --> 01:05:45.039
shell were quarried at a place called
Tura, on the other side of the river. The

01:05:45.039 --> 01:05:50.000
stone from these quarries was of
exceptional quality, a pale white in

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:54.880
color, almost like marble.
For this reason, it was highly

01:05:54.880 --> 01:06:02.319
prized for use on the interiors of
tombs, and the perfect casing for a

01:06:02.319 --> 01:06:08.559
pyramid. This limestone was cut out of
underground tunnels in these quarries and

01:06:08.559 --> 01:06:13.599
dragged down to the banks of the Nile,
where it was loaded onto barges to be

01:06:13.599 --> 01:06:17.119
carried downstream.
In order to ease the

01:06:17.119 --> 01:06:22.240
transportation of these stones, the
Egyptians dug a series of canals and

01:06:22.240 --> 01:06:27.520
artificial harbors that came right up to
the base of the pyramids, one of which

01:06:27.520 --> 01:06:35.039
was known as She-Khufu, or  the pool of
Khufu . One papyrus has been uncovered, the

01:06:35.039 --> 01:06:40.799
oldest ever found, that is the work
journal of an overseer named

01:06:40.799 --> 01:06:49.000
Merer. In it, he records the process of
this perhaps less than exhilarating task.

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:56.440
Day 25: Inspector Merer spends the
day hauling stones in Tura South;

01:06:56.440 --> 01:07:02.400
spends the night at Tura.
Day 26: Inspector Merer casts off

01:07:02.400 --> 01:07:06.960
from Tura loaded with stone; spends the
night at the pool of Khufu.

01:07:06.960 --> 01:07:13.799
Day 27: Sets sail loaded with stone;
spends the night at the pyramid.

01:07:13.799 --> 01:07:20.720
Day 28: casts off from the
pyramid in the morning; sails upriver to

01:07:20.720 --> 01:07:23.920
Tura South. Day 29: Inspector Merer

01:07:23.920 --> 01:07:30.079
spends the day hauling
stones in Tura South; spends the night at

01:07:30.079 --> 01:07:37.760
Tura. Day 30: Inspector Merer spends the
day hauling stones in Tura South; spends

01:07:37.760 --> 01:07:40.200
the night at Tura.

01:07:42.640 --> 01:07:49.160
Remarkably, the pyramid was
oriented perfectly to true north, with

01:07:49.160 --> 01:07:54.559
one of its faces at each point of the
compass, suggesting that the Egyptians

01:07:54.559 --> 01:07:59.039
must have used measurements of the
stars in order to align it, the only

01:07:59.039 --> 01:08:02.039
method by which they could have achieved
such accuracy.

01:08:02.039 --> 01:08:07.319
With the kingdom's now
exceptional organization, it's been

01:08:07.319 --> 01:08:13.680
estimated that it took only about twenty-
three years to build, with the final stones

01:08:13.680 --> 01:08:18.319
being placed around 2560 BC.

01:08:18.319 --> 01:08:26.880
Upon its completion, the Great Pyramid
of Giza would stand 147 meters high,

01:08:26.880 --> 01:08:30.600
or nearly forty stories.
It was the tallest man-made

01:08:30.600 --> 01:08:35.759
structure in the world, and would remain
so for nearly four thousand years.

01:08:35.759 --> 01:08:41.120
The building that eventually
surpassed it, the wooden spire of Lincoln

01:08:41.120 --> 01:08:47.239
Cathedral in England, completed in 1311,
would stand for little more than two

01:08:47.239 --> 01:08:54.640
centuries before it collapsed in a
storm. Today, Khufu has cemented his name

01:08:54.640 --> 01:08:59.759
into history with the construction of
these monuments, but other than his

01:08:59.759 --> 01:09:05.440
ambitious pyramid, little else is known
about him. The only representation of him

01:09:05.440 --> 01:09:12.920
ever found is a single statuette carved
from ivory, and ironically for a man so

01:09:12.920 --> 01:09:23.319
obsessed with grand scale, this statue is
only seven centimeters, or less than three

01:09:23.319 --> 01:09:30.880
inches, tall. When Khufu died around
2525 BC, his son Djedefre would take the

01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:36.000
throne. But his reign was short, and when
he died, another of Khufu s sons became

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:42.920
pharaoh. His name was Khafre.
The pharaoh Khafre would follow in

01:09:42.920 --> 01:09:49.400
his father's and grandfather's footsteps,
and build a grand pyramid of his own. He

01:09:49.400 --> 01:09:54.120
would place it right beside his father s,
but for some reason, he declined to build

01:09:54.120 --> 01:09:58.800
it any higher.
It could be that his builders, perhaps

01:09:58.800 --> 01:10:04.159
tiring of this mania for ever bigger and
better pyramids, simply told him that it

01:10:04.159 --> 01:10:09.880
wouldn't be possible to build any bigger.
It may be that Khafre worried that it

01:10:09.880 --> 01:10:15.800
would have appeared unseemly to one-up
his dead father quite so ostentatiously.

01:10:15.800 --> 01:10:21.560
Perhaps for this reason,
Khafre's pyramid would be a differential three-

01:10:21.560 --> 01:10:26.920
and-a-half meters shorter than his father's,
although he he was sure to place it on a

01:10:26.920 --> 01:10:33.840
slightly higher shelf of limestone,
meaning that from many angles, it appears

01:10:33.840 --> 01:10:40.000
taller. Coupled with slightly steeper,
angled sides, this meant Khafre was also

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:47.280
able to build his pyramid with perhaps
350,000 fewer stone blocks, a saving that

01:10:47.280 --> 01:10:52.679
his teams of laborers and stonemasons no
doubt appreciated.

01:10:52.679 --> 01:10:58.560
Today, the pyramid of Khafre
is the only pyramid at Giza to retain

01:10:58.560 --> 01:11:03.719
any of its original casing stones of
smooth, white Tura limestone, which still

01:11:03.719 --> 01:11:09.159
cling to the top-third of the structure,
perhaps since its steeper sides made it

01:11:09.159 --> 01:11:15.159
more difficult for stone thieves to
extract the very top of its masonry.

01:11:15.159 --> 01:11:19.760
This allows us to picture how
these monuments would have looked in

01:11:19.760 --> 01:11:25.320
their golden age, the smooth, white sides
that must have gleamed blindingly in the

01:11:25.320 --> 01:11:31.400
the desert sun, and at night shone in the
light of the moon.

01:11:31.400 --> 01:11:37.360
These pyramids were also likely
capped with a stone known as a

01:11:37.360 --> 01:11:43.320
pyramidion, usually carved of diorite or
granite, and carved with

01:11:43.320 --> 01:11:48.639
hieroglyphs. Some examples of these
pyramidions have been found with

01:11:48.639 --> 01:11:53.960
distinctive grooves that suggest that
they were encased in a decorative metal,

01:11:53.960 --> 01:11:59.280
either copper or shining electrum, an
alloy of gold and silver.

01:11:59.280 --> 01:12:04.679
Since the pyramidions for the Giza
pyramids have never been found, it's

01:12:04.679 --> 01:12:09.800
unknown whether their tops were encased
in metal, but if they were, it would have

01:12:09.800 --> 01:12:16.840
made them an even more impressive sight,
a gleaming pinnacle reaching up to the

01:12:16.840 --> 01:12:22.120
heavens. Within only a hundred years or so
of the construction of Djoser's first

01:12:22.120 --> 01:12:28.239
stepped pyramid, all of Egypt's largest
pyramids had already been built, all by

01:12:28.239 --> 01:12:33.400
only three generations of the same
family. But almost from the moment the

01:12:33.400 --> 01:12:39.000
final capstone was placed on Khafre's
massive monument, enthusiasm for enormous

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:42.600
pyramids began to wane.

01:12:44.280 --> 01:12:51.120
The pharaoh Menkaure, the son of Khafre
and grandson of Khufu, also built his

01:12:51.120 --> 01:12:57.560
pyramid at Giza around 2510 BC, but his
would be significantly smaller.

01:12:57.560 --> 01:13:02.719
It's not even a tenth the size of the
Great Pyramid, and only two-thirds

01:13:02.719 --> 01:13:09.080
the size of even Djoser's stepped
pyramid. One explanation for this was

01:13:09.080 --> 01:13:13.040
that Menkaure didn't expect to live long
enough to build such a grand

01:13:13.040 --> 01:13:18.239
construction as his
predecessors. Herodotus records one piece

01:13:18.239 --> 01:13:23.719
of tradition about the pharaoh Menkaure,
which recounts how an oracle told him

01:13:23.719 --> 01:13:28.440
that his reign would be short.
As a result, he determined to make the

01:13:28.440 --> 01:13:35.280
best of the time he had, and perhaps this
left him little time for pyramid-building.

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:42.239
The king deemed this unjust, and
sent back to the oracle a message of

01:13:42.239 --> 01:13:49.080
reproach, blaming the god; why must he die
so soon, whereas his father and his uncle

01:13:49.080 --> 01:13:54.480
had lived long? He caused many lamps to
be made, and would light these at

01:13:54.480 --> 01:14:01.080
nightfall and drink and make merry. By
day or night, he never ceased from reveling,

01:14:01.080 --> 01:14:06.239
roaming to the marsh country and the
groves and whenever he heard of the

01:14:06.239 --> 01:14:09.840
likeliest places of pleasure.

01:14:11.719 --> 01:14:16.239
Whether there's any truth to
this or not, it's clear Menkaure had

01:14:16.239 --> 01:14:21.679
different priorities to Khufu and Khafre,
and his more modest pyramid seems to

01:14:21.679 --> 01:14:26.199
have broken the spell of his family's
one-upmanship.

01:14:26.199 --> 01:14:31.239
For the next thousand years, pharaohs
would continue to build pyramid tombs,

01:14:31.239 --> 01:14:36.400
but they would be mostly at a much
reduced scale, and they would cut bigger

01:14:36.400 --> 01:14:40.880
and bigger corners in their
construction. Instead of a solid

01:14:40.880 --> 01:14:45.040
limestone structure, these later
monuments would often be a simple

01:14:45.040 --> 01:14:52.120
limestone shell encasing a core of mud
brick, or simply earth and sand. For this

01:14:52.120 --> 01:14:57.520
reason, little remains of these later
pyramids other than melancholy heaps

01:14:57.520 --> 01:15:02.760
alone in the desert.
Slowly, the practice would begin

01:15:02.760 --> 01:15:07.840
to die out altogether.
The reason Egyptians stopped

01:15:07.840 --> 01:15:12.400
building pyramids was partly due to
changes in religious attitudes towards

01:15:12.400 --> 01:15:17.360
burial, but it also seems to have stemmed
from concern over tomb-robbers.

01:15:17.360 --> 01:15:22.600
After all, a pyramid was
essentially an enormous sign announcing

01:15:22.600 --> 01:15:27.840
to the world that the richest man in
Egypt was buried there. From the earliest

01:15:27.840 --> 01:15:33.280
days, people were drawn to the tombs of
long-dead kings to attempt to steal

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:37.560
their treasures.
One tomb inscription of a

01:15:37.560 --> 01:15:42.800
royal architect named Ineni gives us a
clue about these changing priorities.

01:15:42.800 --> 01:15:48.320
He writes that he constructed his king s
tomb not in an ostentatious declaration

01:15:48.320 --> 01:15:53.239
of power, but in total secrecy.

01:15:53.280 --> 01:16:00.080
I supervised the excavation of
the cliff tomb of His Majesty alone, no

01:16:00.080 --> 01:16:04.480
one seeing, no one hearing.

01:16:05.040 --> 01:16:10.920
Even with these secret tombs,
grave-robbers were still a constant

01:16:10.920 --> 01:16:16.000
concern. One pharaoh of the later New
Kingdom would order an inspection of his

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:21.719
predecessors  tombs, and his inspectors
brought back troubling news.

01:16:21.719 --> 01:16:27.199
The tomb of the king; it was found
that the evildoers have damaged it

01:16:27.199 --> 01:16:31.400
by forcing an opening into the main
chamber of his tomb, through the passage

01:16:31.400 --> 01:16:35.480
wall of the sanctuary of Nebamen,
superintendent of the grain stores of

01:16:35.480 --> 01:16:40.600
the king. In the funerary place, the body of
the king had been removed, and the tomb

01:16:40.600 --> 01:16:46.360
of his royal spouse, the royal lady of
Nubshas, was empty. The robbers had laid

01:16:46.360 --> 01:16:51.480
violent hands on them.
It wasn't just the precious

01:16:51.480 --> 01:16:57.120
treasures inside that were
stolen. As the overseer Merer had found,

01:16:57.120 --> 01:17:01.280
cutting the limestone blocks from the
quarries of Tura was one of the most

01:17:01.280 --> 01:17:06.600
time-consuming parts of construction.
For this reason, pharaohs who felt more

01:17:06.600 --> 01:17:12.280
pressed for time sometimes despoiled
previous pyramids of their cut stone in

01:17:12.280 --> 01:17:18.280
order to speed along their own
monuments. One Middle Kingdom text known

01:17:18.280 --> 01:17:25.760
as the Instruction of Merikare advises
kings against this shameful practice.

01:17:25.760 --> 01:17:30.840
Do not despoil the monument of another,
but quarry stone in Tura.

01:17:30.840 --> 01:17:39.199
Do not build your tomb out of ruins,
using what has been made for what is to

01:17:39.199 --> 01:17:44.239
be made.
In place of constructing their own

01:17:44.239 --> 01:17:49.639
pyramids at Saqqara or Giza, the later
pharaohs would be buried at a place near

01:17:49.639 --> 01:17:54.520
Thebes that the Egyptians called  the
Great and Majestic Necropolis of the

01:17:54.520 --> 01:18:01.040
Millions of Years of the Pharaoh , or
sometimes  the Great Field , but today it

01:18:01.040 --> 01:18:07.400
is known as the Valley of the
Kings. Here, a natural rock formation

01:18:07.400 --> 01:18:14.239
known as el-qurn, or the horn, rises above a
series of dramatic red cliffs.

01:18:14.239 --> 01:18:19.199
When viewed from the entrance to
the tombs here, this pointed peak

01:18:19.199 --> 01:18:23.760
somewhat resembles a natural
pyramid. It's possible that this

01:18:23.760 --> 01:18:29.199
convenient landform may have relieved
some of the pressure on Egypt's pharaohs

01:18:29.199 --> 01:18:34.760
and allowed them an equally prestigious
place to be buried, while freeing up an

01:18:34.760 --> 01:18:39.000
untold amount of energy and manpower in
the kingdom.

01:18:39.000 --> 01:18:46.120
Egypt's manual laborers could
perhaps breathe a sigh of relief. Slowly,

01:18:46.120 --> 01:18:51.159
the age of the pyramids came to an end.

01:18:57.199 --> 01:19:02.199
Still, that was a long time in the future,
and throughout the fourth and fifth

01:19:02.199 --> 01:19:06.639
dynasties of Egypt, royal monument
construction continued

01:19:06.639 --> 01:19:13.840
confidently. But in the sixth dynasty,
around the 23rd century BC, construction

01:19:13.840 --> 01:19:19.000
began to decline.
Part of the reason for this was

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:24.400
an increasing decentralization of the
empire and a gradual weakening of the

01:19:24.400 --> 01:19:30.400
power of the king.
The final pharaoh of the Old

01:19:30.400 --> 01:19:36.080
Kingdom was named Pepi II.
He came to the throne at the age of

01:19:36.080 --> 01:19:43.199
six, and ruled for more than sixty years.
Pepi was an excitable and enthusiastic

01:19:43.199 --> 01:19:48.440
child, as we can see from one tomb
inscription by one of his officials

01:19:48.440 --> 01:19:54.080
named Harkhuf.
Harkhuf had a long and illustrious

01:19:54.080 --> 01:19:57.960
career. He served
as the mayor of one of Egypt's

01:19:57.960 --> 01:20:03.520
southern provinces in the region of the
Nile cataract of Aswan, the narrow gate

01:20:03.520 --> 01:20:07.320
to the south.
The highlight of his life was the

01:20:07.320 --> 01:20:12.280
four journeys of exploration he
undertook on behalf of his pharaoh,

01:20:12.280 --> 01:20:16.600
following the Nile down into the heart
of Central Africa into what the

01:20:16.600 --> 01:20:22.600
Egyptians called  the horizon lands . He
wrote a full account of one of these

01:20:22.600 --> 01:20:31.280
expeditions on the walls of his tomb.
I accomplished it in seven months.

01:20:31.280 --> 01:20:38.239
I brought back from there all sorts of
beautiful, exotic produce, and was praised

01:20:38.239 --> 01:20:46.600
for it very greatly. I came back with three
hundred donkeys laden with incense, ebony,

01:20:46.600 --> 01:20:52.159
precious oil, grain, leopard skins, and
elephant tusks.

01:20:52.159 --> 01:20:57.800
The boy pharaoh Pepi was so
delighted with Harkhuf's trip that he wrote a

01:20:57.800 --> 01:21:03.560
letter directly to him. The letter was
likely written on fragile papyrus and

01:21:03.560 --> 01:21:09.600
has not survived, but luckily, Harkhuf was so
proud of this sign of royal favor that

01:21:09.600 --> 01:21:14.520
he had the letter copied out word for
word on the wall of his tomb, his

01:21:14.520 --> 01:21:21.199
proudest moment etched into stone for
eternity. In it, we get a sense for the

01:21:21.199 --> 01:21:27.840
voice of this excitable young king.
You know how to do what your lord loves

01:21:27.840 --> 01:21:32.080
and favors. You wake and you sleep
planning to do what your lord loves, favors,

01:21:32.080 --> 01:21:40.159
and commands. Unique friend Harkhuf!
Pepi was especially excited by a

01:21:40.159 --> 01:21:45.120
small man that Harkhuf had come across in
East Africa and had brought back with

01:21:45.120 --> 01:21:50.600
him, perhaps either a man with dwarfism
or a member of the so-called pygmy

01:21:50.600 --> 01:21:55.400
tribes of Central Africa.

01:21:55.400 --> 01:21:58.920
You have further said in this message
that you have brought a dwarf of the

01:21:58.920 --> 01:22:03.239
god's dances from the land of the
horizon-dwellers. Come downstream to the

01:22:03.239 --> 01:22:07.880
residence at once. Hurry and bring with
you this dwarf that you have brought

01:22:07.880 --> 01:22:12.800
alive, prosperous, and healthy, for the
king. When he goes down with you into the

01:22:12.800 --> 01:22:18.159
boat, have excellent people around him on
deck lest he fall in the water. My Majesty

01:22:18.159 --> 01:22:23.320
wishes to see this particular dwarf
more than the produce of the lands.

01:22:23.320 --> 01:22:28.480
However, as a pharaoh, Pepi was
relatively ineffectual.

01:22:28.480 --> 01:22:34.120
During his childhood, his
mother and grand viziers seem to have done

01:22:34.120 --> 01:22:39.120
much of the ruling, and as an adult, he
continued a relatively hands-off

01:22:39.120 --> 01:22:44.199
approach to the kingdom.
For much of its history, Egypt

01:22:44.199 --> 01:22:48.920
had been governed by regional
administrators known as nomarchs, who

01:22:48.920 --> 01:22:53.440
were appointed by the pharaoh to rule
over their regions on his behalf.

01:22:53.440 --> 01:22:59.120
Pepi's long reign saw an
increasing amount of power passing to

01:22:59.120 --> 01:23:03.520
these regional governors.
Gradually, their positions

01:23:03.520 --> 01:23:08.920
became hereditary rather than appointed,
so that single families began to amass

01:23:08.920 --> 01:23:14.239
large amounts of power, and their tombs
became larger and more elaborate with

01:23:14.239 --> 01:23:19.040
every passing year.
These nomarchs were soon beginning to

01:23:19.040 --> 01:23:25.400
look a lot like feudal lords or even
petty kings, and even began fighting

01:23:25.400 --> 01:23:32.840
amongst themselves. Meanwhile, the once
boy king Pepi was now entering his seventies,

01:23:32.840 --> 01:23:37.120
frail and increasingly detached from the
business of ruling.

01:23:37.120 --> 01:23:42.280
This might not have been a death
blow for the kingdom, but it was around

01:23:42.280 --> 01:23:47.360
this time that a record drought
descended over Egypt and the entire

01:23:47.360 --> 01:23:53.440
Eastern Mediterranean, starting around
the year 2,200 BC.

01:23:53.440 --> 01:23:59.679
This climate shift we have
encountered before; it is known as the

01:23:59.679 --> 01:24:05.360
4.2 kiloyear event, and has been
implicated in the collapse of the

01:24:05.360 --> 01:24:10.040
Akkadian Empire in Mesopotamia, and
perhaps even the Indus Valley

01:24:10.040 --> 01:24:15.920
civilization in India and
Pakistan. In Egypt, the result of this

01:24:15.920 --> 01:24:21.639
event was a series of years in which the
Nile floods were much reduced, and

01:24:21.639 --> 01:24:26.960
agriculture came under immense pressure.
The drought was so severe and

01:24:26.960 --> 01:24:33.400
long-lasting that the verdant lake at
Faiyum that once stood sixty-five meters

01:24:33.400 --> 01:24:40.400
deep completely dried up over the next fifty
years, and crop yields would have

01:24:43.920 --> 01:24:49.159
plummeted. The long reign of a pharaoh
was usually good news for the

01:24:49.159 --> 01:24:55.119
kingdom. It tended to generate a period
of stability and often prosperity,

01:24:55.119 --> 01:24:59.480
but when a king's rule went on too long,
it had the tendency to create what we

01:24:59.480 --> 01:25:04.440
might call  the old king problem .
The long reign of the pharaoh

01:25:04.440 --> 01:25:09.679
Pepi, along with his multiple wives, meant
that he had countless children, many of

01:25:09.679 --> 01:25:15.760
them now old men themselves with
children and grandchildren of their own,

01:25:15.760 --> 01:25:21.560
and they were all impatient to see this
old king pass on so that they would get

01:25:21.560 --> 01:25:26.719
their chance to rule. When Pepi finally
died around 2175 BC,

01:25:26.719 --> 01:25:34.320
what followed was a succession
crisis of immense

01:25:35.360 --> 01:25:42.000
proportions. The chaos serpent of Isfet
now wound its way around all the lands

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:44.280
of Egypt.

01:25:58.400 --> 01:26:03.840
In the two decades that followed, the
kingdom would see no fewer than seventeen

01:26:03.840 --> 01:26:11.000
pharaohs come and go, some perhaps dying
of old age, and others no doubt killed by

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:15.000
their rivals.
The only one of these kings to

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:21.000
survive more than a year on the throne
was a man named Ibi, who even, somewhat

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:25.520
optimistically, tried his hand at
building a pyramid at the royal burial

01:26:25.520 --> 01:26:31.840
ground of Saqqara. But this monument was a
testament to the now much-reduced state

01:26:31.840 --> 01:26:36.000
of the empire.
Standing at little more than thirty

01:26:36.000 --> 01:26:42.040
meters high, it was smaller than the pyramids
of some of the earlier kings  wives. On top

01:26:42.040 --> 01:26:47.679
of that, it was lazily constructed around
a core of mud and limestone chips.

01:26:47.679 --> 01:26:54.000
King Ibi, the man who was to be
buried under this sad monument, ruled for

01:26:54.000 --> 01:27:00.920
only two years, one month, and a day,
and likely did not control all of Egypt.

01:27:00.920 --> 01:27:07.560
Now, local nomarch governors declared
independence and ruled their provinces

01:27:07.560 --> 01:27:13.199
alone. Their tombs around this time stop
referring to the reign of a pharaoh, and

01:27:13.199 --> 01:27:18.400
are full of boasts and elaborate titles
that they seem to have invented for

01:27:18.400 --> 01:27:25.440
themselves. One tomb inscription for a
powerful nomarch named Ankhtifi demonstrates

01:27:25.440 --> 01:27:30.159
how the centralized power of the king
was declining.

01:27:32.199 --> 01:27:37.520
I am the vanguard of the men,
the rear guard of the men; a leader of

01:27:37.520 --> 01:27:43.239
the land through active conduct, strong
in speech, collected in thought, for I am

01:27:43.239 --> 01:27:49.440
without Peer, who spoke out when people
were silent, on the day of fear, when

01:27:49.440 --> 01:27:52.520
Upper Egypt was silent.

01:27:53.119 --> 01:28:00.360
Ankhtifi recalls the time of famine
that swept over the land as crisis after

01:28:00.360 --> 01:28:07.159
crisis rocked the struggling Old Kingdom.
All of Upper Egypt was dying of

01:28:07.159 --> 01:28:12.480
hunger to such a degree that everyone
had come to eating his children, but I

01:28:12.480 --> 01:28:17.280
managed that no one died of hunger in
this province. The entire country had

01:28:17.280 --> 01:28:22.119
become like a starved grasshopper, with
people going to the north and to the

01:28:22.119 --> 01:28:28.920
south in search of grain.
Egypt was now fracturing into something

01:28:28.920 --> 01:28:33.719
like the shape it had been before King
Narmer had fused it into a stable

01:28:33.719 --> 01:28:41.639
centralized state nearly eight hundred
years before. Refugees were flooding the

01:28:41.639 --> 01:28:47.080
roads. Another later Egyptian writer
called Ipuwer, who lived in the period

01:28:47.080 --> 01:28:52.920
following this chaos, describes people
resorting to theft to survive, and

01:28:52.920 --> 01:28:56.040
violence spreading.

01:28:56.199 --> 01:29:02.320
The guardians of the house say,  Let us go
and steal.  The snarers of birds have

01:29:02.320 --> 01:29:07.000
formed themselves into armed bands. The
peasants of the delta have provided

01:29:07.000 --> 01:29:12.880
themselves with shields. A man regards
his son as his enemy. The wrongdoer is in

01:29:12.880 --> 01:29:21.040
every place. The inundation of the Nile
comes, yet no one goes out to plough.

01:29:21.639 --> 01:29:28.719
Ipuwer describes a widespread economic
collapse, during which trade from foreign

01:29:28.719 --> 01:29:34.679
lands dried up.
The skilled masons who built pyramids

01:29:34.679 --> 01:29:39.480
now labor on farms, and those who tended
the boat of the gods are yolked together

01:29:39.480 --> 01:29:43.400
in ploughing.
Men do not go on voyages

01:29:43.400 --> 01:29:48.880
today. What shall we do for cedar wood for
our mummies, in coffins of which priests

01:29:48.880 --> 01:29:52.280
are buried, and with the oil of which men
are embalmed?

01:29:52.280 --> 01:29:56.880
They come no longer. Everything
is in ruins. Laughter is dead.

01:29:56.880 --> 01:30:06.280
If I only knew where god was,
I would make offerings to him.

01:30:06.440 --> 01:30:12.560
Throughout this period of about two
hundred years, some at least must have dreamed

01:30:12.560 --> 01:30:18.080
of a better time awaiting them in the
future. Another text written after this

01:30:18.080 --> 01:30:24.159
time, known as the Prophecy of Neferti,
contains a prediction that a ruler would

01:30:24.159 --> 01:30:28.600
come who would end this time of strife.

01:30:28.880 --> 01:30:36.520
A king will come. He will take the
white crown; he will wear the red crown.

01:30:36.520 --> 01:30:43.280
He will unite the two mighty lands.
Rejoice, ye people of his time. The

01:30:43.280 --> 01:30:50.480
Asiatics will fall to his sword, and the
Libyans will fall to his flame. The

01:30:50.480 --> 01:30:56.239
rebels belong to his wrath, and the
treacherous in heart belong to the awe

01:30:56.239 --> 01:31:01.440
of him.
The man who would fulfill this

01:31:01.440 --> 01:31:06.199
prophecy, or rather, the man in whose
reign the prophecy was more likely

01:31:06.199 --> 01:31:11.800
written, would reunite Egypt and usher in
a new age of stability.

01:31:11.800 --> 01:31:18.440
His name was Nebhepetre Mentuhotep II.

01:31:33.199 --> 01:31:39.360
Mentuhotep was a king in the city of
Thebes in Upper Egypt.

01:31:39.360 --> 01:31:46.000
Sitting on the eastern bank of the
Nile, about eight hundred kilometers from the

01:31:46.000 --> 01:31:51.679
Mediterranean, Thebes is one of the sunniest
and driest cities in the world. It had been

01:31:51.679 --> 01:31:55.960
the capital of its own province
throughout the Old Kingdom, but had

01:31:55.960 --> 01:32:01.239
always been something of a backwater and
somewhat influenced by the African

01:32:01.239 --> 01:32:05.600
culture of Nubia.
But during the more than a century

01:32:05.600 --> 01:32:11.080
of chaos that surrounded the collapse of
the Old Kingdom, Thebes slowly grew to

01:32:11.080 --> 01:32:16.760
become the capital of the south, and its
kings began referring to themselves as

01:32:16.760 --> 01:32:22.840
the great overlord of Upper Egypt.
It was a city where tightly-packed

01:32:22.840 --> 01:32:28.480
rows of houses, granaries, and workshops
clustered around the central temple to

01:32:28.480 --> 01:32:32.520
the god Amun,
and its people clearly sought a

01:32:32.520 --> 01:32:37.360
break from the suffocating influence of
the kings in Memphis.

01:32:37.360 --> 01:32:43.280
But in the north, near the
traditional center of Egyptian power, an

01:32:43.280 --> 01:32:47.600
ambitious and ruthless rival was also
amassing its forces.

01:32:47.600 --> 01:32:53.800
This was centered around the city
of Henen-Nesut in Lower Egypt, in the verdant

01:32:53.800 --> 01:32:59.560
region between the river Nile and
the great lake at Faiyum, a region that the

01:32:59.560 --> 01:33:06.800
desert Thebans dismissively called  the
marshlands . This city would later be

01:33:06.800 --> 01:33:14.760
known as Heracleopolis, or  the city of
Hercules . For about a hundred years during

01:33:14.760 --> 01:33:20.400
this time of dissolution, Thebes and
Henen-Nesut had fought bitter wars over

01:33:20.400 --> 01:33:26.520
small border regions, forts, and roads, but
neither side could ever gain the upper

01:33:26.520 --> 01:33:32.600
hand. That was until the reign of the
king of Thebes, Mentuhotep.

01:33:32.600 --> 01:33:39.360
He was named after the Theban god of
war, and came from a line of warlike

01:33:39.360 --> 01:33:44.159
kings. He clearly desired to bring this
series of conflicts to a decisive

01:33:44.159 --> 01:33:48.440
conclusion and reunite the fractured
kingdom of old.

01:33:48.440 --> 01:33:54.239
The final confrontation between
north and south would be sparked

01:33:54.239 --> 01:34:01.159
by a rebellion in the city of Thinis, once
home to King Narmer, and which was now one

01:34:01.159 --> 01:34:05.920
of the vassals of Thebes.
Delighted by this development,

01:34:05.920 --> 01:34:11.600
the northern power of Henen-Nesut seized
the opportunity, and marched south into

01:34:11.600 --> 01:34:15.239
the desert to capture the

01:34:15.360 --> 01:34:22.199
town. War soon raged across all
Egypt. At one point, the northerners

01:34:22.199 --> 01:34:28.199
pushed south and captured the ancient,
sacred city of Abydos, and there

01:34:28.199 --> 01:34:33.840
unleashed a wave of destruction against
its temples and palaces.

01:34:37.400 --> 01:34:43.199
One later text known as the
Instruction to Merikare purports to be

01:34:43.199 --> 01:34:48.560
written by a king of northern Henen-Nesut,
who is racked with guilt for the

01:34:48.560 --> 01:34:55.960
destruction of this sacred city.
Lo, a shameful deed occurred in my

01:34:55.960 --> 01:35:02.320
time; the province of Theese was ravaged.
Though it happened through my doing, I

01:35:02.320 --> 01:35:08.960
learned it after it was done. There was
retribution for what I had done, for it

01:35:08.960 --> 01:35:14.440
is evil to destroy.
Beware of it! A blow is repaid by its

01:35:14.440 --> 01:35:19.800
like. To every action, there is a response.

01:35:19.920 --> 01:35:25.719
This response would come in the
form of a thundering reprisal by the

01:35:25.719 --> 01:35:29.520
king of Thebes, Mentuhotep.

01:35:32.840 --> 01:35:38.960
He would march into the north and
defeat the armies of Henen-Nesut.

01:35:38.960 --> 01:35:46.320
Next, he rounded on the northern
capital. When he captured it, all of the

01:35:46.320 --> 01:35:52.760
funerary monuments of its kings were
defaced and destroyed, perhaps suggesting

01:35:52.760 --> 01:35:57.719
a sacking of the city. Whatever the
northerners had done to the sacred

01:35:57.719 --> 01:36:04.400
center of Abydos, it was clearly visited
upon them and their city

01:36:04.400 --> 01:36:10.159
tenfold. Mentuhotep now swept through
Northern Egypt, and the provincial

01:36:10.159 --> 01:36:16.639
governors saw the writing on the wall,
and swore fealty to him. After nearly two

01:36:16.639 --> 01:36:25.560
centuries of dissolution, the two halves
of Egypt were once again united.

01:36:32.080 --> 01:36:37.400
The period that followed, known as the
Middle Kingdom of Egypt, would last for

01:36:37.400 --> 01:36:43.360
around three hundred years, but it has not
left an impressive archaeological

01:36:43.360 --> 01:36:49.000
record. Compared to the towering pyramids
of the Old Kingdom and the architectural

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:54.560
magnificence of the later New Kingdom, it
stands out as something of a dull time

01:36:54.560 --> 01:36:59.000
for grand monument construction.
But it did experience a

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:05.239
flourishing in another area; that is, in
the realm of Egyptian

01:37:05.239 --> 01:37:11.520
literature. One famous story written
around this time is called the Tale of

01:37:11.520 --> 01:37:17.679
Sinuhe. It narrates the life of a man who
traveled north into Palestine and beyond,

01:37:17.679 --> 01:37:24.239
but who eventually becomes homesick and
decides to return to Egypt.

01:37:24.239 --> 01:37:28.000
Another collection of stories was
written around this time, a kind of

01:37:28.000 --> 01:37:32.119
ancient Arabian Nights, known as the
Tales of Wonder.

01:37:32.119 --> 01:37:36.960
It relates a number of
fantastical stories, imagining that they

01:37:36.960 --> 01:37:42.560
were told to the great Pharaoh Khufu of
the Old Kingdom by his three sons.

01:37:42.560 --> 01:37:47.840
Another story written during the
Middle Kingdom is known as the Tale of

01:37:47.840 --> 01:37:54.040
the Shipwrecked Sailor, a kind of ancient
Gulliver s Travels. It is remarkable for

01:37:54.040 --> 01:38:00.239
its innovative structure, a tale within a
tale about a sailor shipwrecked in the

01:38:00.239 --> 01:38:06.639
Mediterranean who finds himself on an
island ruled by a gigantic serpent.

01:38:15.960 --> 01:38:22.440
A storm came up, with us on the
open sea, and no chance for us to reach

01:38:22.440 --> 01:38:28.480
harbor. The wind grew sharp and made a
constant moaning, and there were hungry

01:38:28.480 --> 01:38:33.239
fourteen-foot-high waves.
A piece of wood of some sort hit

01:38:33.239 --> 01:38:40.400
me, and then the ship was dead.
Of all those fine men, not a one

01:38:40.400 --> 01:38:50.760
survived. Then I was carried to a desert
island by a swell of the great green sea.

01:38:54.679 --> 01:38:59.840
The man speaks with the great serpent,
who tells him a sad story of his own,

01:38:59.840 --> 01:39:05.639
that his whole family was killed when a
star fell to Earth. The serpent tells the

01:39:05.639 --> 01:39:11.280
man not to fear, that a ship will
eventually pass by the island and rescue

01:39:11.280 --> 01:39:17.560
him, and reassures him that he will soon
have a great story to tell.

01:39:21.679 --> 01:39:28.520
Now, you are going to spend one
month, and then another, until you finish

01:39:28.520 --> 01:39:35.080
four months on this island; then a ship
will come from Egypt with sailors in it

01:39:35.080 --> 01:39:41.920
whom you know, that you may go with them
toward home and die in your own city.

01:39:41.920 --> 01:39:48.400
What joy for one who lives, to tell
the things he has been through when the

01:39:48.400 --> 01:39:52.320
suffering is over!

01:39:58.320 --> 01:40:04.239
Finally, the predicted ship arrives, and
the man is rescued.

01:40:12.400 --> 01:40:18.840
At last the ship arrived just as
he had foretold. I climbed a lofty tree

01:40:18.840 --> 01:40:24.119
and recognized the sailors in the ship,
and went running to report it.

01:40:24.119 --> 01:40:28.880
Then I descended to the shore near where
the ship was. I hailed the crew and offered

01:40:28.880 --> 01:40:35.679
thanks beside the sea to the Lord of
the Isle, and those on board did likewise.

01:40:42.040 --> 01:40:48.040
We have examples of myths and
legends written before this time, and

01:40:48.040 --> 01:40:53.920
religious texts, but this is not the
story of some bygone king or the actions

01:40:53.920 --> 01:41:00.719
of the gods. It's a story about an
ordinary man in a fantastical situation,

01:41:00.719 --> 01:41:05.119
told seemingly just for the
entertainment value of telling a story,

01:41:05.119 --> 01:41:10.599
and for that reason, it is possibly the
first true piece of literature. It was likely

01:41:10.599 --> 01:41:19.080
written around the year 1900 BC, and is
therefore nearly four thousand years old.

01:41:27.440 --> 01:41:32.239
The lives of Egypt's pharaohs take up so
much of the usual discussion of its

01:41:32.239 --> 01:41:36.760
history partly because they are the ones
who commissioned the inscriptions, the

01:41:36.760 --> 01:41:41.480
monuments, and the statues. But as the
Middle Kingdom's flourishing of

01:41:41.480 --> 01:41:46.040
literature continued, we get more and
more of a sense of what life was like

01:41:46.040 --> 01:41:53.239
for ordinary people in the Nile
Valley. One text of this period

01:41:53.239 --> 01:41:58.719
known as the Papyrus Lansing gives a
fascinating insight into the lives of

01:41:58.719 --> 01:42:03.119
Egypt's common people.
It is written as a piece of

01:42:03.119 --> 01:42:09.520
rhetoric by a master scribe to one of
his pupils, attempting to convince him to

01:42:09.520 --> 01:42:14.560
become a scribe in turn, and from
this, we get a wonderful impression

01:42:14.560 --> 01:42:20.960
of all the ways that people could
make their living in the land of Egypt.

01:42:21.679 --> 01:42:29.480
Young fellow writing, to him who
knows it, is more profitable than any

01:42:29.480 --> 01:42:38.320
profession. It is pleasanter than bread
and beer, than clothing, than oil. Yes, it

01:42:38.320 --> 01:42:45.639
is more precious than an inheritance in
Egypt, than a tomb in the west. Look for

01:42:45.639 --> 01:42:52.560
thyself with your own eye; here, all the
professions are set before you.

01:42:52.560 --> 01:42:59.320
The washer-man spends the whole day going
up and down, every limb of his is a-weary,

01:42:59.320 --> 01:43:03.159
whitening the clothes of his neighbors
every day.

01:43:03.159 --> 01:43:09.719
The potter is smeared with mud, like
a man in mourning; his hands and feet are

01:43:09.719 --> 01:43:14.520
full of clay. He is like one who lives in
the bog.

01:43:14.520 --> 01:43:21.000
The cobbler mixes tanning lotions;
his odor is marked, his hands are red

01:43:21.000 --> 01:43:24.480
with dye, like one who is smeared with
his blood.

01:43:24.480 --> 01:43:31.119
The florist makes bouquets and
makes the wine jar stands beautiful; he

01:43:31.119 --> 01:43:36.520
spends a night of toil sweating, like one
on whose body the sun is shining.

01:43:36.520 --> 01:43:41.960
The merchants fare downstream and
upstream, and are as busy as can be,

01:43:41.960 --> 01:43:46.920
carrying wares from one town to another,
and supplying him that hath not.

01:43:46.920 --> 01:43:55.040
If thou hast any
sense, be a scribe.

01:43:55.840 --> 01:44:01.119
Whether or not daily life was truly that
bad for all these other workers, we can't

01:44:01.119 --> 01:44:08.939
tell, because of course, none of them
wrote down how they felt.

01:44:12.679 --> 01:44:18.320
Most of Egypt's people were peasant
farmers, and even when they practiced

01:44:18.320 --> 01:44:23.840
these other professions, they likely
engaged in some farming, too.

01:44:23.840 --> 01:44:28.320
These peasants did not own the land they
worked, and were required to give most of

01:44:28.320 --> 01:44:33.119
the food they produced to the crown or
to their local temple.

01:44:33.119 --> 01:44:39.800
To supplement their diets, most
houses kept private kitchen gardens, too,

01:44:39.800 --> 01:44:43.480
which the women would tend while the men
went out to the fields.

01:44:43.480 --> 01:44:48.239
Egyptian women were also
responsible for baking the bread they

01:44:48.239 --> 01:44:53.719
ate every day.
Bread in Egypt was made primarily

01:44:53.719 --> 01:45:00.679
with emmer wheat. Dough was often pressed
into clay molds and baked, and at times,

01:45:00.679 --> 01:45:06.840
people got creative, baking bread in
spirals like the cinnamon swirl, and using

01:45:06.840 --> 01:45:11.760
shaped molds to bake loaves in the form
of animals.

01:45:11.760 --> 01:45:17.080
Those who could afford it also
baked cakes and pastries out of the

01:45:17.080 --> 01:45:23.679
finest flour, sweetened with dates and
honey. Alongside

01:45:23.679 --> 01:45:29.400
their bread, Egyptians ate a
varied diet including garlic and spring

01:45:29.400 --> 01:45:34.480
onions, lettuce, celery, cucumbers, gourds,
and melons.

01:45:34.480 --> 01:45:40.599
They supplemented these with high-
protein beans and pulses, like lentils

01:45:40.599 --> 01:45:47.000
and chickpeas, and a kind of edible tuber
known as a tiger nut that grows at the

01:45:47.000 --> 01:45:52.040
base of wetland sedges.
All of this was cooked in olive

01:45:52.040 --> 01:45:55.719
oil, at least from the time the
pyramids were built.

01:45:55.719 --> 01:46:04.000
At times, they would also eat meat,
primarily beef, lamb, pork, and goat, as

01:46:04.000 --> 01:46:12.000
well as quail, pigeon, duck, geese, and
partridge. Mice were even eaten at times,

01:46:12.000 --> 01:46:15.560
and even hedgehogs.
The Egyptians cooked these

01:46:15.560 --> 01:46:21.639
spiky creatures by wrapping them in wet
clay and baking them in it, and when the

01:46:21.639 --> 01:46:27.440
clay was cracked open afterwards, it took
the hedgehog's spines with it. The

01:46:27.440 --> 01:46:34.560
Egyptians also made cheese and even foie gras,
made from force-feeding geese.

01:46:34.560 --> 01:46:41.360
One text written by a scribe to
the queen Nefertari urges people to

01:46:41.360 --> 01:46:47.080
share with others the food they have.
Do not eat bread while another

01:46:47.080 --> 01:46:54.040
stands by without extending your hand to
him. As to food, it is here always. It

01:46:54.040 --> 01:47:01.800
is man who does not last; one man is rich,
another is poor, but food remains for him

01:47:01.800 --> 01:47:06.679
who shares it.
Beer was exceptionally popular in

01:47:06.679 --> 01:47:13.040
Egypt, and people consumed it daily. As a
result, breweries were important centers

01:47:13.040 --> 01:47:16.480
of industry.
Beer was thought to have been

01:47:16.480 --> 01:47:23.119
given to Egypt by the goddess Hathor, the
goddess of beauty, music, and dancing, and

01:47:23.119 --> 01:47:28.360
breweries were watched over by the
goddess Tenenet; so, fittingly, many beer

01:47:28.360 --> 01:47:34.080
factories were run by women. Some of
these were enormous and were capable of

01:47:34.080 --> 01:47:40.040
brewing more than a million liters a
year. They used large pottery vats

01:47:40.040 --> 01:47:46.000
propped up on mud bricks over crackling
fires, and inside these they heated

01:47:46.000 --> 01:47:51.480
barley and water, then left the mixture
to ferment before flavoring the brew

01:47:51.480 --> 01:47:55.599
with honey and syrups made of dates and
other fruit.

01:47:55.599 --> 01:48:01.480
There was even one annual festival
called the Tekh Festival, that would

01:48:01.480 --> 01:48:05.440
become known as  the Festival of

01:48:07.920 --> 01:48:13.320
Drunkenness . During this fiesta, Egyptians
would drink as much beer as they could,

01:48:13.320 --> 01:48:18.400
and then fall asleep together in a large
hall. They would then be awoken all

01:48:18.400 --> 01:48:23.679
together by the loud beating of drums. It
was said that in the moment just after

01:48:23.679 --> 01:48:29.080
waking, some of them would meet the
goddess Hathor herself.

01:48:38.520 --> 01:48:44.760
Egypt was one of the most stable
and prosperous agricultural societies in

01:48:44.760 --> 01:48:49.599
the ancient world, but it was a society
built entirely on the collection and

01:48:49.599 --> 01:48:56.280
storage of grain. As a result, there was
one ever-present danger; that was the

01:48:56.280 --> 01:49:02.400
presence of mice and rats.
Grain was stored in large circular

01:49:02.400 --> 01:49:08.920
granaries within the towns, shaped like
beehives, and freshly-harvested wheat or

01:49:08.920 --> 01:49:15.000
barley was poured in through a hole in
the top to be preserved in the hot, dry

01:49:15.000 --> 01:49:20.560
air. When grain was needed for bread-
making or beer-brewing, it was taken from

01:49:20.560 --> 01:49:26.400
a small door in the bottom of these
granaries. But if mice got into this storage

01:49:26.400 --> 01:49:31.199
or even ate the grain while it was still
in the fields, then thousands of hours of

01:49:31.199 --> 01:49:35.639
work could be wasted, and people might
even starve.

01:49:35.639 --> 01:49:42.520
But thankfully, Egyptians were
able to rely on one particular set of

01:49:42.520 --> 01:49:47.280
allies; that was the domestic cat.

01:49:49.760 --> 01:49:57.080
There were two major breeds of wild
cat native to Egypt; the jungle cat, or

01:49:57.080 --> 01:50:02.480
Felis chaus, and the African wild cat,
Felis silvestris lybica.

01:50:02.480 --> 01:50:08.480
Of these, the African wild cat had
something of a calmer temperament, and so,

01:50:08.480 --> 01:50:14.320
was most commonly bred as a pet, with
evidence of their domestication in Egypt

01:50:14.320 --> 01:50:18.599
from at least five thousand years ago.

01:50:18.599 --> 01:50:24.880
These cats were kept around Egyptian
settlements for their obvious utility

01:50:24.880 --> 01:50:30.239
both in controlling mice and with their
almost supernatural reflexes for their

01:50:30.239 --> 01:50:35.239
ability to kill venomous snakes.
But it's clear that the Egyptians

01:50:35.239 --> 01:50:39.080
also enjoyed their company, and even
loved them.

01:50:39.080 --> 01:50:45.000
Some particularly beloved pets were
buried with tiny offerings intended to

01:50:45.000 --> 01:50:50.760
serve them well in the cat afterlife.
The Greek writer Diodorus of Sicily

01:50:50.760 --> 01:50:57.159
recalls seeing Egyptians performing
burial ceremonies for their cats.

01:50:57.159 --> 01:51:03.599
When one of these animals dies, they
wrap it in fine linen, and then, wailing

01:51:03.599 --> 01:51:09.159
and beating their breasts, carry it off
to be embalmed, and after it has been

01:51:09.159 --> 01:51:13.880
treated with cedar oil and such spices
as have the quality of imparting a

01:51:13.880 --> 01:51:19.480
pleasant odor and of preserving the body
for a long time, they lay it away in a

01:51:19.480 --> 01:51:23.440
consecrated tomb.

01:51:23.440 --> 01:51:28.079
While the earliest domestication of the
house cat took place elsewhere in the

01:51:28.079 --> 01:51:32.560
fertile crescent, it was in Egypt that it
accelerated dramatically.

01:51:32.560 --> 01:51:38.960
As cats got used to their
new survival niche, they in turn began to

01:51:38.960 --> 01:51:45.800
adapt. They largely lost their original
camouflage coatings, became smaller, and

01:51:45.800 --> 01:51:51.599
even developed new ways of signaling to
their human patrons with soft insistent

01:51:51.599 --> 01:51:56.159
cries, modulated
to similar frequencies as a

01:51:56.159 --> 01:52:01.520
human baby.
Fittingly, the Egyptian word for  cat

01:52:01.520 --> 01:52:04.040
was  miu .

01:52:05.840 --> 01:52:12.079
Over time, this adoration of their
feline companions seems to have become a

01:52:12.079 --> 01:52:17.280
religious reverence, too.
With their ease and grace, cats in

01:52:17.280 --> 01:52:22.280
Egypt were associated with femininity,
and paintings in tombs often show the

01:52:22.280 --> 01:52:27.400
house household dog sitting below a
man's chair while a cat sits under the

01:52:27.400 --> 01:52:32.079
woman's chair.
One goddess named Bastet would

01:52:32.079 --> 01:52:38.159
soon become revered, and she manifested
as a woman with the head of a house

01:52:38.159 --> 01:52:44.280
cat. Bastet became a god of fertility, and
women would appeal to her during times

01:52:44.280 --> 01:52:49.440
of childbirth and pregnancy.
Diodorus later records seeing

01:52:49.440 --> 01:52:54.639
an Egyptian festival during which cats
were ritually fed.

01:52:54.639 --> 01:52:59.560
For the cats, they break up bread
into milk, and calling them with a

01:52:59.560 --> 01:53:04.360
clucking sound, set it before them, or
else they cut up fish caught in the Nile

01:53:04.360 --> 01:53:10.639
and feed the flesh to them raw. All who
meet these animals fall down before them

01:53:10.639 --> 01:53:16.480
and render them with honor.
The Egyptians were also fiercely

01:53:16.480 --> 01:53:21.440
protective of their feline companions, as
Diodorus recounts.

01:53:21.440 --> 01:53:25.920
Whoever kills a cat, whether
intentionally or unintentionally,

01:53:25.920 --> 01:53:32.400
he is certainly put to death,
for common people gather in crowds

01:53:32.400 --> 01:53:37.560
and deal with the perpetrator most
cruelly, sometimes doing this without

01:53:37.560 --> 01:53:43.760
waiting for a trial.
The worship and veneration of cats

01:53:43.760 --> 01:53:48.239
would continue throughout all the
thousands of years of Ancient Egyptian

01:53:48.239 --> 01:53:53.040
history, and for the cats, it is perhaps
something that they have never

01:53:53.040 --> 01:53:58.119
quite forgotten.

01:53:58.119 --> 01:54:03.400
The Middle Kingdom was not
just a time of entertainment and

01:54:03.400 --> 01:54:08.440
pleasure. With the mania for pyramid-
building somewhat subsided, certain

01:54:08.440 --> 01:54:13.199
pharaohs engaged in large-scale
construction projects to strengthen and

01:54:13.199 --> 01:54:19.440
develop the empire. One king spent much
of his life on a vast irrigation project

01:54:19.440 --> 01:54:26.040
around the oasis at Faiyum, determined to
turn it into a productive swathe of farmland.

01:54:26.040 --> 01:54:30.679
Another built a large series of
defensive walls in the Nile Delta,

01:54:30.679 --> 01:54:35.079
hemming Egypt off from the people of the
wider Middle East, whom the Egyptians

01:54:35.079 --> 01:54:39.239
called Asiatics.
These people were often

01:54:39.239 --> 01:54:44.960
depicted in their paintings with lighter,
more yellowish skin than the Egyptians,

01:54:44.960 --> 01:54:50.440
and were held in general contempt as
uncivilized barbarians.

01:54:50.440 --> 01:54:55.239
The Egyptians soon began
pushing their sphere of influence into

01:54:55.239 --> 01:55:00.400
this area, expanding their territory
north along the Mediterranean coast and

01:55:00.400 --> 01:55:05.560
into Palestine. They crossed the Sinai
Desert and subjugated the Phoenician

01:55:05.560 --> 01:55:12.119
city of Byblos. Then they turned their
attention south to Eastern Africa, what

01:55:12.119 --> 01:55:18.800
the Egyptians called  the horizon lands ,
the lands of the Nubians.

01:55:25.400 --> 01:55:29.920
Like the light-skinned Asiatics in the
north, the Egyptians considered the

01:55:29.920 --> 01:55:34.679
southern Nubians different to them, and
usually depicted them with darker skin

01:55:34.679 --> 01:55:40.159
than Egyptians, and more typically
African features. At this time, these

01:55:40.159 --> 01:55:45.639
kingdoms were relatively underdeveloped,
and were easy prey for an aggressive and

01:55:45.639 --> 01:55:48.560
expansionist Egypt.

01:55:50.639 --> 01:55:56.960
We've already seen that the first
cataract of the Nile was at Aswan, where

01:55:56.960 --> 01:56:02.000
the granite bedrock forced the water
into a series of rushing whitewater

01:56:02.000 --> 01:56:07.560
rapids. If an Ancient Egyptian traveled
upriver beyond Aswan and into the

01:56:07.560 --> 01:56:12.920
horizon lands, they would encounter five
more major cataracts of the Nile.

01:56:12.920 --> 01:56:18.400
These are each places where the
river becomes shallow and travel by boat

01:56:18.400 --> 01:56:24.719
becomes difficult, and so, there were
natural stops along any journey upriver.

01:56:24.719 --> 01:56:30.760
They were also the obvious place to draw
borders. During the Middle Kingdom, Egypt

01:56:30.760 --> 01:56:35.840
marched into the horizon lands multiple
times, and pushed its southern border as

01:56:35.840 --> 01:56:42.880
far as the second cataract.
Around the 1860s BC, one Middle

01:56:42.880 --> 01:56:48.800
Kingdom king named Senusret III marched
even further south into the Nubian

01:56:48.800 --> 01:56:57.159
kingdoms of Kush and Punt. He
remembers this brutal campaign in one

01:56:57.599 --> 01:57:05.000
inscription. The Nubians are wretches,
craven-hearted. My Majesty has seen it; it

01:57:05.000 --> 01:57:11.079
is not an untruth. I have captured their
women, I have carried off their subjects,

01:57:11.079 --> 01:57:20.719
poisoned their wells, killed their cattle,
cut down their grain, set fire to it.

01:57:20.760 --> 01:57:27.119
In this remorseless fashion, Senusret
marched beyond the second cataract and

01:57:27.119 --> 01:57:31.760
built a powerful set of fortresses.
We get a sense for their

01:57:31.760 --> 01:57:37.880
purpose from the names the Egyptians
gave to them. One of them at Askut was

01:57:37.880 --> 01:57:45.480
named  Crushing the Nubians , while another
at Shalfak was named  Subduing the Foreign

01:57:45.480 --> 01:57:52.599
Lands . In another imposing fortress at
Semna, now more than four hundred kilometers

01:57:52.599 --> 01:57:58.639
upstream from the former border of Aswan,
Senusret left a stone monument with the

01:57:58.639 --> 01:58:05.239
following triumphant inscription.
Year 16, third month of winter;

01:58:05.239 --> 01:58:10.280
the king made his southern
boundary. I have made my boundary further

01:58:10.280 --> 01:58:16.719
south than my father's. I have added to
what was bequeathed me. As for any son of

01:58:16.719 --> 01:58:24.040
mine, who shall maintain this border
which my Majesty has made, he is my son.

01:58:24.040 --> 01:58:29.760
But he who abandons it, who fails to
fight for it, he is not my son. He was not

01:58:29.760 --> 01:58:36.000
born to me.

01:58:36.000 --> 01:58:42.760
These forts were manned by powerful
units of Egyptian soldiers tasked with

01:58:42.760 --> 01:58:49.280
keeping order among the newly-colonized
Nubians. To this end, they engaged in a

01:58:49.280 --> 01:58:53.280
paranoid surveillance regime of the
local people.

01:58:53.280 --> 01:58:58.280
To the pharaoh Senusret, they sent back
constant updates on papyrus scrolls

01:58:58.280 --> 01:59:03.920
about the movements of even the most
minute groups of Nubians, some of which

01:59:03.920 --> 01:59:08.639
have survived.
The patrol who went forth to

01:59:08.639 --> 01:59:14.560
patrol the desert edge from the fortress
Khesef-Medja ew in year 3, month three of the

01:59:14.560 --> 01:59:19.560
growing season, have come to report to me
saying, we have found the tracks of thirty-two

01:59:19.560 --> 01:59:22.640
men and three donkeys.

01:59:24.199 --> 01:59:29.679
All these dispatches end in the same way,
with the same comforting offer of

01:59:29.679 --> 01:59:34.400
reassurance to the king.
All the affairs of the king's domain

01:59:34.400 --> 01:59:40.199
are safe and sound. All the affairs
of the master are safe and sound.

01:59:40.199 --> 01:59:46.239
But we have reason to believe that
King Senusret was not entirely

01:59:46.239 --> 01:59:52.079
reassured. He is famous for the numerous
sculptures he had made of himself,

01:59:52.079 --> 01:59:57.560
statues carved from black diorite that
depict him in strangely realistic

01:59:57.560 --> 02:00:02.920
fashion, unlike any depictions of a
pharaoh that had come before. In these

02:00:02.920 --> 02:00:08.880
statues, his ears are extended to
enormous proportions like a bat, perhaps

02:00:08.880 --> 02:00:14.159
projecting the image of a king who heard
every movement in his kingdom, relayed by

02:00:14.159 --> 02:00:19.440
his extensive system of spies.
Three of these statues in

02:00:19.440 --> 02:00:27.520
particular show the king first as a boy,
then as a man, and finally in old age. In

02:00:27.520 --> 02:00:32.719
this final statue, we get a sense for the
mental toll it took on a man to sit at

02:00:32.719 --> 02:00:39.079
the top of this paranoid system; the
pharaoh's weary sunken eyes, his haggard

02:00:39.079 --> 02:00:43.280
face contorted in an expression of
eternal worry.

02:00:43.280 --> 02:00:49.320
Today, these three statues stand as
a kind of metaphor for the state the

02:00:49.320 --> 02:00:53.679
Egyptian Middle Kingdom had sunk into
during during its final decades.

02:00:53.679 --> 02:01:00.079
Senusret's son, Amenemhat III, did
just as his father's inscriptions had

02:01:00.079 --> 02:01:03.639
urged, and held the southern border
against the Nubians.

02:01:03.639 --> 02:01:11.560
But following his reign, Egypt
was once more plunged into a succession

02:01:13.119 --> 02:01:18.239
crisis. The crisis was so severe that
their next king was something that had

02:01:18.239 --> 02:01:23.480
until then been almost unthinkable; a
woman. Her name

02:01:23.480 --> 02:01:28.880
was Sobekneferu, possibly the
daughter, sister, or wife of the previous

02:01:28.880 --> 02:01:33.840
pharaoh. She was probably not the first
woman to hold power in Egypt, but she was

02:01:33.840 --> 02:01:40.320
the first one to attain the full
official title of a king. Sobekneferu used

02:01:40.320 --> 02:01:45.520
masculine titles in her inscriptions, and
one statue of her even shows her wearing

02:01:45.520 --> 02:01:49.079
an unconventional mixture of male and
female clothing.

02:01:49.079 --> 02:01:54.040
However, she did not succeed in
slowing the dynasty's decline.

02:01:54.040 --> 02:02:00.400
She died after ruling for only four
years, and did not leave any heirs.

02:02:00.400 --> 02:02:10.970
After that, the serpent Isfet
uncoiled once more, and Egypt slid into chaos.

02:02:17.520 --> 02:02:23.679
During the time that followed,
known as the Second Intermediate Period,

02:02:23.679 --> 02:02:28.760
there were 150 years during which at
least fifty kings ruled.

02:02:28.760 --> 02:02:34.760
Egypt once again split in two, and
local governors stopped mentioning the

02:02:34.760 --> 02:02:39.760
king in their tomb inscriptions.
The pyramids of this period

02:02:39.760 --> 02:02:45.480
had already become small and meager,
mostly built from mud brick, but now

02:02:45.480 --> 02:02:50.840
their construction stopped altogether.
Some kings were even buried in

02:02:50.840 --> 02:02:57.679
simple shaft tombs, little better than
commoners. Much of the Nile Delta of

02:02:57.679 --> 02:03:02.719
Lower Egypt had already broken away from
the empire, and now in the south, the

02:03:02.719 --> 02:03:08.840
people of Nubia were in open
rebellion. One by one, the Egyptians were

02:03:08.840 --> 02:03:13.599
forced to let go of their southern forts,
abandoning them to the

02:03:13.599 --> 02:03:19.880
Nubians. Once a symbol of the empire's
confidence, these powerful fortresses now

02:03:19.880 --> 02:03:25.079
became unprecedented military assets for
their enemies, and bases from which

02:03:25.079 --> 02:03:30.800
powerful raiding parties ranged ever
farther into Egypt. The cruelty that the

02:03:30.800 --> 02:03:37.119
Egyptians had shown to their Nubian
neighbors was now being paid back in

02:03:37.119 --> 02:03:42.320
full. With the northern and southern
borders convulsed in conflict, Egypt's

02:03:42.320 --> 02:03:46.040
trade links with the rest of the world
were severely disrupted.

02:03:46.040 --> 02:03:50.960
It was also during this time
or perhaps later that the entire

02:03:50.960 --> 02:03:55.000
Mediterranean, in fact,
most of the world, witnessed one

02:03:55.000 --> 02:03:58.599
of the largest natural disasters in
human history.

02:03:58.599 --> 02:04:04.559
That is the eruption of the
volcano Thera, now known as the Greek

02:04:04.559 --> 02:04:11.000
island of Santorini, only seven hundred
kilometers from the Egyptian coast.

02:04:17.880 --> 02:04:22.599
It's likely that the Egyptians
would have heard the deep boom of this

02:04:22.599 --> 02:04:27.199
explosion, which went off with the force
of several hundred atomic bombs.

02:04:27.199 --> 02:04:34.400
When the Indonesian volcano Krakatoa
erupted in 1883, the explosion was heard

02:04:34.400 --> 02:04:40.079
more than three thousand kilometers away,
and it s thought that the Thera explosion

02:04:40.079 --> 02:04:45.000
was at least four times more
powerful. Today, the seawater-filled

02:04:45.000 --> 02:04:52.880
volcanic crater left by the eruption is
more than ten kilometers wide.

02:04:52.880 --> 02:04:58.840
This event may have ejected more than forty
square kilometers of rock into the

02:04:58.840 --> 02:05:04.000
atmosphere. The black plume would have
been riven with volcanic lightning, and

02:05:04.000 --> 02:05:09.079
it would have triggered tsunamis ten meters
high that would have devastated coastal

02:05:09.079 --> 02:05:15.119
regions, as well as causing a volcanic
winter. The eruption may have wiped out

02:05:15.119 --> 02:05:20.760
the Minoan civilization on Crete in one
blow, perhaps inspiring part of the

02:05:20.760 --> 02:05:24.840
Atlantis myth, and
chronicles as far away as China

02:05:24.840 --> 02:05:30.119
record a period when the sky turned a
strange yellow color, and crop yields

02:05:30.119 --> 02:05:37.400
fell. One Egyptian inscription known as
the Tempest Stelae may record some memory

02:05:37.400 --> 02:05:40.760
of this terrifying event.

02:05:41.480 --> 02:05:47.040
The gods expressed their discontent.
The gods made the sky come

02:05:47.040 --> 02:05:53.559
with a tempest. It caused darkness in the
western region. The sky was unleashed,

02:05:53.559 --> 02:05:58.840
more powerful on the mountains than the
turbulence of the cataract at Aswan.

02:05:58.840 --> 02:06:02.840
Each house, each shelter that they
reached, were floating in the water like the

02:06:02.840 --> 02:06:07.800
barks of papyrus outside the royal
residence for days.

02:06:08.239 --> 02:06:14.559
Volcanic ash, or tephra, would have
begun to rain down on the whole region,

02:06:14.559 --> 02:06:22.760
and today could be detected at virtually
every site in the Eastern Mediterranean.

02:06:22.760 --> 02:06:27.599
Spurred by this natural disaster and
exacerbated by the collapse of the

02:06:27.599 --> 02:06:33.280
Egyptian administration, soon famine once
more descended on the land.

02:06:33.280 --> 02:06:39.480
Among all of this, a powerful and
mysterious force of outsiders must have

02:06:39.480 --> 02:06:43.119
been watching.
They came from the Eastern

02:06:43.119 --> 02:06:48.119
Mediterranean region from across the
Sinai Desert, and they intended to

02:06:48.119 --> 02:06:56.480
conquer Egypt and rule it for themselves.
These people were known as the Hyksos.

02:07:04.119 --> 02:07:11.840
The word  Hyksos  comes from the
Egyptian phrase  hekau khasut , meaning  rulers

02:07:11.840 --> 02:07:16.920
of foreign lands .
Where exactly the Hyksos were from

02:07:16.920 --> 02:07:22.239
is unknown, but it's thought they may
have originated in the region of Syria,

02:07:22.239 --> 02:07:26.719
and one thing seems to have been behind
their great military success,

02:07:26.719 --> 02:07:30.960
and that was the chariot.

02:07:31.239 --> 02:07:36.079
At this point, some form of
chariot had been used by various

02:07:36.079 --> 02:07:41.239
societies for many
centuries. Vehicles like a kind of war

02:07:41.239 --> 02:07:46.559
cart with four solid, wooden wheels
pulled by donkeys are depicted on the

02:07:46.559 --> 02:07:50.800
Sumerian standard of Ur, which was
created around the time that the

02:07:50.800 --> 02:07:56.119
pyramids of Giza were being built. But
Egypt had never experimented with this

02:07:56.119 --> 02:08:01.800
kind of vehicle, and over the preceding
millennium, the technology had taken huge

02:08:01.800 --> 02:08:05.599
leaps forward.
The chariots that the Hyksos

02:08:05.599 --> 02:08:11.280
brought into Egypt for the first time
had two wheels with spokes, light and

02:08:11.280 --> 02:08:16.079
fast, and they were each pulled by two
powerful animals that had been recently

02:08:16.079 --> 02:08:20.040
introduced to the region, the horse.

02:08:22.800 --> 02:08:27.840
These chariots were strong and mobile
battle platforms that could break enemy

02:08:27.840 --> 02:08:34.119
battle lines, while onboard archers with
powerful bows could pelt enemies with

02:08:34.119 --> 02:08:39.719
missiles. Whether the Hyksos arrived in
Egypt as a violent invasion or a more

02:08:39.719 --> 02:08:44.719
peaceful migration is somewhat up for
debate. People from the north have been

02:08:44.719 --> 02:08:49.559
settling in the Nile Delta for centuries,
and much of the population there was

02:08:49.559 --> 02:08:53.520
already what the Egyptians would
consider foreign by the time the Hyksos

02:08:53.520 --> 02:08:57.719
rulers arrived. But the Hyksos were
clearly not pacifists.

02:08:57.719 --> 02:09:03.199
They set up their own kingdom
in the Nile Delta, with its capital at

02:09:03.199 --> 02:09:09.559
Avaris, and in a devastating blow to
Egyptian morale, even swept south to

02:09:09.559 --> 02:09:16.679
capture the ancient capital of Memphis.
One much later source named Manetho

02:09:16.679 --> 02:09:21.920
records the arrival of the Hyksos.

02:09:21.920 --> 02:09:27.480
By main force, they easily seized the
country without striking a blow, and

02:09:27.480 --> 02:09:31.960
having overpowered the rulers of the
land, they then burned our cities

02:09:31.960 --> 02:09:36.880
ruthlessly, razed to the ground the
temples of the gods.

02:09:36.880 --> 02:09:43.040
Finally, they appointed as king one
of the number he had his seat at Memphis,

02:09:43.040 --> 02:09:47.520
levying tribute from Upper and Lower
Egypt, and always leaving garrisons behind

02:09:47.520 --> 02:09:54.000
in the most advantageous positions.
The pyramids, that great symbol

02:09:54.000 --> 02:10:01.360
of Egyptian prestige, were now in foreign
hands. Egyptian kings would now retreat

02:10:01.360 --> 02:10:07.040
back to their former capital in Upper
Egypt, the city of Thebes.

02:10:07.040 --> 02:10:12.000
With the Nubians increasingly
powerful in the south, and now the new

02:10:12.000 --> 02:10:17.480
threat of these Hyksos kings looming from
the north, the weakened Egyptians

02:10:17.480 --> 02:10:23.119
increasingly felt like they were being
crushed in a vice.

02:10:23.119 --> 02:10:31.719
For a time, it must have seemed like the
age of an independent Egypt was over.

02:10:31.719 --> 02:10:39.559
One king named Kamose, who came to
the throne of Thebes around 1555 BC,

02:10:39.559 --> 02:10:46.079
would put this intolerable situation in
the following terms.

02:10:46.079 --> 02:10:51.880
I should like to know what serves
this strength of mine when a chieftain

02:10:51.880 --> 02:10:59.800
is in Avaris and another in Kush, and I
sit united with an Asiatic and a Nubian,

02:10:59.800 --> 02:11:06.520
each in possession of his slice of Egypt,
and I cannot pass by him as far as

02:11:06.520 --> 02:11:12.800
Memphis. No man can settle down when
despoiled by the taxes of the Asiatics.

02:11:12.800 --> 02:11:19.360
I will grapple with him, that I may rip
open his belly! My wish is to save Egypt

02:11:19.360 --> 02:11:23.960
and to smite the Asiatic!

02:11:23.960 --> 02:11:29.119
King Kamose may have had a very personal
reason to hate the Hyksos.

02:11:29.119 --> 02:11:34.719
The mummified remains of the
previous pharaoh, his father, have been

02:11:34.719 --> 02:11:40.119
uncovered, and modern analysis shows that
he suffered brutal wounds to the head

02:11:40.119 --> 02:11:46.000
from a heavy, bladed weapon. These blows
must have sliced his cheek and fractured

02:11:46.000 --> 02:11:51.960
his jaw and skull, leading many to
conclude that he died on the battlefield.

02:11:51.960 --> 02:11:57.199
The king's body was then rushed back to
Thebes, where it was hastily

02:11:57.199 --> 02:12:02.520
mummified. If Prince Kamose saw his
father's body in this state as it was

02:12:02.520 --> 02:12:07.119
carried back into the city, we can only
imagine the kind of hatred that must

02:12:07.119 --> 02:12:12.280
have burned in his heart towards the
Hyksos invaders in the north.

02:12:12.280 --> 02:12:17.679
But many in Kamose's court were
clearly afraid of what a war with the

02:12:17.679 --> 02:12:22.440
Hyksos would do to the fragile state of
the country.

02:12:22.440 --> 02:12:27.679
One text known as the Carnarvon Tablet
describes how they appealed to their king

02:12:27.679 --> 02:12:32.800
to maintain the peace.
We are tranquil in our part of

02:12:32.800 --> 02:12:37.639
Egypt. Aswan at the first cataract is
strong, and the middle part of the land

02:12:37.639 --> 02:12:43.480
is with us. Men till for us the finest of
their lands. They allow our cattle to

02:12:43.480 --> 02:12:49.320
pasture in the papyrus marshes. Corn is
sent for our swine. Our cattle are not

02:12:49.320 --> 02:12:55.960
taken away. He holds the land of the
Asiatics; we hold Egypt. Only when one

02:12:55.960 --> 02:13:04.239
comes against us, should we act against him.
But Kamose refused.

02:13:04.239 --> 02:13:09.520
He wanted to strike a blow at
the Hyksos, but he knew that he would have

02:13:09.520 --> 02:13:15.960
to secure the southern border first and
recapture the old fortress of Buhen, just

02:13:15.960 --> 02:13:21.599
before the second cataract of the Nile.
Buhen was one of the strong-walled

02:13:21.599 --> 02:13:26.840
bastions built by Senusret III, and it was
one of the only forts the Egyptians

02:13:26.840 --> 02:13:32.760
built from stone rather than brick. But
since the collapse of the Middle Kingdom,

02:13:32.760 --> 02:13:37.199
its garrison had served a Nubian lord
from the kingdom of Kush.

02:13:37.199 --> 02:13:42.480
If the southern border was to hold
while Kamose expelled the Hyksos in the

02:13:42.480 --> 02:13:49.239
north, he would need to recapture the
fort of Buhen.

02:13:49.239 --> 02:13:55.440
Kamose marched south, preparing to
assault the fort, but it seems that upon

02:13:55.440 --> 02:14:00.719
sighting the enormous Egyptian army on
the horizon, the citizens of the fortress

02:14:00.719 --> 02:14:06.880
got the message and decided to swear
allegiance to the pharaoh without a

02:14:06.880 --> 02:14:12.520
fight. With this powerful fort now
holding the south, Kamose marched back to

02:14:12.520 --> 02:14:17.559
Thebes and prepared for the next
campaign season, when he would seek to

02:14:17.559 --> 02:14:22.320
bring war to the Hyksos and unite Egypt
once more.

02:14:22.320 --> 02:14:27.159
In the third year of his reign,
Kamose struck.

02:14:27.159 --> 02:14:32.760
I sailed north in my might to
repel the Asiatics through the command

02:14:32.760 --> 02:14:38.320
of Amun, with my brave army before me
like a flame of fire and the archers

02:14:38.320 --> 02:14:44.000
atop our fighting decks.
Kamose's fleet descended swiftly on

02:14:44.000 --> 02:14:48.960
the Hyksos in what appears to have been
something of a surprise attack. Caught

02:14:48.960 --> 02:14:56.040
off guard, the foreigners were defeated
and the vengeance of Kamose was terrible.

02:14:56.840 --> 02:15:03.440
When day dawned, I was upon him
as if it were a hawk. When breakfast time

02:15:03.440 --> 02:15:09.079
came, I overthrew him, having destroyed
his walls and slaughtered his people, and

02:15:09.079 --> 02:15:15.000
made his wife descend to the river bank.
My army acted like lions with their

02:15:15.000 --> 02:15:22.159
spoil   chattels, cattle, fat, honey   dividing
their things, their hearts joyful.

02:15:22.159 --> 02:15:29.119
As for Avaris on the two rivers, I laid
it waste without inhabitants; I destroyed

02:15:29.119 --> 02:15:33.639
their towns and burned their homes to
reddened ruin-heaps

02:15:33.639 --> 02:15:39.400
forever, because of the destruction they
had wrought in the midst of Egypt; they

02:15:39.400 --> 02:15:44.960
who had allowed themselves to hearken to
the call of the Asiatics, had forsaken

02:15:44.960 --> 02:15:49.960
Egypt, their mistress.
The king of the Hyksos

02:15:49.960 --> 02:15:55.800
immediately appealed to his Nubian ally,
the king of Kush, for help. At one point,

02:15:55.800 --> 02:16:00.360
the Egyptians intercepted a secret
message traveling south along the desert

02:16:00.360 --> 02:16:04.880
roads, the contents of which they recorded.

02:16:06.719 --> 02:16:13.520
Have you noticed what Egypt has
done against me? The ruler who is there,

02:16:13.520 --> 02:16:19.599
Kamose, penetrates my territory even
though I have not attacked him as he has

02:16:19.599 --> 02:16:26.800
you. He chooses these two lands in
order to afflict them, my land and yours,

02:16:26.800 --> 02:16:33.719
and he has ravaged them. Come northward;
do not flinch. Then we shall divide up

02:16:33.719 --> 02:16:36.599
the towns of Egypt.

02:16:36.960 --> 02:16:42.960
When this messenger returned to
the embattled Hyksos king, shamefaced and

02:16:42.960 --> 02:16:47.439
with the letter undelivered, he must have
known that all was lost. The war

02:16:47.439 --> 02:16:53.639
came to a swift end, and Kamose
recounts, with perhaps some exaggeration,

02:16:53.639 --> 02:16:58.399
his heroic return to Thebes.

02:16:58.760 --> 02:17:06.880
What a happy home trip for the
ruler! Life! Prosperity! Happiness! With his

02:17:06.880 --> 02:17:12.880
army ahead of him! They had no casualties,
nor did anyone blame his fellow, nor did

02:17:12.880 --> 02:17:18.760
their hearts weep! I moored on home soil
during the season of inundation; the

02:17:18.760 --> 02:17:25.280
riverbank was resplendent! Thebes was
festive; women and men had come to see me,

02:17:25.280 --> 02:17:31.120
every woman hugged her neighbor, no one
was tearful.

02:17:32.040 --> 02:17:37.439
His son Ahmose would press this
advantage, and in an even more

02:17:37.439 --> 02:17:42.160
devastating campaign, seized the ancient
capital of Memphis.

02:17:42.160 --> 02:17:47.359
Ahmose would be the first
pharaoh in at least a hundred years to

02:17:47.359 --> 02:17:51.880
recapture the great pyramids of Giza, and
we can imagine imagine his feelings as

02:17:51.880 --> 02:17:57.559
he gazed up at the monuments of his
ancestors Khufu and Khafre, by now already

02:17:57.559 --> 02:18:02.719
more than a thousand years old.
It's clear that the site inspired him,

02:18:02.719 --> 02:18:08.800
and he would even build a pyramid of
his own in Upper Egypt at the site of

02:18:08.800 --> 02:18:13.399
Abydos. This was one of the first
pyramids built for an Egyptian pharaoh

02:18:13.399 --> 02:18:18.040
since the fall of the Middle Kingdom, and
it was clearly designed as a symbol of

02:18:18.040 --> 02:18:23.719
renewal of the empire's great legacy.
But it would also be the last ever

02:18:23.719 --> 02:18:30.359
pyramid built by an Egyptian ruler.
After securing the Nile Delta,

02:18:30.359 --> 02:18:35.559
Ahmose marched north and even crossed the
Sinai, smashing through the traditional

02:18:35.559 --> 02:18:41.120
heartland of the Hyksos people, and seizing
territory in Palestine in the region of

02:18:41.120 --> 02:18:45.200
modern Gaza.
After that, he returned to the

02:18:45.200 --> 02:18:49.960
southern people of Kush, and pushed the
empire's borders farther south than they

02:18:49.960 --> 02:18:53.639
had ever been,
beyond the second cataract to the river

02:18:53.639 --> 02:18:59.719
island of Sai, now in northern
Sudan. From its lowest ebb, Egypt had

02:18:59.719 --> 02:19:08.889
suddenly reemerged as a major regional
power. This was the age of the

02:19:19.719 --> 02:19:22.719
New Kingdom.

02:19:24.240 --> 02:19:29.160
During the five centuries of the New
Kingdom, Egypt would reach its greatest

02:19:29.160 --> 02:19:35.519
territorial extent and construct some of
its most impressive monuments and

02:19:35.519 --> 02:19:40.800
artifacts. Despite recapturing Memphis,
its kings saw no reason to move the

02:19:40.800 --> 02:19:46.639
capital again, and so they now once again
ruled from the city of Thebes, far up

02:19:46.639 --> 02:19:51.800
the river in Upper Egypt.
By now, Egypt had also adopted the

02:19:51.800 --> 02:19:57.600
technology of the horse-drawn chariot from
their Hyksos foes, and its armies were now

02:19:57.600 --> 02:20:04.240
made up of powerful contingents of these
vehicles. During these centuries, Egypt

02:20:04.240 --> 02:20:09.760
saw the rule of its first great woman
pharaoh, Hatshepsut, who was one of its

02:20:09.760 --> 02:20:15.920
most prolific builders. She constructed the
towering temple complex at Karnak and the

02:20:15.920 --> 02:20:22.640
stately mortuary temple known as the
Holy of Holies. She also undertook a

02:20:22.640 --> 02:20:28.880
voyage in five ships to the land of Punt,
somewhere in Africa, and brought back

02:20:28.880 --> 02:20:35.640
incense trees and other goods to Egypt,
which she celebrated in one inscription.

02:20:36.080 --> 02:20:41.399
The ships returned with the
marvels of the land of Punt and with all

02:20:41.399 --> 02:20:47.439
the good woods of Ta-Netjer, with heaps of
incense, with trees producing green

02:20:47.439 --> 02:20:54.359
fragrance, with ebony and pure ivory,
with gold and green agates found in the

02:20:54.359 --> 02:21:00.000
land of the Amu, with hides of the
panthers of the south. Never since the

02:21:00.000 --> 02:21:06.479
beginning of the world have the like of
these wonders been brought by any king.

02:21:06.479 --> 02:21:12.280
The New Kingdom would also see some
of the most striking dramas emerge in

02:21:12.280 --> 02:21:18.280
the royal courts of Egypt. Of these, none
have drawn so much attention as the

02:21:18.280 --> 02:21:24.560
story of one pharaoh. He has been
described by some as a revolutionary, by

02:21:24.560 --> 02:21:29.200
others as a visionary, and by others
still as simply insane.

02:21:29.200 --> 02:21:35.000
He was a ruler named Amunhotep IV.

02:21:39.800 --> 02:21:47.479
Amunhotep came to the throne around
1350 BC. He had inherited his name from

02:21:47.479 --> 02:21:51.319
his father, who had ruled as Amunhotep III.

02:21:51.319 --> 02:21:57.280
Like most Egyptian names, it
included the name of a god, Amun, and it

02:21:57.280 --> 02:22:00.479
meant  Amun is satisfied .

02:22:00.680 --> 02:22:06.000
Amun had long been the god of
the city of Thebes, and was considered

02:22:06.000 --> 02:22:12.240
the god of fertility and of the wind. But
when the Hyksos were expelled from Egypt

02:22:12.240 --> 02:22:17.960
and Thebes became the capital once more,
this god Amun was given something of a

02:22:17.960 --> 02:22:23.840
promotion. He was unified with the
sun god Ra to create a compound deity

02:22:23.840 --> 02:22:31.479
now known as Amun-Ra, the perfect symbol
of the power of a new united Egypt.

02:22:35.240 --> 02:22:41.560
Amun-Ra was depicted as a man
bearing a golden staff and wearing a

02:22:41.560 --> 02:22:45.439
high crown, and later would be shown with
blue skin.

02:22:45.439 --> 02:22:50.880
This new deity was placed at the
head of all the various gods that

02:22:50.880 --> 02:22:56.280
the Egyptians worshiped; the king of the
gods and creator of the universe.

02:22:56.280 --> 02:23:02.760
One hymn to Amun-Ra describes
the primacy of his position.

02:23:02.760 --> 02:23:10.240
Lord of truth, father of the
gods, maker of men, creator of all animals,

02:23:10.240 --> 02:23:15.040
lord of things that are, creator of the
staff of life.

02:23:15.040 --> 02:23:21.040
The pharaoh Amunhotep IV would
keep his name for the first four years

02:23:21.040 --> 02:23:26.479
of his rule, but around his fifth year on
the throne, he made the unprecedented

02:23:26.479 --> 02:23:32.200
decision to change his royal name. That's
because he had a vision of a new system

02:23:32.200 --> 02:23:38.359
of belief that he wanted to spread over
all of Egypt. He wanted to do away with

02:23:38.359 --> 02:23:43.000
the messiness of Egyptian religion and
the system of different gods in

02:23:43.000 --> 02:23:48.520
different cities, different temples and
cults and priests. He devised a new

02:23:48.520 --> 02:23:54.279
system of worship that focused not on
any god but on the sun itself, which he

02:23:54.279 --> 02:24:00.560
seems to have believed was his true
father. This new god would be depicted as

02:24:00.560 --> 02:24:06.720
a bare, impersonal disc showering the
Earth with beams of light. It would be

02:24:06.720 --> 02:24:15.479
called simply the orb, or in Egyptian, the
Aten. One surviving hymn to the Aten,

02:24:15.479 --> 02:24:19.920
perhaps even written by the pharaoh
himself, shows the enormous power this

02:24:19.920 --> 02:24:23.560
new god was supposed to have.

02:24:31.760 --> 02:24:38.439
O sole god, like whom there is no
other, thou didst create the world

02:24:38.439 --> 02:24:43.240
according to thy desire.
You are in my heart; there is no

02:24:43.240 --> 02:24:52.319
other who knows you. Every land chatters
at his rising every day.

02:24:55.680 --> 02:25:00.920
Around year five of his reign, the
pharaoh Amunhotep abandoned his old

02:25:00.920 --> 02:25:07.200
name that paid respect to the god Amun,
and changed it to a new name for his new

02:25:07.200 --> 02:25:11.840
god. This new name meant  effective spirit
for the Aten .

02:25:11.840 --> 02:25:16.960
He was now the pharaoh Akhenaten.

02:25:17.880 --> 02:25:23.640
Akhenaten is the first recorded
person in history to have started a new

02:25:23.640 --> 02:25:28.000
religion by himself. He was also the
first monotheist.

02:25:28.000 --> 02:25:34.720
In Akhenaten s kingdom, only the
Aten could be worshiped. Temples to Amun

02:25:34.720 --> 02:25:40.640
were eventually shut down, and all
worship of the former god was banned. The

02:25:40.640 --> 02:25:46.000
king even sent out workmen and soldiers
to all corners of Egypt, where they burst

02:25:46.000 --> 02:25:52.000
into temples with hammers and chisels,
and chipped the name of Amun off the

02:25:52.000 --> 02:25:57.160
walls. His determination to rid his
kingdom of Amun was so great that he

02:25:57.160 --> 02:26:02.840
even sent workmen climbing to the top of
the red pyramid of Sneferu to chip the

02:26:02.840 --> 02:26:09.359
name of Amun from the pyramid's topmost
capstone. To the Egyptians, used as they

02:26:09.359 --> 02:26:15.160
were to placating a whole host of deities
with prayers and offerings, this radical

02:26:15.160 --> 02:26:20.040
shift must have seemed like a
frightening and risky gamble. Many must

02:26:20.040 --> 02:26:25.399
have feared to turn their backs on their
old, trusted gods and consort with this

02:26:25.399 --> 02:26:30.479
new and untested ideology.
But the king's word was the

02:26:30.479 --> 02:26:36.439
king's word, and for the most part, they
seem to have fallen into line.

02:26:36.439 --> 02:26:42.800
At first, Akhenaten converted old
temples in Thebes to the Aten, and even

02:26:42.800 --> 02:26:47.319
began constructing some new ones, but he
soon went off the idea.

02:26:47.319 --> 02:26:52.720
Thebes' old temples were
covered with carvings and hieroglyphs

02:26:52.720 --> 02:26:58.120
praising the other gods, and the depth of
their history couldn't be erased

02:26:58.120 --> 02:27:03.800
overnight. Thebes was also home to a
powerful priestly class that resisted

02:27:03.800 --> 02:27:08.640
his reforms.
In answer to this problem, Akhenaten

02:27:08.640 --> 02:27:14.240
took the remarkable decision to build an
entirely new capital. He would build it

02:27:14.240 --> 02:27:19.359
out in the middle of the desert, at a
completely uninhabited location halfway

02:27:19.359 --> 02:27:25.920
between Memphis and Thebes. He would
call this city  the horizon of the Aten ,

02:27:25.920 --> 02:27:29.520
or in Egyptian, Akhetaten.

02:27:29.640 --> 02:27:35.200
Standing out on the bare and level
plain where he hoped to build his new

02:27:35.200 --> 02:27:41.800
city, the pharaoh Akhenaten gave the
following proclamation to his courtiers.

02:27:43.359 --> 02:27:48.800
The Aten desires that there
be made for him a monument with an

02:27:48.800 --> 02:27:55.120
eternal and everlasting name.
It is Aten, my father, who gave me

02:27:55.120 --> 02:28:00.760
counsel concerning it. No official has
ever given me counsel, not any of the

02:28:00.760 --> 02:28:06.600
people who are in the entire land.
At Akhetaten, I shall make the house

02:28:06.600 --> 02:28:08.800
of Aten.

02:28:13.240 --> 02:28:19.399
This new city would be furnished
with everything a royal capital needed;

02:28:19.399 --> 02:28:25.680
palaces for Akhenaten and his chief wife
Nefertiti, along with his four other wives,

02:28:25.680 --> 02:28:31.520
gardens, tombs, administrative buildings,
and workshops, and of course, a vast

02:28:31.520 --> 02:28:38.399
temple complex to the new god, Aten.
Construction of this city would

02:28:38.399 --> 02:28:44.200
take at least eight years, and when it was
finished, in the twelfth year of his reign,

02:28:44.200 --> 02:28:52.160
Akhenaten held a magnificent
ceremony. The year was 1342 BC.

02:28:52.160 --> 02:28:59.120
At his new capital, Akhenaten received
delegations from all over the region,

02:28:59.120 --> 02:29:04.359
from the Hittites, from Syria and islands
in the Mediterranean like Cyprus and

02:29:04.359 --> 02:29:10.800
Crete, as well as from the Nubian lands
of Punt and Kush in the south, all here

02:29:10.800 --> 02:29:16.439
to bear witness to the glory of his new
city and his successful conversion of

02:29:16.439 --> 02:29:20.720
his empire.
The priests may have grumbled,

02:29:20.720 --> 02:29:26.680
the common people may have fretted, but he
had finally done it. The ceremony must

02:29:26.680 --> 02:29:33.319
have been grand, full of celebration and
pomp, musicians and dancers, the burning

02:29:33.319 --> 02:29:39.359
of incense, and feasts of fine foods.
We can imagine the foreign guests

02:29:39.359 --> 02:29:45.840
listening to the singing of hymns like
the following to the new god, Aten.

02:29:47.359 --> 02:29:54.120
Thou didst create the world
according to thy desire; all men, cattle,

02:29:54.120 --> 02:30:00.720
and wild beasts, whatever is on Earth
going upon its feet, and what is on high,

02:30:00.720 --> 02:30:08.240
flying with its wings. The countries of
Syria and Nubia, the land of Egypt, thou

02:30:08.240 --> 02:30:13.640
settest every man in his place, thou suppliest their necessities.

02:30:13.640 --> 02:30:19.040
Their tongues are separate in speech, and their natures as well.

02:30:19.040 --> 02:30:26.017
Every one has his food, and his time of life is reckoned.

02:30:28.760 --> 02:30:35.160
But the consequences of this piece
of royal pageantry were dire. A

02:30:35.160 --> 02:30:39.760
plague had been spreading around the
Middle East for some time now, affecting

02:30:39.760 --> 02:30:44.520
lands in Syria and the Hittite Empire in
what is now Turkey.

02:30:44.520 --> 02:30:50.479
One group of texts written around
this time, known as the Hittite Plague

02:30:50.479 --> 02:30:55.960
Prayers, invoke the gods to deliver them
from this disaster.

02:30:55.960 --> 02:31:01.520
For twenty years now, people have
been dying in Hatti. Will the plague never

02:31:01.520 --> 02:31:08.080
be removed from Hatti? I cannot control
the worry in my heart. I can no longer

02:31:08.080 --> 02:31:14.479
control the anguish of my soul.
With foreign dignitaries coming

02:31:14.479 --> 02:31:19.200
from all over the region with large
entourages and doubtless groups of

02:31:19.200 --> 02:31:24.840
slaves in tow, a deadly dose of this
disease arrived that year in the heart

02:31:24.840 --> 02:31:30.800
of Egypt, and from there would have
spread all up and down the Nile. If

02:31:30.800 --> 02:31:35.479
Akhenaten had hoped that this ceremony
would secure his people's confidence in

02:31:35.479 --> 02:31:40.240
his new god, then it couldn't have
backfired more dramatically.

02:31:40.240 --> 02:31:46.640
In the pandemic that
followed, no one was safe. Numerous deaths

02:31:46.640 --> 02:31:51.120
may even have occurred within Akhenaten's
family, perhaps including his

02:31:51.120 --> 02:31:56.439
mother, his wife, and three of his
daughters. If the situation was so

02:31:56.439 --> 02:32:01.560
severe, even in the relatively protected
royal court, we can assume that in the

02:32:01.560 --> 02:32:07.080
population at large, the effects were
even more devastating. For the people of

02:32:07.080 --> 02:32:12.279
Egypt, this incomprehensible disaster
must have seemed like the judgment of

02:32:12.279 --> 02:32:18.279
the old gods on the man who had so
arrogantly turned his back on them.

02:32:18.279 --> 02:32:26.880
Akhenaten died only a few years later,
around 1335 BC, after seventeen years of

02:32:26.880 --> 02:32:32.680
rule. After his death, some members of his
family attempted to maintain the cult of

02:32:32.680 --> 02:32:37.399
the Aten in the now plague-ravaged new
capital of Akhetaten.

02:32:37.399 --> 02:32:43.120
They would take turns to rule for
the next four years, but seemingly without

02:32:43.120 --> 02:32:48.240
much success.
Now, the whole empire seemed like

02:32:48.240 --> 02:32:54.439
it was teetering on the brink of
collapse. But eventually, one of Akhenaten s

02:32:54.439 --> 02:32:59.240
sons, a boy of only eight years old,
came to the throne.

02:32:59.240 --> 02:33:05.560
His father had given him the
hopeful name Tutankh-Aten, or  living

02:33:05.560 --> 02:33:12.120
image of the Aten , but he would not rule
under it for long. Turning his back on

02:33:12.120 --> 02:33:17.439
his father's new faith and to enormous
celebration around the empire, in the

02:33:17.439 --> 02:33:22.040
third year of his rule, he changed his
name to the one we now remember him

02:33:22.040 --> 02:33:28.880
by, the living image not of Aten, but of
the old god Amun, now triumphantly

02:33:28.880 --> 02:33:44.200
welcomed back by the people of Egypt.
His name was Tutankh-Amun.

02:33:44.200 --> 02:33:51.080
As symbolized by his change of name,
the boy king Tutankh-Amun rowed back a great

02:33:51.080 --> 02:33:57.399
number of his father's attempted reforms.
He ended all worship of the god Aten,

02:33:57.399 --> 02:34:03.920
and reinstated Amun to supremacy in
Thebes. Tutankh-Amun lifted the ban on the

02:34:03.920 --> 02:34:09.479
cults of other gods, and restored the
traditional privileges of the

02:34:09.479 --> 02:34:15.200
priesthood. Many temples to the Aten in
Thebes and elsewhere were torn down, and

02:34:15.200 --> 02:34:20.800
their painted bricks were used as filler
in the walls of other temples.

02:34:20.800 --> 02:34:26.520
Everyone seemed to be in agreement; the
whole sorry business of Akhenaten was

02:34:26.520 --> 02:34:29.240
better off forgotten.

02:34:29.800 --> 02:34:35.880
Today, the boy king Tutankh-Amun
is perhaps the most famous of all the

02:34:35.880 --> 02:34:42.080
Egyptian pharaohs, more famous than the
great Khufu and Khafre of Giza, or the

02:34:42.080 --> 02:34:48.359
pharaoh's Djoser and Sneferu, who perfected
the pyramid form. He's more famous than

02:34:48.359 --> 02:34:52.600
Kamose or Ahmose,
who reunited the kingdom and expelled

02:34:52.600 --> 02:34:58.760
the Hyksos, more famous than his colorful
father Akhenaten or the great queen

02:34:58.760 --> 02:35:03.640
Hatshepsut. But there's nothing in his reign
that really warrants that level of

02:35:03.640 --> 02:35:09.720
recognition. In fact, this boy king died
while still a teenager after only nine

02:35:09.720 --> 02:35:13.880
years of rule.
He does seem to have been a good

02:35:13.880 --> 02:35:20.960
king, and popular, and set Egypt back on
course after his father's erratic reign.

02:35:20.960 --> 02:35:26.800
But the source of his fame was really
one of absolute historical

02:35:26.800 --> 02:35:34.760
accident. When he died in 1323 BC, the boy
king Tutankh-Amun was buried in a tomb in

02:35:34.760 --> 02:35:40.479
the Valley of the Kings. It was not a
particularly resplendent royal tomb, and

02:35:40.479 --> 02:35:45.720
a far cry from the glorious pyramids of
the Old Kingdom. But shortly after it was

02:35:45.720 --> 02:35:50.960
sealed, there was a chance flash flood in
this portion of the necropolis, and the

02:35:50.960 --> 02:35:58.840
doorway to the tomb was buried in sand
and rock. This left it completely

02:35:58.840 --> 02:36:04.760
concealed. For the next
3,300 years, tomb robbers would scour the

02:36:04.760 --> 02:36:10.240
Valley of the Kings, stealing from nearly
every one of the great pharaoh's tombs,

02:36:10.240 --> 02:36:15.000
making away with their treasures,
removing their mummies, and despoiling

02:36:15.000 --> 02:36:19.800
their decorations.
But buried in the sand,

02:36:19.800 --> 02:36:26.240
Tutankh-Amun s tomb remains sealed.
For this reason, it was completely untouched

02:36:26.240 --> 02:36:30.200
until the year 1922,
when it was uncovered by the

02:36:30.200 --> 02:36:35.560
Egyptologist Howard Carter, and all its
artifacts were recovered to

02:36:35.560 --> 02:36:40.120
international astonishment.
Today, the most glorious of

02:36:40.120 --> 02:36:46.000
these, the golden burial mask of Tutankh-Amun,
is one of the most famous objects

02:36:46.000 --> 02:36:51.240
from the ancient world, a resplendent
image of royal wealth and power.

02:36:51.240 --> 02:36:56.960
At times, it can be hard to
remember that this golden image is also

02:36:56.960 --> 02:37:02.720
a portrait of a boy who had power thrust
upon him in a time of upheaval and

02:37:02.720 --> 02:37:13.670
strife, looking up at us from the dark
depths of the ages.

02:37:18.520 --> 02:37:25.520
The New Kingdom of Egypt would
reach its highest point around fifty years

02:37:25.520 --> 02:37:30.439
after the reign of Tutankh-Amun.
It would come during the rule

02:37:30.439 --> 02:37:36.160
of perhaps the greatest Egyptian pharaoh.
He came to the throne under the name

02:37:36.160 --> 02:37:43.319
Ramesses II, but he would go down in history
as Ramesses the Great.

02:37:44.520 --> 02:37:51.319
Ramesses came to the throne at the
age of fourteen, in 1279 BC.

02:37:51.319 --> 02:37:57.359
At the time, Egypt's Mediterranean
coast was being ravaged by groups of

02:37:57.359 --> 02:38:02.760
pirates, and he spent much of his early
rule dealing with this nuisance. But he

02:38:02.760 --> 02:38:07.279
is most famous for pushing the
boundaries of Egypt far to the north

02:38:07.279 --> 02:38:13.160
into the region of Syria.
Over the preceding centuries, a

02:38:13.160 --> 02:38:17.800
powerful rival had grown up in the
mountains of what is today Turkey, and

02:38:17.800 --> 02:38:21.120
was steadily spreading its influence in
all directions.

02:38:21.120 --> 02:38:27.359
This was the powerful Hittite
Empire, centered on their hill fortress

02:38:27.359 --> 02:38:33.080
capital of Hattusha.
The Hittites were a relatively new

02:38:33.080 --> 02:38:37.200
power in the region, but their territory
was wealthy and extensive.

02:38:37.200 --> 02:38:42.439
They had mastered the use of
chariots in warfare, turning them from

02:38:42.439 --> 02:38:48.600
light hit-and-run vehicles into heavy,
armored shock troops. For the last

02:38:48.600 --> 02:38:53.800
two centuries, Egypt had been fighting
increasingly bitter wars with them over

02:38:53.800 --> 02:38:59.560
who would control the region of
Palestine. In the fourth year of his

02:38:59.560 --> 02:39:05.120
reign, Ramesses II gathered an
expeditionary force and marched across

02:39:05.120 --> 02:39:11.080
the Sinai Desert to Gaza, and from there
marched north.

02:39:11.080 --> 02:39:17.800
One epic poem written about this
expedition exalts in the enormous force

02:39:17.800 --> 02:39:21.359
that Ramesses brought.

02:39:21.840 --> 02:39:26.880
His Majesty journeyed northward, his
infantry and chariotry with him. He began

02:39:26.880 --> 02:39:32.279
to march on the good way. Every foreign
country was trembling before him. Their

02:39:32.279 --> 02:39:36.720
chiefs were bringing their tribute, and
all the rebels were coming, bowing down

02:39:36.720 --> 02:39:41.000
through dread of the personality of His

02:39:42.720 --> 02:39:50.000
Majesty. Ramesses' aim was to capture the
strong fortress city of Kadesh, situated

02:39:50.000 --> 02:39:53.880
along the sandy banks on a fork of the
Orontes River.

02:39:53.880 --> 02:39:58.640
For years now, Kadesh had been
playing the Hittites and Egypt off

02:39:58.640 --> 02:40:04.960
against one another, allying first with
one, then the other. Now, Ramesses was

02:40:04.960 --> 02:40:10.160
determined to finally seize Kadesh for

02:40:13.279 --> 02:40:20.640
Egypt. He marched north with four of his
divisions, named after the gods Amun, Ra,

02:40:20.640 --> 02:40:27.840
Seth, and Ptah. With him he brought thousands
of chariots, and one unit of elite

02:40:27.840 --> 02:40:33.720
chariot riders he sent by sea, telling
them to land on the coast and ride

02:40:33.720 --> 02:40:38.319
inland to meet him on the day that he
arrived at Kadesh.

02:40:38.319 --> 02:40:44.880
At first, everything seemed to be
going well. On his way, the pharaoh's

02:40:44.880 --> 02:40:50.439
scouts captured a pair of tribesmen from
the Shasu people, who told him that the

02:40:50.439 --> 02:40:55.960
Hittite king was cowering further to the
north. He was afraid of the might of

02:40:55.960 --> 02:41:04.120
Egypt, they said. He had left Kadesh
defenseless. Excited by this news, Ramesses

02:41:04.120 --> 02:41:09.040
threw all caution to the wind and
hastened northward to seize the city

02:41:09.040 --> 02:41:15.800
with only one of his four divisions, his
prided Amun troops, but this would prove

02:41:15.800 --> 02:41:20.399
to be a fatal mistake.
Ramesses didn't know it yet, but

02:41:20.399 --> 02:41:25.720
these Shasu tribesmen were actually
agents of the Hittite king sent to lure

02:41:25.720 --> 02:41:28.479
him into a trap.

02:41:29.040 --> 02:41:35.560
When he arrived at Kadesh, Ramesses set
up his camp beside a stony brook, and his

02:41:35.560 --> 02:41:41.399
scouts set out into the surrounding
landscape to detect any threats. Some of

02:41:41.399 --> 02:41:46.279
these scouts ran into a pair of Hittite
soldiers who had been lying low in the

02:41:46.279 --> 02:41:51.640
undergrowth, watching them. They
skirmished and the Egyptians managed to

02:41:51.640 --> 02:41:56.160
capture the Hittites.
After perhaps a stern beating,

02:41:56.160 --> 02:42:01.640
these men revealed what lay waiting for
the Egyptians nearby, the full might of

02:42:01.640 --> 02:42:08.479
the Hittite armies amassed in an ambush,
hidden behind the looming fortress of

02:42:08.479 --> 02:42:14.359
Kadesh. The Kadesh poem records this
imposing force.

02:42:14.399 --> 02:42:20.040
Now the wretched foe of Hatti had
come, having gathered all foreign countries

02:42:20.040 --> 02:42:25.479
to the very ends of the sea; the land of
Hatti in its entirety. They covered the

02:42:25.479 --> 02:42:28.760
mountains and the valleys like the
grasshoppers with their

02:42:28.760 --> 02:42:34.120
multitudes. He left neither silver nor
gold in his land, but despoiled it of all

02:42:34.120 --> 02:42:38.000
its possessions, and gave them to all
foreign countries to bring them with him

02:42:38.000 --> 02:42:40.240
to combat.

02:42:40.800 --> 02:42:46.880
Ramesses flew into a rage with his
generals for allowing this to happen. He

02:42:46.880 --> 02:42:52.319
had hurried ahead with his Amun division,
and now he was critically overstretched,

02:42:52.319 --> 02:42:56.880
with his reinforcements in the Ra
division still on the road.

02:42:56.880 --> 02:43:03.000
The Hittites would not allow the
Egyptians to regroup. Before the Ra

02:43:03.000 --> 02:43:09.680
division could arrive, a terrifying force
of 2,500 Hittite chariots burst out of

02:43:09.680 --> 02:43:15.800
hiding and swept across the river
plain. Hittite chariots were the tanks of

02:43:15.800 --> 02:43:21.560
their day, heavy and armored, their riders
covered in chain mail down to their

02:43:21.560 --> 02:43:27.319
toes. These chariots rolled in and
smashed into the Ra regiment, who

02:43:27.319 --> 02:43:33.080
frantically tried to form a shield wall.
The Hittites scattered this

02:43:33.080 --> 02:43:37.040
division completely, and then rounded on
the Egyptians  camp.

02:43:37.040 --> 02:43:43.760
Ramesses was surrounded, cut off from
his reinforcements and now

02:43:43.760 --> 02:43:49.960
outnumbered. But in this dire situation,
he recounts how he rallied his men and

02:43:49.960 --> 02:43:54.760
led them in a desperate charge against
the enemy.

02:43:55.120 --> 02:44:03.319
I found the 2,500 spans of
chariotry, in whose midst I was, becoming

02:44:03.319 --> 02:44:09.560
heaps of corpses before my horse. Not
one of them found his hand to fight, for

02:44:09.560 --> 02:44:15.680
their hearts quailed in their bodies
from terror of me, and all their arms

02:44:15.680 --> 02:44:24.319
were powerless so they could not shoot,
nor find their courage to seize their javelins.

02:44:24.319 --> 02:44:29.319
Whether or not this self-
aggrandizing account is an accurate

02:44:29.319 --> 02:44:34.920
depiction of that day, it's clear that
the tide did begin to turn.

02:44:34.920 --> 02:44:40.640
The Egyptian soldiers were elite
fighters, and many of the Hittite forces

02:44:40.640 --> 02:44:45.040
may have been mercenaries or
conscripts. After destroying the Ra

02:44:45.040 --> 02:44:50.439
division and sweeping into the Egyptians
camp, the chariots became bogged down, and

02:44:50.439 --> 02:44:56.040
many of the Hittite soldiers, believing the
battle to be already over, began looting

02:44:56.040 --> 02:45:01.600
rather than press their advantage.
More Egyptian reinforcements

02:45:01.600 --> 02:45:06.920
were soon arriving from the south, and as
the bloody afternoon wore on, that

02:45:06.920 --> 02:45:12.640
contingent of elite charioteers that had
been sailing up the coast also arrived

02:45:12.640 --> 02:45:17.800
on the scene.
The arrival of this cavalry on the

02:45:17.800 --> 02:45:23.160
horizon was enough to steel the resolve
of the Egyptian troops and break the

02:45:23.160 --> 02:45:25.920
will of the Hittites.

02:45:26.120 --> 02:45:32.800
Ramesses gives a florid rendition of
what happened next.

02:45:33.160 --> 02:45:38.319
I made them plunge into the water
as crocodiles plunge, for they were

02:45:38.319 --> 02:45:45.279
falling upon their faces, one on another,
as I slew among them whom I desired.

02:45:45.279 --> 02:45:50.520
Neither could one look behind him, nor
could another turn about, and whoever of

02:45:50.520 --> 02:45:54.840
them fell, he could not raise himself.

02:45:57.960 --> 02:46:03.640
The Hittite army withdrew, with
many of their soldiers pushed into the

02:46:03.640 --> 02:46:08.200
Orontes River.
When the next day dawned, the two

02:46:08.200 --> 02:46:14.399
sides clashed again, but both had been
fatally weakened by the previous days

02:46:14.399 --> 02:46:21.040
fighting. After a few hours of bloody
slaughter, Ramesses withdrew, and the Hittite

02:46:21.040 --> 02:46:26.760
king sent him a peace offer.
The pharaoh's hands were tied.

02:46:26.760 --> 02:46:32.080
The Egyptians lacked any siege
equipment to breach the strong walls of

02:46:32.080 --> 02:46:37.720
Kadesh, and the only option to take the
city would have been a lengthy siege,

02:46:37.720 --> 02:46:43.439
during which Ramesses would have found his
forces exposed to attack, poorly supplied,

02:46:43.439 --> 02:46:47.680
and prone to encirclement.
Instead, he decided to

02:46:47.680 --> 02:46:54.520
declare victory and march back to Egypt.
The Hittites in turn also declared

02:46:54.520 --> 02:47:00.359
victory, and the city of Kadesh would
slip out of Ramesses' grasp.

02:47:00.359 --> 02:47:06.120
Despite the overflowing praise of
Ramesses and his glorious victory in the

02:47:06.120 --> 02:47:12.600
Kadesh poem, the war actually ended with
a stalemate, and the question of the city

02:47:12.600 --> 02:47:16.680
remained unresolved.
But it's clear that Ramesses

02:47:16.680 --> 02:47:22.120
thought back to his role during the
battle with no small amount of pride, and

02:47:22.120 --> 02:47:26.600
he would decorate the walls of his
temple at Abu Simbel with a vast low-

02:47:26.600 --> 02:47:32.000
relief carving of every one of the
battle s twists and turns.

02:47:32.000 --> 02:47:38.000
The war with the Hittites would
drag on for a further fifteen years, and

02:47:38.000 --> 02:47:41.960
during this time, Egypt would often
capture territory along the

02:47:41.960 --> 02:47:48.359
Mediterranean coast, only to lose it
again the very next year. Before long,

02:47:48.359 --> 02:47:52.800
both sides grew weary of this
grinding conflict.

02:47:52.800 --> 02:47:57.560
The war was finally brought to
an end with what has gone down in

02:47:57.560 --> 02:48:04.200
history as the first written peace
treaty, the text of which has survived.

02:48:04.200 --> 02:48:12.240
Behold, Hattusili, the ruler of the
Hittites, binds himself by treaty to

02:48:12.240 --> 02:48:19.319
Ramesses, chosen one of Ra, the great
ruler of Egypt, beginning today, so that

02:48:19.319 --> 02:48:25.479
perfect peace and brotherhood may be
created between us forever; he being in

02:48:25.479 --> 02:48:32.120
brotherhood and peace with me, and I
being in brotherhood and peace with him

02:48:32.120 --> 02:48:37.960
forever. The treaty was written on silver
tablets, with both the Hittites and the

02:48:37.960 --> 02:48:44.040
Egyptians being given a copy. Its text
was written in both hieroglyphics and

02:48:44.040 --> 02:48:49.080
Hittite cuneiform, but the two
translations do have slightly different

02:48:49.080 --> 02:48:54.560
wordings. In a diplomatic stroke of
genius, the Egyptian version claims that

02:48:54.560 --> 02:48:59.720
the Hittites had come begging Egypt for
peace, which the Egyptians graciously

02:48:59.720 --> 02:49:05.399
accepted, while in the Hittite version, it
is the Egyptians who asked to end the

02:49:05.399 --> 02:49:11.240
war. With both sides thus able to save
face, the destructive conflict was

02:49:11.240 --> 02:49:17.239
allowed to come to an end, and nearly a
century of relative peace

02:49:17.239 --> 02:49:23.080
ensued. Despite the the pride Ramesses took
in his battles, today it is this peace

02:49:23.080 --> 02:49:28.680
treaty that we most remember, and a
replica of it hangs on the walls of the

02:49:28.680 --> 02:49:33.160
United Nations headquarters in New

02:49:35.319 --> 02:49:41.319
York. After what seemed like a lucky
escape at Kadesh, Ramesses would turn his

02:49:41.319 --> 02:49:47.319
attention away from war and towards
construction. He spent the next decades

02:49:47.319 --> 02:49:53.279
of his rule building temples and
monuments up and down Egypt, and today,

02:49:53.279 --> 02:49:58.120
his name is the one that appears on the
most surviving monuments of any

02:49:58.120 --> 02:50:03.760
pharaoh. This is partly due to his
prolific building campaign, but also due

02:50:03.760 --> 02:50:09.000
to the fact that he ensured his name was
inscribed more deeply in the stone than

02:50:09.000 --> 02:50:14.920
any other pharaoh, so deep that it could
never be erased.

02:50:15.200 --> 02:50:22.120
Ramesses II would rule for a total of
sixty-six years, and would be remembered as

02:50:22.120 --> 02:50:29.800
perhaps Egypt's greatest pharaoh. His
full Egyptian name was Usermaatre Setepenre

02:50:29.800 --> 02:50:35.760
Ramesses, which the Greeks would later
render into a name they found easier to

02:50:35.760 --> 02:50:42.479
pronounce; they would call him Ozymandias.
More than a thousand years later,

02:50:42.479 --> 02:50:47.920
the Greek writer Diodorus of Sicily
would visit Egypt and write an account

02:50:47.920 --> 02:50:53.600
of visiting one monument to Ramesses II.

02:50:53.600 --> 02:50:59.760
At its entrance, there is a pylon
constructed of variegated stone two

02:50:59.760 --> 02:51:06.880
plethora in breadth and forty-five cubits high.
The inscription upon it runs,  King of

02:51:06.880 --> 02:51:12.439
kings am I, Ozymandias.
If anyone would know how great I

02:51:12.439 --> 02:51:20.160
am and where I lie, let him surpass one
of my works.

02:51:20.160 --> 02:51:25.479
Ramesses would also build a new capital for
his empire, and with his military

02:51:25.479 --> 02:51:31.040
ambitions lying in the north, he decided
to place it in the northeast of the Nile

02:51:31.040 --> 02:51:38.200
Delta, and in characteristic fashion, he
named it after himself, calling it

02:51:38.200 --> 02:51:45.720
Per-Ramesses, or  the house of
Ramesses . One Egyptian poem would celebrate

02:51:45.720 --> 02:51:50.520
the beauty of this new city.

02:51:51.359 --> 02:51:56.800
The residence is pleasant in life; its
field is full of everything good. It is

02:51:56.800 --> 02:52:02.960
full of supplies and food every day, its
ponds with fish and its lakes with birds.

02:52:02.960 --> 02:52:08.160
Its meadows are verdant with grass, its
banks bear dates, its melons are abundant

02:52:08.160 --> 02:52:12.760
on the sands. Its granaries are so full
of barley and emmer wheat that they come

02:52:12.760 --> 02:52:18.200
near to the sky; red wedj fish swim in
the canal of the resident city, which

02:52:18.200 --> 02:52:25.200
live on lotus flowers.
This city of Per-Ramesses has long

02:52:25.200 --> 02:52:31.840
been associated with the city of Ramesses,
referred to in the Hebrew Book of Exodus,

02:52:31.840 --> 02:52:38.399
the second book of the Hebrew
Bible. Exodus describes a population of

02:52:38.399 --> 02:52:43.160
enslaved Hebrews forced to work on the
construction of the city.

02:52:43.160 --> 02:52:49.760
The reality of the Exodus story has
long been debated, and most historians

02:52:49.760 --> 02:52:55.720
now consider it to be a piece of ancient
literature. There is no evidence for a

02:52:55.720 --> 02:53:01.560
large population of Hebrew slaves ever
living in Egypt, or that the city of Per-

02:53:01.560 --> 02:53:07.760
Ramesses was built by slaves at all. More
likely, it was built using the Egyptians

02:53:07.760 --> 02:53:13.319
usual combination of skilled artisans
and seasonal peasant laborers.

02:53:13.319 --> 02:53:19.399
But with the proximity of the
Nile Delta to the Levantine coast, it's

02:53:19.399 --> 02:53:24.479
certainly not impossible that some of
these laborers were Hebrew people who

02:53:24.479 --> 02:53:28.279
had traveled across the Sinai to sell
their labor in Egypt.

02:53:28.279 --> 02:53:33.319
If that were the case, then for one
reason or another, they left no

02:53:33.319 --> 02:53:39.600
impression in the archaeological record,
but perhaps printed an indelible mark on

02:53:39.600 --> 02:53:42.680
our collective imaginations.

02:53:44.040 --> 02:53:52.399
When Ramesses finally died in 1213 BC,
he was probably nearly ninety years

02:53:52.399 --> 02:53:59.040
old. His reign had been one of Egypt's
golden ages, but his long rule had once

02:53:59.040 --> 02:54:06.840
again created that old king problem; all
of his heirs were now also old men. By

02:54:06.840 --> 02:54:13.120
the time of his death, twelve of his oldest
sons had already died, and now his

02:54:13.120 --> 02:54:19.800
thirteenth son took the throne at the age
of about seventy. He was the pharaoh

02:54:19.800 --> 02:54:25.880
Merneptah. But only a few years into this
man's reign, Egypt was attacked by a

02:54:25.880 --> 02:54:30.640
devastating new enemy.
These were the Libyan people to

02:54:30.640 --> 02:54:36.479
the west of the Nile Delta.
The king of Libya, a man named

02:54:36.479 --> 02:54:42.640
Meryey, had seemingly planned his attack
for some time. All of a sudden, a large

02:54:42.640 --> 02:54:47.600
Libyan army flooded through Egypt's
northwestern border, and they were

02:54:47.600 --> 02:54:53.479
reinforced with groups of people from
all over the Mediterranean, perhaps from

02:54:53.479 --> 02:54:59.880
Greece, Sardinia, Sicily, and elsewhere
across the sea. These were a diverse

02:54:59.880 --> 02:55:05.160
group of peoples that had suddenly begun
to appear in increasing numbers across

02:55:05.160 --> 02:55:09.200
the Eastern Mediterranean.
They would later become

02:55:09.200 --> 02:55:16.000
known as the sea peoples.
The pharaoh Merneptah remembers

02:55:16.000 --> 02:55:20.319
this event on one carved stelae.

02:55:20.640 --> 02:55:26.439
The wretched fallen chief of Libya, Meryre,
son of Ded, has fallen upon the country

02:55:26.439 --> 02:55:34.840
of Tehenu with his bowmen; Sherden, Shekelesh,
Ekwesh, Lukka, Teresh, taking the best of every

02:55:34.840 --> 02:55:40.800
warrior and every man of war of his
country. He has brought his wife and his

02:55:40.800 --> 02:55:45.920
children; leaders of the camp, and he has
reached the western boundary in the

02:55:45.920 --> 02:55:50.239
fields of Perire.

02:55:50.800 --> 02:55:57.120
The pharaoh Merneptah defeated this invasion,
and as a warning to any others who would

02:55:57.120 --> 02:56:03.439
try such a surprise attack, he had many
of the invading soldiers impaled along

02:56:03.439 --> 02:56:09.960
the road into Memphis.
The princes are prostrate, saying,

02:56:09.960 --> 02:56:16.800
Mercy!  Not one raises his head among
the nine bows. Desolation is for Tehenu;

02:56:16.800 --> 02:56:23.359
Hatti is pacified; plundered is the Canaan
with every evil. Hurra is become a widow.

02:56:23.359 --> 02:56:28.760
All lands together, they are pacified.

02:56:29.800 --> 02:56:36.040
But these lands would not stay
pacified for long.

02:56:45.080 --> 02:56:52.520
After the death of the pharaoh
Merneptah around 1204 BC, Egypt entered a

02:56:52.520 --> 02:56:58.279
period of civil strife, with the
descendants of Ramesses fighting over who

02:56:58.279 --> 02:57:03.080
would take the crown.
Against this backdrop, the entire

02:57:03.080 --> 02:57:09.160
region also once again began to
experience a series of record

02:57:09.160 --> 02:57:13.040
droughts. What caused this climate
shift is uncertain.

02:57:13.040 --> 02:57:18.439
As we saw in our second
episode on the Bronze Age collapse, the cause

02:57:18.439 --> 02:57:23.319
may have been volcanic, with a large
eruption taking place in the Icelandic

02:57:23.319 --> 02:57:29.800
volcano of Hekla around this time. Others
have proposed that an eruption in Sicily

02:57:29.800 --> 02:57:37.439
around 1300 BC may have been to blame, or
that the super volcano Thera in Santorini

02:57:37.439 --> 02:57:43.760
may have resumed some activity some five
hundred years after its last enormous

02:57:43.760 --> 02:57:48.720
eruption. The cause may not have been
volcanic at all, and could have been due

02:57:48.720 --> 02:57:54.520
to variations in the sun's activity or
weather systems in the Atlantic,

02:57:54.520 --> 02:58:01.000
depriving the Mediterranean of moisture.
The reality was much as it is today; the

02:58:01.000 --> 02:58:06.960
planet's climate system is fragile,
interconnected, and chaotic, and even

02:58:06.960 --> 02:58:11.920
relatively small changes in its
equilibrium can have devastating

02:58:11.920 --> 02:58:18.399
effects. During this time, formerly green
lands became dry and arid, and more

02:58:18.399 --> 02:58:24.319
plants suited to desert landscapes
flourished. Analysis of sediment cores

02:58:24.319 --> 02:58:30.239
and oxygen isotopes in cave mineral
deposits have all shown that the 13th

02:58:30.239 --> 02:58:35.680
and 12th centuries BC saw much less rain
than the preceding

02:58:35.680 --> 02:58:40.800
centuries. Alongside this scientific
evidence, we can see marks of severe

02:58:40.800 --> 02:58:45.080
drought in the region's written records,

02:58:45.200 --> 02:58:51.399
too. Egypt's great rivals, the Hittites, in
their stony mountains, were hit

02:58:51.399 --> 02:58:56.279
particularly hard by the
drought. One Hittite text has come down

02:58:56.279 --> 02:59:02.120
to us that seems to capture the spirit
of this age, and it is known as the myth

02:59:02.120 --> 02:59:05.880
of Telepinu.
It comes from a poetic

02:59:05.880 --> 02:59:12.520
convention known as  the vanishing god
myth, which describes how a certain deity

02:59:12.520 --> 02:59:17.319
is so offended by the misdeeds of
humanity that he flies into a fit of

02:59:17.319 --> 02:59:23.399
sorrow and abandons his
duties. Telepinu was a god of farming,

02:59:23.399 --> 02:59:28.720
fertility, and the weather. The beginning
of the text has been lost, so we don't

02:59:28.720 --> 02:59:34.840
know what it was humanity did to provoke
his rage, but the poem describes its

02:59:34.840 --> 02:59:37.319
deadly consequences.

02:59:38.399 --> 02:59:44.920
Thereupon, soot beset the windows;
smoke beset the house. The ashes

02:59:44.920 --> 02:59:51.680
lay crammed on the hearth. Off stalked
Telepinu. Grain and abundance he

02:59:51.680 --> 02:59:56.239
took away from field and meadow.
Off to the copses stalked Telepinu,

02:59:56.239 --> 03:00:02.960
and in a copse he buried
himself. Forthwith, the seed ceased to

03:00:02.960 --> 03:00:10.000
yield produce; oxen, sheep, and men ceased
to breed, while even those that had

03:00:10.000 --> 03:00:16.560
conceived did not bear.
Hillsides were bare; trees were bare

03:00:16.560 --> 03:00:22.680
and put forth no new branches.
Pastures were bare; springs ran dry.

03:00:22.680 --> 03:00:31.840
A famine arose in the land; men and gods
alike were about to perish of hunger.

03:00:32.359 --> 03:00:37.399
While the Egyptians may have
celebrated this weakening of their great

03:00:37.399 --> 03:00:44.040
rival, in Egypt, the situation was hardly
any better. One text dated to around the

03:00:44.040 --> 03:00:51.800
year 1200 BC is called the Lament to Amun,
and it stands as a wail of sorrow

03:00:51.800 --> 03:00:55.160
in a darkening age.

03:00:55.160 --> 03:01:00.760
Come to me, father Amun, protect me
in this bitter year of

03:01:00.760 --> 03:01:06.520
confrontation. God shines in the sun, yet
he will not shine. Winter crowds hard

03:01:06.520 --> 03:01:13.479
upon summer; months happen backwards;
disheveled hours lurch drunken by. Those

03:01:13.479 --> 03:01:18.080
cut down in high places cry out to you,
Amun; these words came on the the

03:01:18.080 --> 03:01:23.200
poisoned air, spoken by herdsmen in
fields and marshes, by those who beat

03:01:23.200 --> 03:01:27.399
clothes on the banks of the river, by
district police deserting their

03:01:27.399 --> 03:01:32.160
precincts, by horned beasts on our
burning deserts.

03:01:34.840 --> 03:01:41.040
From this period of unrest and
the chaos in Egypt's royal court, which

03:01:41.040 --> 03:01:47.000
lasted for about a century, a military
strongman named Setnakhte would eventually

03:01:47.000 --> 03:01:52.359
rise to power.
He would rule for only three years before

03:01:52.359 --> 03:01:55.640
dying and passing the throne on to his
young son. This boy

03:01:55.640 --> 03:02:02.720
was the empire's last hope
to turn around its floundering fortunes,

03:02:02.720 --> 03:02:07.120
and if such a hope was to be sustained,
there was only one name he could

03:02:07.120 --> 03:02:11.560
possibly rule under.
His parents would name him after

03:02:11.560 --> 03:02:17.000
his great predecessor, who had ruled
nearly a century before and fought at

03:02:17.000 --> 03:02:27.120
the battle of Kadesh. And so, this boy would
rule as Ramesses III.

03:02:32.000 --> 03:02:38.760
This new boy king Ramesses was a
determined and tenacious ruler, and it's

03:02:38.760 --> 03:02:44.319
clear that he openly admired and sought
to emulate the legendary pharaoh of

03:02:44.319 --> 03:02:50.399
old. He even went so far as to name
all his own sons after the sons of

03:02:50.399 --> 03:02:55.840
Ramesses II, and also gave them all the
same positions in his court.

03:02:55.840 --> 03:03:01.040
It was clear he wanted to do
everything he could to recreate the

03:03:01.040 --> 03:03:06.160
glory days that had slipped out of
Egypt's grasp, as he writes in one of

03:03:06.160 --> 03:03:11.960
his inscriptions.
Rejoice ye, O Egypt, to the

03:03:11.960 --> 03:03:18.160
height of heaven, for I am ruler of the
south and north upon the throne of Atum.

03:03:18.160 --> 03:03:24.120
The gods have appointed me to be king
over Egypt, to be victor, to expel them

03:03:24.120 --> 03:03:30.239
for her from the countries; they decreed
to me the kingdom while I was a child,

03:03:30.239 --> 03:03:34.640
and my reign is full of plenty.

03:03:36.279 --> 03:03:42.560
Under other circumstances, Ramesses
might have been one of Egypt's great

03:03:42.560 --> 03:03:49.640
rulers, but the entire region was soon to
be convulsed in a series of bitter

03:03:49.640 --> 03:03:54.800
wars. One of the great drivers of these
conflicts was the loose collection of

03:03:54.800 --> 03:04:00.239
peoples that had first appeared in the
reign of the pharaoh Merneptah, and who are

03:04:00.239 --> 03:04:03.680
known as the sea peoples.

03:04:04.279 --> 03:04:09.399
These invaders were now
descending on the entire region in ever-

03:04:09.399 --> 03:04:15.080
greater numbers, apparently spurred by
widespread crop failures in Northern and

03:04:15.080 --> 03:04:22.000
Western Europe. Already, powerful trading
cities like the port town of Ugarit had

03:04:22.000 --> 03:04:27.000
been attacked by sea, seemingly by
complete surprise, and they were

03:04:27.000 --> 03:04:31.760
destroyed so thoroughly that they were
never reoccupied.

03:04:31.760 --> 03:04:37.960
The Egyptians  great rivals, the Hittites,
were now on the brink of collapse, as

03:04:37.960 --> 03:04:42.000
trade networks around the region went
into freefall.

03:04:42.000 --> 03:04:47.880
Ramesses remembers this time of
strife as these northern Invaders

03:04:47.880 --> 03:04:50.800
descended on the coast.

03:04:53.399 --> 03:04:59.359
The northerners in their isles were
disturbed, swept away in battle. Not one

03:04:59.359 --> 03:05:07.399
stood before their lands; from Kheta,
Carchemish, Arvad, Alasa, they were wasted.

03:05:07.399 --> 03:05:13.880
They set up a camp in one place in Amor.
They desolated his people and his land like

03:05:13.880 --> 03:05:16.560
that which is not.

03:05:18.279 --> 03:05:23.560
When news of the sea people's attacks
came to Ramesses, he would have been pharaoh

03:05:23.560 --> 03:05:29.000
for about eight years. He had already
repelled two further invasions from

03:05:29.000 --> 03:05:35.840
Libya and must have been rising in
confidence. But the news troubled him, and

03:05:35.840 --> 03:05:41.439
soon he got word that the fleet of the sea
peoples was on the move and were heading

03:05:41.439 --> 03:05:51.629
to Egypt, as he recounts in the inscription
on his mortuary temple at Medinet Habu.

03:05:52.279 --> 03:05:58.880
They came with fire prepared before
them, forward to Egypt. Their main support

03:05:58.880 --> 03:06:07.640
was Peleset, Thekel, Shekelesh, Denyen, and
Weshesh. Their lands were united, and they laid

03:06:07.640 --> 03:06:12.920
their hands upon the land as far as the
Circle of the Earth. Their hearts were

03:06:12.920 --> 03:06:16.520
confident, full of their plans.

03:06:18.239 --> 03:06:23.160
Ramesses knew that these attackers would
have to be stopped, and he decided that

03:06:23.160 --> 03:06:28.560
he would make his stand at the mouth of
the Nile, the lush, fertile

03:06:28.560 --> 03:06:33.720
delta. He would have to play to what
strengths the Egyptian army still had in

03:06:33.720 --> 03:06:38.640
this challenging terrain.
He decided to lay an ambush and

03:06:38.640 --> 03:06:43.359
give the sea peoples a surprise attack
of their own.

03:06:44.800 --> 03:06:51.600
Now, it happened through this god, the
lord of gods, that I was prepared and

03:06:51.600 --> 03:06:58.600
armed to trap them like wild fowl. I
equipped my frontier at Zahi, prepared

03:06:58.600 --> 03:07:05.279
before them. The chiefs, the captains of
infantry, the nobles, I caused to equip

03:07:05.279 --> 03:07:11.439
the harbor-mouths like a strong wall,
with warships, galleys, and barges.

03:07:11.439 --> 03:07:17.000
They were manned completely from
bow to stern with valiant warriors

03:07:17.000 --> 03:07:22.760
bearing their arms, soldiers of all the
choicest of Egypt, being like lions

03:07:22.760 --> 03:07:27.720
roaring upon the mountaintops. Their
horses were quivering in their every

03:07:27.720 --> 03:07:32.920
limb, ready to crush the countries under
their feet.

03:07:33.680 --> 03:07:40.600
As the enemy's ships amassed, Ramesses
gathered archers on the banks, supported

03:07:40.600 --> 03:07:46.760
by spearmen and cavalry in their
thousands, all concealed in the reeds. The

03:07:46.760 --> 03:07:52.080
tension must must have been tremendous,
all the soldiers of the Egyptian army

03:07:52.080 --> 03:07:56.600
holding their breath and waiting for
that first sign of an enemy

03:07:56.600 --> 03:08:03.680
ship. Then at last, a sail was
sighted. After that came another and

03:08:03.680 --> 03:08:10.080
another, until the whole fleet of the sea
peoples was in sight. The Egyptians must

03:08:10.080 --> 03:08:15.760
have been able to hear the creak of
10,000 oars, the beating of the drums, the

03:08:15.760 --> 03:08:22.359
shouts of the helmsmen and soldiers.
Then, once the sea people's ships

03:08:22.359 --> 03:08:28.640
were within range, Ramesses
struck. Arrows flew out of the reeds and

03:08:28.640 --> 03:08:34.200
rained down on the ships.
Panicked, the invaders attempted to

03:08:34.200 --> 03:08:38.720
land on the banks, but as they did, the
Egyptian spearmen appeared out of the

03:08:38.720 --> 03:08:45.000
treeline and met them with a shield
wall. While the enemy was held at bay, the

03:08:45.000 --> 03:08:49.439
Egyptian navy sailed in down the river.

03:08:49.960 --> 03:08:54.479
Those who reached my boundary, their
heart and their soul are finished

03:08:54.479 --> 03:09:00.600
forever and ever. As for those who had
assembled before them on the sea, the

03:09:00.600 --> 03:09:06.800
full flame was in their front, before the
harbor-mouths, and a wall of metal upon

03:09:06.800 --> 03:09:13.239
the shore surrounded them. They were
dragged, overturned, and laid low upon the

03:09:13.239 --> 03:09:19.160
beach; slain, and made heaps from stern to
bow of their galleys, while all their

03:09:19.160 --> 03:09:24.680
things were cast upon the water.
Thus, I turned back the waters to

03:09:24.680 --> 03:09:31.239
remember Egypt, and when they even
mention my name in their land, may it

03:09:31.239 --> 03:09:38.560
consume them with fear.
The pharaoh's plan had worked. The

03:09:38.560 --> 03:09:43.439
Egyptians were the first people to turn
back these sea-going invaders and stop their

03:09:43.439 --> 03:09:48.439
campaign of destruction.
Ramesses  inscription at Medinet Habu

03:09:48.439 --> 03:09:53.359
ends on the following triumphant note.

03:09:55.680 --> 03:10:03.399
Rejoice ye, O Egypt; I have expelled
your mourning which was in your heart,

03:10:03.399 --> 03:10:11.840
and I have made you dwell in peace. Those
whom I have overthrown shall not return.

03:10:14.720 --> 03:10:20.880
But despite their victory, the
land of the pharaohs now stood alone in

03:10:20.880 --> 03:10:25.439
a devastated region.
Virtually every other society

03:10:25.439 --> 03:10:31.359
around them had been gutted and reduced
to ash. Numerous long-established

03:10:31.359 --> 03:10:37.200
civilizations, the Mycenaean Greeks,
the Hittites, Ugarit, and Babylon had

03:10:37.200 --> 03:10:43.200
collapsed, and civil order had given way
to chaos. The precarious trade routes on

03:10:43.200 --> 03:10:47.720
which they had all relied to supply them
with bronze and other commodities were

03:10:47.720 --> 03:10:53.840
now broken, and Egypt's economy went
into a steep and unstoppable decline.

03:10:53.840 --> 03:10:59.640
By the end of this period, which has
become known as the Late Bronze Age

03:10:59.640 --> 03:11:04.279
collapse, Egypt was a shadow of its
former self. As other

03:11:04.279 --> 03:11:11.000
enemies encroached on its
borders, Egypt was able to fight them off,

03:11:11.000 --> 03:11:16.040
but its treasury became so depleted that
it never fully recovered its imperial

03:11:16.040 --> 03:11:21.279
power. The first workers  strike in
recorded history happened during the

03:11:21.279 --> 03:11:26.800
29th year of Ramesses III's reign, when
Egypt could no longer provide food

03:11:26.800 --> 03:11:32.120
rations for its elite artisans who were
constructing the king's tomb in the

03:11:32.120 --> 03:11:38.399
village of Deir el-Medina. The lack of
rations went on so long that the workers

03:11:38.399 --> 03:11:43.359
eventually marched through the town
shouting the following chant.

03:11:43.359 --> 03:11:48.760
We're hungry. There's no more
clothing, no more oil, no more fish, no

03:11:48.760 --> 03:11:56.160
more vegetables. Send word to the
pharaoh. If food was not reaching these

03:11:56.160 --> 03:12:02.359
crucial workers, we can only imagine the
dire situation in the wider kingdom. The

03:12:02.359 --> 03:12:07.239
dispute dragged on for weeks, with one
leader of the protest even threatening

03:12:07.239 --> 03:12:12.680
to damage a royal monument if they were
not paid. If was a threat that they would

03:12:12.680 --> 03:12:16.920
never have dared to make unless the
authority of the pharaoh was beginning

03:12:16.920 --> 03:12:20.239
to be seriously undermined.

03:12:26.560 --> 03:12:32.239
Ramesses III ruled for another
two decades after his battle with the

03:12:32.239 --> 03:12:40.160
sea peoples, for a total reign of thirty-one
years, but by the year 1156 BC, some

03:12:40.160 --> 03:12:44.960
members of his family were beginning to
get impatient.

03:12:45.160 --> 03:12:51.520
In the Egyptian court, all of
the women, the king's wives and mother

03:12:51.520 --> 03:12:57.520
and other consorts, all lived together in
a large palace complex with its own

03:12:57.520 --> 03:13:04.040
land. This was convenient for the king,
but it could also encourage courtly

03:13:04.040 --> 03:13:09.960
intrigue. There was a strict hierarchy to
the pharaoh's queens, and everyone knew

03:13:09.960 --> 03:13:15.920
that the children of his main wife were
to be his heirs before any others. Some

03:13:15.920 --> 03:13:20.800
of the women who were lower down on this
ladder could at times resort to plotting

03:13:20.800 --> 03:13:26.920
to improve their stations, and perhaps
get their own sons on the throne

03:13:26.920 --> 03:13:32.560
instead. One of these women was a queen
named Tiye. Tiye was a secondary

03:13:32.760 --> 03:13:40.760
wife of Ramesses, and
her son Pentawer was not in line for the

03:13:40.760 --> 03:13:46.439
throne. In order to remedy this situation,
she began a plot that would go down in

03:13:46.439 --> 03:13:52.439
history as the harem conspiracy.
Soon, she brought in other

03:13:52.439 --> 03:13:58.000
members of the king's household and even
high ranking members of the government,

03:13:58.000 --> 03:14:04.800
as one later papyrus records.
They are the abomination of the

03:14:04.800 --> 03:14:10.800
land. The great criminal, who was then
chief of the chamber, was in collusion

03:14:10.800 --> 03:14:18.279
with Tiye and the women of the harem. He had
made common cause with them; he had begun

03:14:18.279 --> 03:14:22.680
to bring out their words to their
mothers and their brothers who were

03:14:22.680 --> 03:14:31.439
there, saying,  Stir up the people! Incite
rebellion against their lord!

03:14:31.800 --> 03:14:37.680
Alarmingly, one of the palace women
had written to her brother named Khaem-waset,

03:14:37.680 --> 03:14:43.200
a commander of Nubian troops in
the south, and gained his support for

03:14:43.200 --> 03:14:49.279
their plot. Others had even turned to
supernatural methods, making wax

03:14:49.279 --> 03:14:56.080
effigies of the king's bodyguards and
laying curses on them to help their

03:14:56.080 --> 03:15:02.720
scheme. Their plan was clear; to kill
Ramesses and install Queen Tiye's son

03:15:02.720 --> 03:15:08.080
Pentawer as pharaoh.
The date they chose to strike was

03:15:08.080 --> 03:15:13.439
during the annual ceremony known as
the Beautiful Festival of the Valley,

03:15:13.439 --> 03:15:18.760
which was held in Thebes every year at
the new moon of the second month of the

03:15:18.760 --> 03:15:24.040
harvesting season of Shemu.
During this festival, which was one

03:15:24.040 --> 03:15:28.239
of the biggest of the year, the pharaoh
would go down to the river in a grand

03:15:28.239 --> 03:15:33.680
and colorful procession, carrying the
statues of the three gods of Thebes;

03:15:33.680 --> 03:15:39.640
Amun, Mut, and Khonsu. He would then board
his royal barge and sail with the

03:15:39.640 --> 03:15:45.560
statues down to the Theban necropolis to
visit his grand temple, as one

03:15:45.560 --> 03:15:50.080
inscription by a Theban priest describes.

03:15:50.080 --> 03:15:55.319
We go giving praise to Amun,
kissing the ground before the Lords of

03:15:55.319 --> 03:16:00.439
the Gods on his festivals, the first day
of Shemu shining, on the day of voyaging

03:16:00.439 --> 03:16:04.160
to the valley.
Here, the citizens would give

03:16:04.160 --> 03:16:09.720
offerings of food and drink and flowers,
as the boats sailed on the river with

03:16:09.720 --> 03:16:14.439
three statues.
As the riotous, days-long

03:16:14.439 --> 03:16:18.920
festival progressed, the plotters took
advantage of the disruption to make

03:16:18.920 --> 03:16:25.080
a strike at the king.
It was day fifteen of Shemu, when the

03:16:25.080 --> 03:16:31.080
pharaoh was relaxing in the royal harem
in the Western Tower of Medinet-Habu,

03:16:31.080 --> 03:16:36.399
perhaps thinking ahead to his role in
the coming festivities, when a group of

03:16:36.399 --> 03:16:40.960
assassins crept up on him with knives.

03:16:43.000 --> 03:16:50.560
Their attack was swift and brutal.
Modern scanning of Ramesses III's mummy

03:16:50.560 --> 03:16:55.680
reveals that his throat was cut right to
the bone with a sharp weapon, severing

03:16:55.680 --> 03:17:02.560
the trachea, esophagus, and major blood
vessels. Death would have followed within

03:17:02.560 --> 03:17:08.920
seconds. Ramesses has no defensive wounds,
suggesting that he was caught completely

03:17:08.920 --> 03:17:15.680
unawares, but curiously, his big toe was
severed at the time of the attack.

03:17:15.680 --> 03:17:20.920
This seems like an unlikely injury to
sustain during a struggle, and studies of

03:17:20.920 --> 03:17:25.680
his mummy have shown that the embalmers
fashioned him a prosthetic toe to take

03:17:25.680 --> 03:17:30.840
with him into the afterlife. This
suggests that the original toe was never

03:17:30.840 --> 03:17:35.560
recovered, perhaps indicating that
someone took it as proof that he was

03:17:35.560 --> 03:17:42.720
dead, or as a grizzly trophy.
Ramesses III had saved Egypt from

03:17:42.720 --> 03:17:49.520
the sea peoples, but now he lay dying in
a pool of of his own blood, betrayed by

03:17:49.520 --> 03:17:54.359
his own family.
But the conspirator s plot would

03:17:54.359 --> 03:18:00.160
not go as planned. In the aftermath of
the bloody assassination, the son of

03:18:00.160 --> 03:18:06.160
Ramesses III was able to crush the coup
and seize the throne. The plotters were

03:18:06.160 --> 03:18:11.279
all put on trial, as well as any who had
heard about the conspiracy but failed to

03:18:11.279 --> 03:18:18.399
report it. In all, twenty-eight people were
executed, and as a final punishment, they

03:18:18.399 --> 03:18:23.160
were even cruelly renamed after their
deaths. The brother of one of the

03:18:23.160 --> 03:18:28.560
plotters, who had commanded his Nubian
troops in the south, was originally named

03:18:28.560 --> 03:18:35.680
Khaemwaset, a name which meant  came from
Thebes , but after his execution he was

03:18:35.680 --> 03:18:44.399
renamed Binemwaset, or  evil in Thebes .
Another's name, Meryra, meant  beloved of

03:18:44.399 --> 03:18:54.080
Ra , but he was given the somewhat spiteful
new name Mesedsura, or  Ra hates him .

03:18:54.080 --> 03:19:00.279
Although order had been restored to
the royal succession, Egypt was in a much

03:19:00.279 --> 03:19:07.080
reduced state. The death of Ramesses was
followed by years of bickering among his

03:19:07.080 --> 03:19:12.960
heirs. Three of his sons would become
king at different times, each feeling the

03:19:12.960 --> 03:19:18.399
need to memorialize him and shore up
their own legit legitimacy by reigning

03:19:18.399 --> 03:19:25.319
as Ramesses IV, VI, and VIII.
In fact, the next eight pharaohs in a

03:19:25.319 --> 03:19:32.600
row would all be named Ramesses after the
slain king, but many of these rulers were

03:19:32.600 --> 03:19:37.840
ineffectual and reigned for only a
few years each.

03:19:37.840 --> 03:19:44.840
Meanwhile, Egypt was increasingly
beset by continuing droughts, lack of

03:19:44.840 --> 03:19:51.920
seasonal floodwaters, famines, civil
unrest, and official corruption.

03:19:55.479 --> 03:20:02.000
Against this backdrop, by the
rule of Ramesses XI, a new power had

03:20:02.000 --> 03:20:08.960
begun to fill the vacuum left by royal
authority. These were the high priests of

03:20:08.960 --> 03:20:15.479
Amun in Thebes.

03:20:15.479 --> 03:20:22.080
This priesthood had become not
only very powerful, but exceedingly

03:20:22.080 --> 03:20:28.120
wealthy. Through a centuries-long game of
acquisition, the Amun priests now

03:20:28.120 --> 03:20:35.720
controlled two-thirds of all the temple lands
in Egypt and ninety percent of all Egypt's

03:20:35.720 --> 03:20:41.800
ships, along with mountains of gold.
On top of that, they were the chief

03:20:41.800 --> 03:20:47.880
prophets and interpreters of the god
Amun-Ra's will, wielding a great deal of

03:20:47.880 --> 03:20:53.600
influence over the kings and their
decisions. Over the last centuries, they

03:20:53.600 --> 03:20:57.720
had changed the rules of the priesthood
so that they could pass their positions

03:20:57.720 --> 03:21:03.680
on to their sons, essentially becoming a
kind of feudal royalty in the baking-hot

03:21:03.680 --> 03:21:11.080
lands of Upper Egypt. One inscription on
the tomb of a high priest named

03:21:11.080 --> 03:21:15.560
Nebwenenef describes the power of
this new hereditary role.

03:21:15.560 --> 03:21:21.720
You are now high priest of Amun. His
treasury and his granary are under your

03:21:21.720 --> 03:21:26.720
seal. You are chief executive of his
temple, and every foundation of his is

03:21:26.720 --> 03:21:31.000
under your authority.
The House of Hathor, Lady of

03:21:31.000 --> 03:21:36.199
Dendera, shall now be under the authority
of your son, as heir to the offices of

03:21:36.199 --> 03:21:40.960
your forefathers, the position which you
have occupied hitherto.

03:21:40.960 --> 03:21:47.000
Soon, the high priests in
Thebes became the de facto rulers of Upper

03:21:47.000 --> 03:21:53.040
Egypt, even having themselves buried in
grand tombs and commanding their own

03:21:53.040 --> 03:21:58.640
armies. In many ways, the pharaoh had
become something of an

03:21:58.640 --> 03:22:04.160
irrelevance, and perhaps for that reason,
there would not be a Ramesses XII.

03:22:04.160 --> 03:22:09.880
With the death of Ramesses XI,
the Egyptian New Kingdom finally

03:22:09.880 --> 03:22:16.239
fractured less than eighty years after the
victorious battle with the sea peoples.

03:22:16.239 --> 03:22:21.439
Egypt would never regain its former power.

03:22:34.359 --> 03:22:40.760
For the next four centuries,
Egypt's influence would undergo a

03:22:40.760 --> 03:22:46.040
steady but unstoppable
decline. One text written around this

03:22:46.040 --> 03:22:52.840
time is called the Tale of Wenamun. It
describes an Egyptian diplomat who

03:22:52.840 --> 03:22:57.399
travels to the north to collect some
cedar wood as tribute from the

03:22:57.399 --> 03:23:03.239
Phoenician city of Byblos, but while
there, he finds that the name of the

03:23:03.239 --> 03:23:07.239
pharaoh no longer holds the kind of
sway it used to.

03:23:07.239 --> 03:23:15.120
Wenamun is robbed on his journey and
appeals to the ruler of Byblos for help.

03:23:15.120 --> 03:23:20.040
That morning when I had risen, I
went to where the prince was and said to

03:23:20.040 --> 03:23:25.840
him,  I've been robbed in your harbor. Now,
you are the prince of this land. You are

03:23:25.840 --> 03:23:32.920
the one who controls it. Search for my
money! Indeed the money belongs to Amun-Ra,

03:23:32.920 --> 03:23:41.640
king of gods, lord of the lands.  He said
to me,  Are you serious? Are you joking?

03:23:41.640 --> 03:23:47.640
Indeed, I do not understand the demand
you make to me.

03:23:47.640 --> 03:23:52.600
To make matters worse, the king of Byblos
refuses to pay the tribute of cedar wood

03:23:52.600 --> 03:23:56.680
that the pharaoh demands.
Whether this story relates a

03:23:56.680 --> 03:24:02.080
true event or is simply a piece of
literature, historians aren't sure, but

03:24:02.080 --> 03:24:07.840
either way, it points to the much-reduced
state of Egypt's standing in the world,

03:24:07.840 --> 03:24:12.399
something that had clearly become

03:24:15.359 --> 03:24:19.680
common knowledge.
The 21st dynasty that ruled from the

03:24:19.680 --> 03:24:25.880
northern Nile Delta through much of the
8th century BC were even descended from

03:24:25.880 --> 03:24:30.960
Libyan invaders, peoples from along the
North African coast to the west.

03:24:30.960 --> 03:24:36.520
While the earliest of these Libyan
pharaohs adopted classical Egyptian

03:24:36.520 --> 03:24:42.880
names, by the 22nd and 23rd dynasties,
they reverted to giving their children

03:24:42.880 --> 03:24:48.680
more ethnically Libyan names, and even
wearing Libyan feathered headdresses to

03:24:48.680 --> 03:24:53.520
underline their identity.
Still, these Libyan kings were

03:24:53.520 --> 03:24:59.439
an unruly bunch who held close to their
old tribal loyalties, and were frequently

03:24:59.439 --> 03:25:05.080
distracted by warring amongst themselves
and their own lords and generals.

03:25:05.080 --> 03:25:11.479
Meanwhile, the high priests of Amun
continued to rule Southern Egypt from

03:25:11.479 --> 03:25:18.600
Thebes. But even further to the south, in
the lands of Nubia, another power was

03:25:18.600 --> 03:25:24.120
rising. This was the Nubian kingdom of

03:25:30.840 --> 03:25:37.239
Kush. As one of the two main African
kingdoms to the south of Egypt, Kush was

03:25:37.239 --> 03:25:43.160
located at the fourth cataract of the
Nile, around the region of Sudan

03:25:43.160 --> 03:25:48.160
today. For centuries now, this Nubian
kingdom had been crushed beneath the

03:25:48.160 --> 03:25:52.720
boot of Egypt.
Repeated expeditions up the Nile

03:25:52.720 --> 03:25:58.000
had seen Egyptian armies stamp out any
sign of a powerful rival appearing in

03:25:58.000 --> 03:26:01.840
East Africa. But now
with the New Kingdom of

03:26:01.840 --> 03:26:07.239
Egypt fractured and the Libyan Kings
ruling it in the north, fighting amongst

03:26:07.239 --> 03:26:13.279
themselves, the Kushites were free to
build their own power base.

03:26:15.239 --> 03:26:22.199
During Egypt's many attempts to
invade and hold on to the lands in Nubia,

03:26:22.199 --> 03:26:27.319
Egypt had left a number of powerful
fortresses to the Kushites. One of these

03:26:27.319 --> 03:26:31.399
had even become the capital of Kush, the
city of Napata,

03:26:31.399 --> 03:26:37.520
but the Egyptians had also left
behind something else; that is, their

03:26:37.520 --> 03:26:44.199
religion. The upper classes in Kush had
long adopted Egyptian gods and forms of

03:26:44.199 --> 03:26:50.080
worship. Kushite rulers even referred to
themselves as  the son of Amun .

03:26:50.080 --> 03:26:55.399
When Herodotus traveled down the
Nile in the following centuries, he

03:26:55.399 --> 03:27:00.160
described this region, which he knew as

03:27:00.760 --> 03:27:06.880
Ethiopia. Above Elephantine, the country
now begins to be inhabited by Ethiopians,

03:27:06.880 --> 03:27:10.680
and half the people of the island are
Ethiopians and half-Egyptians.

03:27:10.680 --> 03:27:17.359
Near to the island is a great lake,
on the shores of which dwell nomad

03:27:17.359 --> 03:27:22.920
Ethiopians. The people of the place
worship no other gods but Amun and

03:27:22.920 --> 03:27:30.199
Osiris. These they greatly honor, and they
have a place of divination sacred to Amun.

03:27:30.800 --> 03:27:35.560
While Egypt had stopped building
pyramids more than a thousand years

03:27:35.560 --> 03:27:40.160
earlier, Kushite kings had taken up the
building of pyramids of their own in

03:27:40.160 --> 03:27:45.439
classic Egyptian style.
In some ways, Kush had become more

03:27:45.439 --> 03:27:49.720
Egyptian than the Egyptians.
The kingdom was becoming

03:27:49.720 --> 03:27:55.199
wealthy, too, its economy boosted by the
Nubian gold mines it controlled, and

03:27:55.199 --> 03:28:00.359
trade with Sub-Saharan Africa.
This wealth soon led to a

03:28:00.359 --> 03:28:05.279
powerful army.
One king of Kush named Kashta would

03:28:05.279 --> 03:28:08.640
seize upon the opportunity that the
situation afforded.

03:28:08.640 --> 03:28:14.640
While the Libyan kings of Egypt
squabbled and fought among themselves,

03:28:14.640 --> 03:28:20.720
Kashta worked to gain influence over the
high priests of Thebes. Eventually, he

03:28:20.720 --> 03:28:27.000
had his own daughter appointed to the
powerful title of god's wife of Amun in

03:28:27.000 --> 03:28:31.800
the great temple of Thebes.
Once she was in that position,

03:28:31.800 --> 03:28:37.120
she moved to consolidate her power and
claimed Thebes and all Upper Egypt for

03:28:37.120 --> 03:28:42.560
her father's kingdom of Kush.
The Libyan kings in the Nile Delta,

03:28:42.560 --> 03:28:47.239
distracted by their civil wars, did
nothing to stop them.

03:28:47.239 --> 03:28:51.520
Upper Egypt was now ruled by Nubians.

03:28:51.960 --> 03:28:58.760
When the Kushite king Kashta died,
his son Piye inherited what was now the

03:28:58.760 --> 03:29:04.279
Kushite Empire.
Sometime around the 720s BC, King

03:29:04.279 --> 03:29:09.680
Piye marched his Nubian armies down the
Nile and conquered the fracture states

03:29:09.680 --> 03:29:14.399
of Lower Egypt.
Piye was clearly pragmatic in his

03:29:14.399 --> 03:29:19.680
approach, and allowed any local governors
to stay in their positions, so long as

03:29:19.680 --> 03:29:25.840
they swore allegiance to him. A victory
stelae that he carved records his

03:29:25.840 --> 03:29:31.279
victories, which he dedicates to the old
Egyptian gods.

03:29:32.040 --> 03:29:36.160
Hear what I have done in exceeding
the ancestors.

03:29:36.160 --> 03:29:41.640
I am the king, the
representation of god, who issued from

03:29:41.640 --> 03:29:47.279
the womb marked as ruler, who is feared
by those greater than he, whose father

03:29:47.279 --> 03:29:52.840
knew and whose mother perceived even in
the egg that he would be ruler, beloved

03:29:52.840 --> 03:29:58.160
of the gods, the son of Ra, beloved of Amun.

03:30:00.359 --> 03:30:08.120
His son Shebitku solidified these
conquests and united Egypt once more. For

03:30:08.120 --> 03:30:17.560
the next century, Egypt would be ruled by
the 25th dynasty, the Nubian pharaohs.

03:30:17.560 --> 03:30:22.680
Over the decades that followed, these
Nubian rulers showed an enthusiastic

03:30:22.680 --> 03:30:27.840
adoption of Egyptian culture.
They used the Egyptian language,

03:30:27.840 --> 03:30:32.279
gave each other Egyptian names, and
worshiped the Egyptian gods with

03:30:32.279 --> 03:30:36.520
apparent devotion.
They even embarked on an

03:30:36.520 --> 03:30:41.840
enthusiastic program of pyramid-building
in Nubia, the first that the region had

03:30:41.840 --> 03:30:47.880
seen in centuries, if nothing quite like
on the grand scale of the Old

03:30:47.880 --> 03:30:54.279
Kingdom. But this flourishing of Egyptian
culture would not last long. That's

03:30:54.279 --> 03:30:59.279
because to the north, a power had finally
risen that would eclipse the Egyptian

03:30:59.279 --> 03:31:05.960
Empire for good.
That was the empire of Assyria.

03:31:19.439 --> 03:31:25.199
As we saw in our thirteenth episode, Assyria
had arisen in the valley of the Tigris

03:31:25.199 --> 03:31:31.439
and Euphrates rivers in Mesopotamia, and
by the 7th century BC, was perhaps the

03:31:31.439 --> 03:31:37.239
most powerful empire on Earth.
They routinely amassed armies of

03:31:37.239 --> 03:31:43.319
more than 100,000 soldiers, and under the
reign of the paranoid king Esarhaddon,

03:31:43.319 --> 03:31:48.439
they were now pressing their power far
along along the Mediterranean coast, and

03:31:48.439 --> 03:31:53.560
soon they dreamed of bringing it to the
banks of the Nile itself.

03:31:53.560 --> 03:32:00.600
The Nubian pharaoh who would face
them was a man named Taharqa.

03:32:01.080 --> 03:32:07.399
Taharqa was the fifth king of the
Nubian 25th dynasty, and he was clearly

03:32:07.399 --> 03:32:12.720
proud of his heritage and his skin color.
He made sure that statues he

03:32:12.720 --> 03:32:18.840
commissioned were carved from hard, black
granite, polished smooth. He had come to

03:32:18.840 --> 03:32:23.560
Egypt as a young prince, and had been
chosen to rule after the death of the

03:32:23.560 --> 03:32:30.080
previous pharaoh, as he writes in one
inscription. I was brought from Nubia

03:32:30.080 --> 03:32:34.680
among the royal brothers that his
majesty had brought. As I was with him, he

03:32:34.680 --> 03:32:39.680
liked me more than all his brothers and
his children, so that he distinguished me.

03:32:39.680 --> 03:32:44.640
I won the heart of all the nobles and
was loved by all. It was only after the

03:32:44.640 --> 03:32:50.720
royal hawk had flown to heaven that I
received the crown in Memphis.

03:32:50.720 --> 03:32:56.120
Curiously, Taharqa was also a
believer in the benefits of long-

03:32:56.120 --> 03:33:01.359
distance running, and insisted that all
his soldiers engaged in nighttime

03:33:01.359 --> 03:33:05.880
marathon practices.
The king himself was on

03:33:05.880 --> 03:33:10.160
horseback to see his army running when
he exercised with them on the desert

03:33:10.160 --> 03:33:14.800
behind Memphis in the ninth hour of the
night. They reached the great lake at the

03:33:14.800 --> 03:33:20.479
hour of sunrise, and they returned to the
residence in the third hour of the day.

03:33:21.040 --> 03:33:26.640
This extreme stamina would serve
them well, and he would engage in

03:33:26.640 --> 03:33:32.080
successful assaults on Libyan positions
across the desert, and capture territory

03:33:32.080 --> 03:33:35.800
in Palestine.
Throughout his reign, Taharqa

03:33:35.800 --> 03:33:42.560
was lucky; a series of exceptional Nile
floods led to a period of abundant

03:33:42.560 --> 03:33:48.319
crops. Funds were clearly so forthcoming
that he donated large amounts of gold to

03:33:48.319 --> 03:33:53.600
the Temple of Amun, and restored several
religious centers, as one of his

03:33:53.600 --> 03:33:59.000
inscriptions boasts.
As His Majesty is the one who

03:33:59.000 --> 03:34:03.760
loves the god, he spends the day and lies
by night seeking what is useful to the

03:34:03.760 --> 03:34:08.960
gods, building their temples fallen into
decay, giving birth to their structures

03:34:08.960 --> 03:34:14.800
as in the primeval times, building
their storehouses, endowing altars,

03:34:14.800 --> 03:34:19.040
presenting them with offerings of fine
gold, silver, copper.

03:34:19.040 --> 03:34:24.640
Now, the heart of His Majesty is
satisfied with doing what is beneficent

03:34:24.640 --> 03:34:30.680
to them every day. This land is inundated
in his time as it was in the time of the

03:34:30.680 --> 03:34:40.279
lord of all, every man sleeping until dawn
and never saying,  Oh, I wish I had

03:34:41.880 --> 03:34:47.640
Egypt was now of a size and
stability that it hadn't seen since the

03:34:47.640 --> 03:34:53.279
collapse of the New Kingdom almost four
hundred years earlier. It must have looked like

03:34:53.279 --> 03:35:00.040
the dawn of a new era of prosperity, but
this luck was not to last.

03:35:00.040 --> 03:35:08.319
In the year 674 BC, in Taharqa's seven-
teenth year on the throne, news came of a

03:35:08.319 --> 03:35:14.720
terrifying army approaching from the
north. This horde belonged to King

03:35:14.720 --> 03:35:17.640
Esarhaddon of Assyria.

03:35:24.600 --> 03:35:30.600
Few foes had ever beaten the
Assyrians on the battlefield, and fear

03:35:30.600 --> 03:35:37.399
must have spread up and down the Nile.
But somehow, against the odds, Taharqa

03:35:37.399 --> 03:35:42.120
was able to repel this force.
The later Greek historian Herodotus

03:35:42.120 --> 03:35:47.680
records a fantastical story in which
the invading Assyrian army was

03:35:47.680 --> 03:35:52.199
attacked by a horde of nighttime pests.

03:35:52.439 --> 03:35:58.080
Where the road comes into Egypt,
there enemies came, and during the night

03:35:58.080 --> 03:36:02.880
were overrun by a horde of field mice
that gnawed quivers and bows and the

03:36:02.880 --> 03:36:07.800
handles of shields, with the result that
many were killed, fleeing unarmed the

03:36:07.800 --> 03:36:14.760
next day. For this reason, to this day, a
statue to the Egyptian king stands in a

03:36:14.760 --> 03:36:18.960
temple with a mouse in his hand.

03:36:18.960 --> 03:36:25.279
What exactly this account records
is difficult to tell. Perhaps it was an

03:36:25.279 --> 03:36:30.720
outbreak of plague among the Assyrian
army that forced them to return home.

03:36:30.720 --> 03:36:36.279
Perhaps it was even a daring nighttime
ambush by Taharqa's men, conditioned as they

03:36:36.279 --> 03:36:42.040
were to run long distances in the middle
of the night, strike, and then disappear

03:36:42.040 --> 03:36:45.840
into the darkness.
With their camp smashed and

03:36:45.840 --> 03:36:50.680
their army in disarray, the Assyrian army
would have been pursued by Egyptian

03:36:50.680 --> 03:36:57.479
chariots right back to their borders,
but we may never know. Perhaps

03:36:57.479 --> 03:37:02.399
unsurprisingly, the Assyrian sources make
no mention of what must have been a

03:37:02.399 --> 03:37:07.080
humiliating defeat.
The sting of this embarrassment

03:37:07.080 --> 03:37:12.319
was clearly sufficient that three years
later, King Esarhaddon amassed an even

03:37:12.319 --> 03:37:18.920
larger Assyrian army and marched back to
Egypt. This time, there was no standing

03:37:18.920 --> 03:37:21.359
in its way.

03:37:22.920 --> 03:37:29.680
The Assyrians flooded into the Nile
Delta, and Taharqa fled from Memphis and

03:37:29.680 --> 03:37:35.520
into the south. The Assyrian advance was
so speedy that the pharaoh was not able

03:37:35.520 --> 03:37:42.359
to evacuate his family when he left the
city. Esarhaddon s troops took Memphis, and

03:37:42.359 --> 03:37:48.680
the Assyrian king wrote the following
gloating inscription about his victory.

03:37:48.680 --> 03:37:54.640
I slew multitudes of his men and
I smote him five times with the point of

03:37:54.640 --> 03:38:01.199
my javelin, with wounds from which there
were no recovery. Memphis, his royal city,

03:38:01.199 --> 03:38:06.160
in half a day, with mines, tunnels,
assaults, I besieged, I captured, I

03:38:06.160 --> 03:38:12.479
destroyed, I devastated, I burned with
fire. His queen, his harem, his heir, and

03:38:12.479 --> 03:38:16.800
the rest of his sons and daughters, his
property and his goods, his horses, his

03:38:16.800 --> 03:38:24.120
cattle, his sheep, in countless numbers, I
carried off to Assyria. The root of Kush

03:38:24.120 --> 03:38:30.080
I tore up out of Egypt, and not one
therein escaped to submit to me. Over all

03:38:30.080 --> 03:38:36.720
of Egypt I appointed new kings, viceroys,
governors, commandants, overseers, and

03:38:36.720 --> 03:38:47.279
scribes. My royal tribute and tax, yearly
without ceasing, I imposed upon them.

03:38:47.279 --> 03:38:53.000
But if Esarhaddon had hoped to easily
absorb Egypt into his empire, he was

03:38:53.000 --> 03:38:59.239
mistaken. Just a year later, the Nubian
king Taharqa reappeared in the south,

03:38:59.239 --> 03:39:02.680
reinforced with troops from the kingdom
of Kush.

03:39:02.680 --> 03:39:08.399
Numerous governors that Esarhaddon
had installed immediately reverted their

03:39:08.399 --> 03:39:13.439
loyalties, and the whole Assyrian
conquest looked like it might be undone.

03:39:13.439 --> 03:39:20.520
Enraged, King Esarhaddon marched
back to Egypt to crush this rebel king,

03:39:20.520 --> 03:39:26.359
but his health failed on the journey, and
he died in the city of Harran without

03:39:26.359 --> 03:39:28.960
reaching Egypt.

03:39:29.040 --> 03:39:36.120
Esarhaddon s son who took the throne
was the Assyrian king Ashurbanipal.

03:39:36.120 --> 03:39:40.960
Virtually his first act as king was to
gather an army and march to the

03:39:40.960 --> 03:39:47.040
rebellious province of Egypt to finish
what his father had started.

03:39:47.040 --> 03:39:53.120
Ashurbanipal easily overwhelmed the now
weakened Egyptian forces, recaptured

03:39:53.120 --> 03:40:00.040
Memphis, and in 663 BC, returned again to
crush another round of rebellions.

03:40:00.040 --> 03:40:05.800
This time, he marched south up
the Nile River, and bore down on the

03:40:05.800 --> 03:40:10.960
ancient capital of Thebes.
By that time, the Nubian king

03:40:10.960 --> 03:40:17.359
Taharqa had died, and his nephew
Tantamani sat on the precarious throne of

03:40:17.359 --> 03:40:24.199
Egypt. Tantamani met the Assyrians in battle,
but he was defeated, and with him, the

03:40:24.199 --> 03:40:29.920
last of Egypt's hope would die.
The Assyrian army now rounded on the

03:40:29.920 --> 03:40:35.160
defenseless city of Thebes.
Ashurbanipal records what

03:40:35.160 --> 03:40:39.359
happened next on one carved cylinder.

03:40:41.520 --> 03:40:48.800
This city, the whole of it, I
conquered it with the help of Ashur and

03:40:48.800 --> 03:40:57.160
Ishtar. Silver, gold, precious stones, all
the wealth of the palace, rich cloth,

03:40:57.160 --> 03:41:03.439
precious linen, great horses, supervising
men and women, two obelisks of splendid

03:41:03.439 --> 03:41:10.960
electrum weighing 2,500 talents. The doors
of the temples I tore from their bases,

03:41:10.960 --> 03:41:15.920
and carried them off to
Assyria. With this weighty booty,

03:41:15.920 --> 03:41:21.000
I left Thebes.
Against Egypt and Kush, I have

03:41:21.000 --> 03:41:26.560
lifted my spear and shown my power.

03:41:28.239 --> 03:41:34.880
The Assyrian sack of Thebes was
the symbolic end of Egyptian power.

03:41:34.880 --> 03:41:40.359
Though Assyria would not hold
Egypt for long and would itself collapse

03:41:40.359 --> 03:41:46.840
within only about fifty years, Egyptian
esteem would never truly recover. A

03:41:46.840 --> 03:41:54.120
century later, Egypt was conquered by the
Persian Achaemenid Empire, and in 343 BC, it

03:41:54.120 --> 03:41:59.199
was conquered again by the Macedonian
forces of Alexander the Great.

03:41:59.199 --> 03:42:04.880
When Alexander's empire collapsed,
Egypt would be left in the hands of one

03:42:04.880 --> 03:42:10.960
of his ex-generals, Ptolemy Soter. For the
next three centuries, Egypt would be

03:42:10.960 --> 03:42:17.920
ruled by his Greek Ptolemaic dynasty, who
spoke Greek and mostly refused to learn

03:42:17.920 --> 03:42:23.319
the native Egyptian language.
These Ptolemies were still in power

03:42:23.319 --> 03:42:30.760
when the tide of Roman expansion swept
across North Africa and finally, over Egypt.

03:42:30.760 --> 03:42:38.080
The last independent ruler of Ptolemaic
Egypt had a name that in Greek meant

03:42:38.080 --> 03:42:45.840
glory of her father , from  kleos , meaning
glory , and  patra , meaning  father .

03:42:45.840 --> 03:42:49.279
Her name was Cleopatra.

03:42:49.960 --> 03:42:57.120
It's unclear if Cleopatra had
any Egyptian ancestry, as her mother is

03:42:57.120 --> 03:43:04.640
unknown, but she did at least make an
effort to learn Egyptian, as Plutarch

03:43:04.640 --> 03:43:09.239
remembers. It was a pleasure merely to
hear the sound of her voice, with which,

03:43:09.239 --> 03:43:14.600
like an instrument of many strings, she
could pass from one language to another,

03:43:14.600 --> 03:43:19.279
so that there were few of the barbarian
nations that she answered by an

03:43:19.279 --> 03:43:24.279
interpreter; to most of them she spoke
herself, as to the Ethiopians, Hebrews,

03:43:24.279 --> 03:43:29.239
Arabians, Syrians, Parthians, and many
others, whose language she had learned,

03:43:29.239 --> 03:43:32.840
which was all the more surprising
because most of the kings, her

03:43:32.840 --> 03:43:39.319
predecessors, scarcely gave themselves
the trouble to acquire the Egyptian

03:43:39.319 --> 03:43:46.000
tongue. When Rome finally invaded and
occupied Egypt, Cleopatra apparently

03:43:46.000 --> 03:43:51.359
committed suicide, most likely by
drinking poison or scratching herself

03:43:51.359 --> 03:43:57.760
with a needle dipped in toxin. The more
florid and famous rendition of her using

03:43:57.760 --> 03:44:03.640
a venomous snake to kill herself was
suggested by some ancient writers, and

03:44:03.640 --> 03:44:08.920
whether true or not, has proved
irresistible to generations of poets,

03:44:08.920 --> 03:44:15.199
including, most famously, William
Shakespeare. With her death in August of

03:44:15.199 --> 03:44:22.359
the year 30 BC, the final vestige of
independent Egyptian power died, too.

03:44:22.359 --> 03:44:29.159
On the day of her death, Cleopatra
stood at the height of more than three

03:44:29.159 --> 03:44:35.960
thousand years of Egyptian history. To her, the
Great Pyramid of Giza was now more than

03:44:35.960 --> 03:44:42.399
2,500 years old, meaning that Cleopatra
lived closer to our time than she did to

03:44:42.399 --> 03:44:48.640
the building of the Great Pyramid, by
more than five hundred years.

03:45:00.439 --> 03:45:06.439
As Egypt came under ever more
foreign influence, its ancient culture

03:45:06.439 --> 03:45:10.800
gradually underwent a
transformation. Over the following

03:45:10.800 --> 03:45:15.720
centuries, as the Greek alphabet became
more prominent, the knowledge of how to

03:45:15.720 --> 03:45:23.560
read hieroglyphics was slowly lost, as
one medieval Arab visitor records.

03:45:23.560 --> 03:45:27.840
I asked why the inscriptions
which cover the pyramids of the temples

03:45:27.840 --> 03:45:31.199
were indecipherable.
He answered,  Since the

03:45:31.199 --> 03:45:35.159
learned men and those who used this
writing have disappeared and Egypt has

03:45:35.159 --> 03:45:39.880
been occupied by a succession of foreign
peoples, the Greek alphabet and writing

03:45:39.880 --> 03:45:44.439
have prevailed, and thus, they lost the
understanding of the writing of their

03:45:44.439 --> 03:45:49.359
ancestors. 

03:45:49.359 --> 03:45:55.960
The last known hieroglyphic inscription
was written in the year 394 AD, at the

03:45:55.960 --> 03:46:01.880
Temple of Philae, built on an island near
the cataract of the Nile at Aswan.

03:46:01.880 --> 03:46:07.760
By then, the now-Christianized
Roman Empire had banned the worship of

03:46:07.760 --> 03:46:13.600
pagan gods in Egypt's temples, but this
religious site was just outside of

03:46:13.600 --> 03:46:19.680
Rome's borders, and so, worship of the
ancient gods continued here, in the last

03:46:19.680 --> 03:46:26.840
of Egypt's great temples.
Here, the names of Ra and Ptah,

03:46:26.840 --> 03:46:35.479
Anubis and Hathor, Amun and Bastet, Seth
and Horus, would still be spoken and sung,

03:46:35.479 --> 03:46:41.520
the incense still burned, the cats still
fed, the offerings still

03:46:41.520 --> 03:46:47.319
given, but this island temple was
increasing isolated, surrounded by the

03:46:47.319 --> 03:46:51.880
crashing waters of a fast-changing

03:46:52.080 --> 03:46:58.479
world. The last hieroglyphic inscription
records the mournful wish of one scribe

03:46:58.479 --> 03:47:04.920
named Nesmeterakhem, wishing that his
inscription would endure forever, just

03:47:04.920 --> 03:47:09.359
like the carvings of his long-dead ancestors.

03:47:09.680 --> 03:47:16.479
Before Mandulis,
son of Horus, by the hand of

03:47:16.479 --> 03:47:24.600
Nesmeterakhem, son of Nesmeter, the
Second Priest of Isis, for all time and

03:47:24.600 --> 03:47:33.040
eternity. Words spoken by Mandulis, lord
of the Abaton, great god.

03:47:33.040 --> 03:47:40.000
As the last-ever inscription of its
kind, in some ways he got his wish, but

03:47:40.000 --> 03:47:44.600
it's likely that by the time he chipped
this message into the temple wall, few

03:47:44.600 --> 03:47:50.319
people alive would know how to
read it. As far as we know, the art of the

03:47:50.319 --> 03:47:57.319
hieroglyph died with him.
The temple was finally closed at

03:47:57.319 --> 03:48:03.880
some point in the 530s by the Byzantine
emperor Justinian, and it was converted

03:48:03.880 --> 03:48:10.479
into a Christian church to Saint
Steven. The age of Ancient Egypt had well

03:48:10.479 --> 03:48:16.760
and truly come to an end.

03:48:21.880 --> 03:48:29.960
Some 1,400 years later, in the year
1818, the Romantic poet Percy Bysshe Shelley

03:48:29.960 --> 03:48:36.319
would enter into a friendly competition
with his friend, the poet Horace Smith.

03:48:36.319 --> 03:48:41.239
They had both read in a London newspaper
about the coming arrival in the British

03:48:41.239 --> 03:48:47.960
Museum of a remarkable fragment of a
statue, brought by ship from the Ramesseum

03:48:47.960 --> 03:48:55.159
mortuary temple in Thebes in Upper
Egypt. It was the head and torso of a

03:48:55.159 --> 03:49:02.159
statue of Egypt's greatest pharaoh, the
hero of the battle of Kadesh, Ramesses II.

03:49:02.159 --> 03:49:08.520
The statue was one of a pair that had
stood at the doorway of his temple.

03:49:08.520 --> 03:49:14.279
European colonial powers had long
been hungering after that fragment of

03:49:14.279 --> 03:49:18.080
statue. Napoleon Bonaparte
had even tried to remove it

03:49:18.080 --> 03:49:24.120
during his time in Egypt in
1798, but he found its bulk of black

03:49:24.120 --> 03:49:29.399
diorite too heavy to shift.
Now, with wooden rollers and

03:49:29.399 --> 03:49:34.319
hundreds of workmen pulling ropes, the
British team hauled the statue to the

03:49:34.319 --> 03:49:39.640
banks of the Nile, where it was
transported down the river and on to

03:49:39.640 --> 03:49:45.840
London. After reading about this statue,
Smith and Shelly agreed to wager. They

03:49:45.840 --> 03:49:50.560
would each write a poem inspired by it,
and they would base their work on an

03:49:50.560 --> 03:49:55.880
extract from the writings of the Greek
historian Diodorus of Sicily, who had

03:49:55.880 --> 03:50:03.239
once visited Ramesses II's temple in
Thebes. Unfortunately for Horace Smith,

03:50:03.239 --> 03:50:09.359
history has decisively concluded their
competition, as his poem is little

03:50:09.359 --> 03:50:15.479
remembered, but Shelley's poem has become a
classic, one of the greatest and most

03:50:15.479 --> 03:50:22.479
well-known sonnets in the English
language. Titled Ozymandias, it is a poem

03:50:22.479 --> 03:50:28.279
that has come to stand as an emblem of
the vain, glorious pride of rulers, the

03:50:28.279 --> 03:50:34.960
inevitable downfall of tyrants, the awe-
inspiring power of time, and the

03:50:34.960 --> 03:50:38.720
transience of all things.

03:50:40.359 --> 03:50:46.720
I met a traveler from an antique
land who said,  Two vast and

03:50:46.720 --> 03:50:53.760
trunkless legs of stone stand in the
desert; near them, on the sand, half-sunk, a

03:50:53.760 --> 03:50:59.960
shattered visage lies, whose frown and
wrinkled lip and sneer of cold command

03:50:59.960 --> 03:51:05.439
tell that its sculptor well those
passions read which yet survive, stamped

03:51:05.439 --> 03:51:11.600
on those lifeless things, the hand that
mocked them and the heart that fed; and

03:51:11.600 --> 03:51:20.520
on the pedestal these words appear:  My
name is Ozymandias, king of kings; look on

03:51:20.520 --> 03:51:28.359
my works, ye Mighty, and despair!
Nothing beside remains. Round the

03:51:28.359 --> 03:51:34.680
decay of that colossal wreck, boundless
and bare, the lone and level sands

03:51:34.680 --> 03:51:38.080
stretch far away.

03:51:42.279 --> 03:51:49.120
On the tomb wall of a Pharaoh Intef
of the Middle Kingdom is a piece of

03:51:49.120 --> 03:51:55.279
literature known as the Harper s Song,
written in Egyptian hieroglyphics.

03:51:55.279 --> 03:52:02.319
It was a song designed to
be sung at funerals, and is more than

03:52:02.319 --> 03:52:07.560
4,200 years old.
At the time of writing his poem Ozymandias,

03:52:07.560 --> 03:52:12.520
Percy Bysshe Shelley could not have
known about this piece of ancient

03:52:12.520 --> 03:52:17.680
literature, since hieroglyphics would not
be conclusively deciphered for several

03:52:17.680 --> 03:52:24.040
more years. But across the gulf of four
millennia, he and the unknown author of

03:52:24.040 --> 03:52:30.680
this song both describe a human emotion
that is all too familiar, the deep sense

03:52:30.680 --> 03:52:36.800
of awe and melancholy we feel when we
look at ruined places, at the crumbling

03:52:36.800 --> 03:52:43.439
palaces of long-fallen emperors, at the
tombs of kings whose age has passed into

03:52:43.439 --> 03:52:48.040
dust. As you listen,
imagine the vast gulf of

03:52:48.040 --> 03:52:55.080
time that separates our world from
theirs. Imagine the sadness of watching

03:52:55.080 --> 03:53:00.680
your language forgotten and your cities
crumbled. Imagine the tombs of ancient

03:53:00.680 --> 03:53:07.600
kings lying opened and robbed, the fallen
pillars of emptied temples half-buried

03:53:07.600 --> 03:53:14.880
in the sand, which shifts and rolls over
the stones, as the great disc of the sun

03:53:14.880 --> 03:53:21.920
sets red and blazing for a final time on
the empire of Egypt.

03:53:32.880 --> 03:53:39.520
One generation passes; another
stays behind. Such has it been since the

03:53:39.520 --> 03:53:45.359
men of ancient times. The gods of long
ago rest in their pyramids, and yet,

03:53:45.359 --> 03:53:49.479
the great and blessed likewise
lie buried in their tombs.

03:53:49.479 --> 03:53:54.720
Yet those who built great mansions,
their places are no more.

03:53:54.720 --> 03:54:00.760
What has become of them all?
I have heard their words retold time

03:54:00.760 --> 03:54:04.960
and again, but where
are their dwellings now?

03:54:04.960 --> 03:54:10.720
Their walls are in ruins and their
places are no more, like something that

03:54:10.720 --> 03:54:15.159
has never been.
There is no return for them

03:54:15.159 --> 03:54:20.800
to explain their present state of being,
to say how it is with them, to gentle our

03:54:20.800 --> 03:54:25.760
hearts until we make our journey to the
place where they have gone.

03:54:25.760 --> 03:54:31.880
So follow your heart and your
happiness; conduct your affairs on Earth

03:54:31.880 --> 03:54:35.800
as your heart dictates,
for that day of mourning will

03:54:35.800 --> 03:54:42.600
surely come for you, so spend your days
joyfully and do not grow weary of

03:54:42.600 --> 03:54:51.359
living. No man takes his things with him,
and none who go can ever come back

03:54:52.399 --> 03:54:56.880
again.

03:55:04.239 --> 03:55:10.399
Thank you once again for listening
to the Fall of Civilizations Podcast. I'd

03:55:10.399 --> 03:55:16.319
like to thank my voice actors for this
